<FIRST>r i PM-BRF--Thatcher     04-19 0218</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Thatcher,0224</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thatcher Says She Survived Assassination Attempt By Chance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher was quoted today
as saying an aide who demanded a policy decision at 2 a.m. probably
saved her life in 1984 when the IRA blew up the hotel where she was
staying.
   She was quoted as saying in an interview with Readers Digest
that she was about to go bed after working in her hotel suite until
2:45 a.m. when her private secretary, Robin Butler, insisted upon a
decision.
   She had been up polishing her keynote address to her
Conservative Party's annual conference.
   ``He thrust a set of papers into my hand and while I was reading
them, the explosion went off,'' Mrs. Thatcher was quoted as saying.
   ``Had I not been reviewing those papers, I would have gone
straight into the bathroom. Another person whose bathroom was a few
floors above mine had done exactly that and was virtually blown to
bits.''
   The Oct. 12, 1984, explosion wrecked the hotel where Mrs.
Thatcher and most of her Cabinet were staying for the convention in
Brighton, killing five people and injuring 30.
   The Irish Republican Army is fighting to push the British out of
Northern Ireland, join it with the Republic of Ireland and set up
an all-Ireland socialist state.
</TEXT>
