<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--BridgeCollapse     04-19 0123</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Bridge Collapse,0127</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fed Agency Backs Tennessee Bridge Inspection Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal agency defended the state's
bridge inspection program, despite the collapse of two Tennessee
bridges in two weeks.
   ``They have a good program with solid routine,'' Ira Deggs,
assistant director of the Federal Highway Administration's state
office, said Tuesday.
   Eight persons died in the collapse of a U.S. 51 bridge over the
Hatchie River near Memphis on April 1. A teen-ager was killed when
a railroad bridge collapsed near Oliver Springs in east Tennessee
on Saturday.
   An inspector four years ago urged repairs to the east Tennessee
bridge, but authorities never recommended that it be closed.
   An inspection of the U.S. 51 bridge also warned of problems.
</TEXT>
