<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-89 0232EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-PreciousWoodcarving     04-19 0347</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Precious Woodcarving,0355</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woodcarver Is Famous At Last</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A little-known early 16th-century German sculptor,
Niclaus Weckmann the Elder, became a major figure in art history
when a woodcarving of his sold at auction for $423,000, Christie's
said.
   ``The price was a very high one for such a work,'' said Mark
Wrey, a spokesman for the auction house, after the sale Tuesday of
the Weckmann's Adoration of the Magi.
   The seller was described only as a continental nobleman.
   The buyer was anonymous but Charles Avery, the firm's head of
sculpture, said the work ``may be going back to south Germany,
which would be appropriate as that was Weckmann's homeland.''
   The limewood carving, more than five feet tall and four feet
wide, was once part of an altarpiece and depicts the wise men
presenting their gifts to the infant Jesus.
   ``It had been in the private chapel of a noble family in Styria
(Austria) for 100 years or so and probably no one else saw it,''
Avery said. ``If we knew where it had been for the 300 years before
that it would been even more costly as a complete antique
provenance adds to value,'' he said.
   Weckmann lived from about 1460 to 1520. His works were
attributed to other artists until 1968, when he was identified as
one of the greatest sculptors working in the town of Ulm around
1500.
   Avery said he was so impressed by the unsigned carving when it
arrived for auction that he asked for a study of it from Alfred
Schaedler, chief curator of sculpture at the National Bavarian
Museum in Munich.
   ``Schaedler is the expert on Weckmann and he attibuted it to him
on grounds of style and type. It is one of the largest and most
splendid pieces of Gothic German wood sculpture to be auctioned in
recent times,'' Avery added.
   As nothing identified as Weckmann's work had been auctioned
before, Christie's said they were uncertain how to estimate the
carving's price, at first setting it at $172,000 and then thinking
it might go up to $344,000.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
