<DOCNO> AP890419-0020 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-89 0116EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-PapLab     04-19 0356</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pap Lab,0366</SECOND>
<HEAD>Closed Lab told To Pay For Millions Of New Pap Tests</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State health officials ordered a laboratory
to offer to pay for repeat Pap smear tests for more than 3 million
women diagnosed as cancer-free after learning the lab's error rate
was greater than 20 percent.
   Central Pathology Services Medical Group of Tarzana, which has
performed 3.3 million Pap smears over the past five years, was
ordered closed last week after a state audit showed an error rate
of 21.2 percent among 1,103 tests selected at random.
   ``It was a sloppy operation,'' said Dr. Kenneth Kizer, state
health services director. ``It was totally unacceptable that they
had such a high error rate.''
   The lab, which also worked under the name Central Diagnostic
Laboratory, processed nearly 700,000 smears last year, more than
half of all of the tests in Southern California.
   Pap smears from California, Arizona, Chicago and Philadelphia
were processed at the company's Tarzana area lab.
   In its order delivered to the lab Monday, the health department
said all women in California and other states who had received
reports indicating no abnormalities from either Central Pathology
or Central Diagnostic within the last five years needed to be
offered the opportunity for a repeat Pap smear.
   The lab, which closed Monday, was given 30 days to contact the
women and recommend they see their doctors about retaking the tests
elsewhere.
   Central Pathology said in a statement it was ``a 27-year-old
facility with a perfect inspection record to this point'' and that
it had recently instituted what it called ``the most stringent
quality-control standards in the nation.''
   The Pap smear, which costs about $25, is a routine test used to
detect cervical cancer and other medical abnormalities.
   The industry average for misdiagnosing Pap smears is about 5
percent, but some pathologists said top labs make even fewer
mistakes.
   Kizer said state officials plan to inspect 10 other Pap smear
laboratories within the next six weeks. He did not identify them.
   ``We need to get an idea of the other labs' error rates and set
some kind of standard,'' Kizer said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
