<FIRST>r w PM-MinimumWage     04-19 0485</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Minimum Wage,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Democrats Say Bush Has to Give First On Minimum Wage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrats leading the effort to raise the
minimum wage say they are willing to make concessions but only if
President Bush does the same.
   ``Nothing is concrete,'' Rep. Austin Murphy, D-Pa., said
Tuesday. ``Just about every provision in this is negotiable.''
   But Murphy and other lawmakers on a conference committee to
resolve differences between House- and Senate-passed minimum wage
bills said they will not offer any concessions unless Bush drops
his repeated veto threats and first offers a compromise of his own.
   The prospects for such a development appear slim. Knowing that,
the Democrats intensified their efforts to portray Bush as turning
his back on the working poor, a pitch that itself is part of an
effort by the Democrats to make political hay of any Bush veto of
minimum wage legislation.
   ``We will send you this bill and we will send you another bill,
and we will make you wish that you didn't have the power to veto,''
said Murphy. ``We're asking for some leadership, not the threat of
a veto.''
   Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., questioned the motives of
Bush's refusal to negotiate by pointing to a number of recent
agreements between Congress and the White House on issues ranging
from Contra aid to the savings and loan crisis.
   ``Why not on the minimum wage?'' Kennedy said. ``To millions of
low-income Americans the answer must seem obvious: the
administration doesn't care enough about them to listen to their
position. Kinder and gentler does not mean you.''
   Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell compared Bush's stance on
the minimum wage with his proposal to expand capital gains tax
breaks that would be enjoyed predominantly by wealthy Americans.
   ``The president ought to have as much concern for the poor as he
does for the rich,'' Mitchell said.
   The conferees said they hope to have a final product in about
two weeks and indicated it would be stripped of a number of Senate
amendments unrelated to the minimum wage, including one that would
raise the outside earnings limit for Social Security recipients.
   Bush has repeatedly said the only minimum wage bill he will
accept is his own, an offer to raise the minimum from its current
level of $3.35 an hour to $4.25 by January 1992, provided employers
can pay all new workers less than the minimum for up to six months.
   Both the House and Senate measures would raise the minimum wage
to $4.55 by October 1991 and allow a ``sub-minimum'' to be paid to
some newly hired workers for just two months.
   Murphy said that if no compromise is reached, he is considering
a number of other approaches to raising the minimum wage, including
a simple one-year increase of the base wage instead of the
incremental boosts contained in the current measures.
</TEXT>
