<FIRST>r w PM-Laurel     04-19 0588</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Laurel,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Philippine Vice President Says Marcos Should Be Allowed to Die at
Home</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Philippine Vice President Salvador Laurel, who
met recently with Ferdinand Marcos at his sickbed, says the exiled
former president should be allowed to leave Hawaii and return home
to die.
   ``I think he should be allowed to return _ not only to die in
his own country, but to face whatever charges will be filed against
him. Let the Philippine people decide the case,'' Laurel said
Tuesday in an interview.
   The vice president, who has broken politically with President
Corazon Aquino, was meeting this week with several members of
Congress during a private visit to the United States. He was
scheduled to deliver an address today before the Center for
Democracy, a private research group.
   Laurel's position is in direct opposition to Mrs. Aquino's.
   The mere idea that the former dictator might return to the
homeland he ruled for 20 years is an extremely sensitive national
question. Mrs. Aquino has repeatedly rejected Marcos' requests,
citing security concerns.
   But the vice president dismissed the idea that Marcos' return to
his homeland _ dead or alive _ would spark unrest.
   ``I don't buy that. I think they are overrating Marcos,'' Laurel
said. ``I don't think his return would cause that kind of
destabilization.''
   The vice president's trip to Marcos' bedside in February was the
subject of some speculation in the Philippines that he was looking
for support from Marcos supporters as he began to work with an
opposition party in advance of the 1992 elections.
   As a former opponent of the Marcos regime, Laurel said he was
surprised to receive the invitation from Imelda Marcos to go to
Hawaii. He said he returned to the Philippines with a message for
Mrs. Aquino from the dying former president, but Mrs. Aquino
refused to see him.
   Laurel said his interest was ``national reconciliation.'' He
said Marcos' message, which he would not reveal, did not involve a
``deal'' but ``was something that might straighten out things.''
   Marcos has been hospitalized in Honolulu since Jan. 16,
suffering from bronchial asthma and pneumonia. In December, he was
hospitalized twice with congestive heart failure.
   Marcos was ousted in 1986 in a popular uprising that later swept
Mrs. Aquino and her running mate, Laurel, into office.
   In September 1987, Laurel resigned as foreign secretary, citing
widespread differences with Mrs. Aquino on the 20-year battle
against a communist insurgency and other issues such as the
country's economic development.
   The Marcoses are under indictment in New York on racketeering
charges. The couple would need permission from the U.S. attorney
general and the U.S. District Court in New York to leave the United
States.
   The indictment accuses the ousted Philippines dictator and his
wife of stealing more than $100 million from the Philippine
treasury to buy real estate and expensive art objects in New York.
   Overall, the Philippines says the couple took $3.5 billion in
cash and property.
   Mrs. Marcos has pleaded innocent to the charges contained in the
U.S. indictment. Marcos has said he is too ill to appear in New
York for legal proceedings.
   Laurel argued that as a man who is charged with looting the
Philippines, Marcos should face charges there first.
   ``The Philippines has a prior claim over the United States. ...
It may be that the U.S. has a valid case against him ... but
offenses committed against the Filipino people should be decided by
the Philippine courts,'' Laurel said.
</TEXT>
