<FIRST>r w PM-EarthDay     04-19 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Earth Day,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Earth Day 1990' Organizers Call for Worldwide Observance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Environmentalists are gearing up for an
international ``Earth Day 1990'' that they hope will dwarf the
original of 20 years ago, an event that helped make U.S. laws more
sensitive to environmental concerns.
   ``The purpose of Earth Day in 1970 was to organize a nationwide
grassroots demonstration of public concern for the environment,''
former Sen. Gaylord Nelson, who founded the event, said Tuesday.
``Though much has been achieved in many areas in the past 20 years,
we continue to lose ground in the fight to improve our
environment.''
   Denis Hayes, coordinator of the first Earth Day, and Sen. John
Kerry, D-Mass. and Rep. Bill Green, R-N.Y, who were local Earth Day
activists 20 years ago, joined Nelson at a news conference to
announce plans for the April 22, 1990, event.
   Nelson, who now is counselor to the Wilderness Society, called
on President Bush to lead other heads of state into a ``battle to
save the Earth.''
   Hayes said the observance is meant to start a decade of
environmental concern showing that countries throughout the world
have a ``shared set of values and commitment to save the planet.''
   He said that organizers have talked to members of the White
House staff, but have not yet approached Bush directly.
   Nelson said no president campaigns against environmental
policies, but none since Theodore Roosevelt has understood what
needs to be done. Leaders of other nations have been similarly
shortsighted, he said.
   ``In the leading industrial nations Prime Minister Thatcher and
President Mitterand have joined President Bush in paying lip
service to global environmental problems,'' Nelson said. ``None has
yet said anything important about their plans for resolving these
problems or made any serious proposals for addressing them.''
   Green said the United States has adopted laws to begin cleanup,
but isn't keeping up with the problems.
   ``Of 1,200 major hazardous waste sites, just 34 have been
cleaned up,'' he said. ``And while Congress in 1980 allocated $1.6
billion to help clean up such sites, estimates of the federal share
now range up to $300 billion.''
</TEXT>
