<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Punitive     04-19 0446</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Punitive,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Asked to Rule on High Liability Awards</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's second-largest waste hauler is
asking the Supreme Court to reverse a $6 million jury verdict
against it as an example of ``bloated, irrational and excessive
awards'' in liability lawsuits.
   In a case that businesses say could have an enormous impact on
their insurance costs and the overall competitiveness of American
industry, Browning-Ferris Industries Inc. argued Tuesday against
what it called huge punitive damage awards.
   BFI attorney Andrew L. Frey told the high court that enormous
punitive damage awards violate the Constitution's Eighth Amendment
prohibition against excessive fines, as well as due process rights
and common law.
   The case centers on a lawsuit brought by Kelco Disposal Inc. of
Burlington, Vt., againt Houston-based BFI, accusing the Texas
company of predatory pricing to drive Kelco out of business.
   A Vermont jury awarded Kelco $51,146 in compensatory damages, in
contrast to the much larger punitive total.
   Kelco lawyer H. Bartow Farr III argued the Eighth Amendment's
prohibition against excessive fines does not apply to punitive
damages ``awarded in a private state court tort action,'' and
applying it would be ``intrusive second-guessing'' of jury verdicts.
   Farr said state laws provide for punitive-damage awards to be
reviewed by the courts, and such awards are ``routinely reduced.''
   ``The courts below upheld this award under traditional common
law standards,'' Farr said. ``Damages are simply not fines.''
   Dozens of ``friend-of-the-court'' briefs were filed as
manufacturers, publishers, insurers, broadcasters, pharmacists, the
Red Cross, defense attorneys and U.S. Chamber of Commerce officials
all urged the justices to place some limits on punitive damages.
   They say unfettered jury decisions allowing huge penalty awards
are driving up insurance rates and discouraging the marketing of
products from medical equipment to football helmets.
   Trial attorneys and consumer groups, who argue punitive damages
are the best protection against bad business practices, have sided
with Kelco, which survived BFI's price cutting and in 1985 forced
the larger company out of town.
   Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and Justice Sandra Day
O'Connor questioned whether ruling for BFI would force the court to
review all future punitive-damage awards that someone considered
excessive.
   Frey said that applying the excessive-fines provision in such
civil cases would sharply curb a growing trend toward excessive
awards that has prompted ``tort reform'' by state legislatures.
   Justice Antonin Scalia insisted Frey was seeking a national
standard that all 50 states would have to follow, rather than
allowing each state to set its own punitive-damage limits.
   The court is expected to announce its decision by July.
   The case is Browning-Ferris Industries of Vermont Inc. vs. Kelco
Disposal Inc., 88-556.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890419-0038 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-89 0403EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Budget     04-19 0658</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Budget,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Committee Passes $4.7 Billion Measure, Bush Threatens Veto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 1990 budget plan reflecting the deal reached
between the White House and Congress is working its way through the
Senate Budget Committee, but a separate $4.7 billion spending bill
for this year is ruffling Republican feathers.
   The Senate Budget Committee began debating the fiscal 1990
budget resolution on Tuesday and hoped to finish its work today.
   On Tuesday, it voted 19-4 to reject an amendment by Sen. J.
Bennett Johnston, D-La., to institute deep across-the-board
spending cuts in place of the compromise reached last week.
   Johnston, complaining that the bipartisan pact ``does not cut
the budget at all,'' said his plan would sent a message ``to start
all over again, to do a real job of budgeting.''
   Joining Johnston was Sen. J. James Exon, D-Neb., who said, ``If
anyone thinks Rosemary's Baby was ugly, I suggest taking a close
look at this newly hatched baby.''
   Administration officials and congressional leaders ended a month
of negotiations last Friday by announcing a deal for $1.2 trillion
budget that claims a deficit of $99.4 billion.
   The budget committee is charged with producing a congressional
resolution that will guide later spending and tax bills for fiscal
1990, which begins Oct. 1. Chairman Jim Sasser, D-Tenn., said he
would oppose any plan that did not follow the White House pact.
   But trouble was brewing across Capitol Hill on a so-called dire
emergency spending bill for this year.
   The House Appropriations Committee approved a $4.7 billion
supplemental spending bill for fiscal 1989, a measure that if
approved could put Congress on a collision course with President
Bush.
   On a unanimous voice vote, the House appropriations panel sent
the wide-ranging spending bill to the House floor.
   But first, in a party-line 28-18 vote, the committee's majority
Democrats rejected a Republican effort that would have shaved about
$1.5 billion in new spending from the measure.
   ``The worst thing we could do here is report a bill perceived to
be fiscally irresponsible and a budget buster,'' said Rep. Silvio
Conte, R-Mass., ranking Republican on the appropriations panel.
   The Bush administration renewed its threat to veto the so-called
``dire emergency'' bill, stating in a letter that the president
favored the less expensive GOP alternative.
   ``In my view, fiscal responsibility requires that we go no
further,'' administration budget director Richard Darman wrote to
Conte.
   Last month, Bush had asked Congress to approve a $2.2 billion
version of the measure. The committee more than doubled its size.
   As passed by the committee, the bill provides $1.2 billion for
veterans programs, $892 million for the Guaranteed Student Loan
program for college students, $822 million for drug efforts, $600
million to fight last summer's forest fires, $423 million for
foster care and adoption programs, and $100 million to pay for the
costs of immigration increases from the Soviet Union, Southeast
Asia and Africa.
   The measure also contains $127 million for workers whose jobs
are lost due to foreign competition; $71 million for the Federal
Aviation Administration to hire more air traffic controllers,
inspectors and security officers; and $35 million to prosecute
fraud cases involving the financially reeling savings and loan
industry.
   Amendments Tuesday added $153 million for programs for the
homeless; $88 million to help subsidize public housing projects;
and $200,000 to provide aid to Poland for upcoming elections.
   One provision would prohibit the Interior Department from
spending money to make the Chicago home of mobster Al Capone a
historic site.
   With the 1989 deficit already projected at more than $163
billion, the spending measure would push the government's shortfall
$1.3 billion deeper, the White House's Office of Management and
Budget said. Under the Gramm-Rudman deficit reduction law, this
year's deficit was not supposed to exceed $146 billion.
   Because the deficit figures reflect overall outlays, the bill's
impact on the deficit is different from the spending authorized in
the bill.
</TEXT>
