<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     04-19 0700</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawmaker Pushes For Fat and Cholesterol Labeling To Fight Heart Disease</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Joseph Moakley, D-Mass., has proposed
requiring that food products include easily understood details of
fat and cholesterol content to help consumers reduce their chances
of heart disease.
   ``You could starve to death in the supermarket just reading the
labels,'' complained the 61-year-old lawmaker.
   Under the measure, the Food and Drug Administration would
require food manufacturers to list the different types of fat _
saturated, polyunsaturated and monounsaturated _ and their amounts.
Federal regulations now require food producers to list only the
total fat content.
   The ninth-term Boston Democrat said the current labeling
provision ``is particularly disturbing since some fats increase
blood cholesterol and other types of fat actually lower one's
cholesterol.''
   The bill also would require food manufacturers to specify
amounts of dietary cholesterol, which also has been linked to heart
disease. There currently is no cholesterol labeling requirement.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>Tax Court Says Wedding Expenses Non-Deductible</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tax Court has turned thumbs down on a
Minnesota undertaker who took a business tax deduction for $11,000
of expenses of wedding receptions for two daughters.
   William L. McReavy of Minneapolis and his wife, Kathleen,
claimed the receptions as an advertising-entertainment expense,
contending that 82 percent of the people invited were clients or
referral sources for his Washburn-McReavy Funeral Chapels, Inc.
   ``The personal element of the expenses for the McReavys'
daughters' weddings was so prominent that we believe that even a
person not versed in the tax law would know that the corporation
could not deduct them,'' the court held on Tuesday.
   The court was so unimpressed by the argument that it allowed the
Internal Revenue Service to add a negligence penalty to the
McReavys' bill.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>Repeal of Program Introduced</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of House Republicans are hoping to
repeal parts of the new catastrophic health expansion of Medicare _
mainly the income tax surcharge imposed on the well-to-do elderly
to help finance the program.
   The proposal, unveiled at a news conference Tuesday, would keep
most major benefits of the program, but revamp a prescription drug
benefit and make its more generous provisions apply only to
low-income Medicare beneficiaries not poor enough to qualify for
Medicaid.
   The law passed by overwhelming margins in both the House and
Senate last year _ despite vocal opposition from opponents of the
surcharge _ and was signed into law by then-President Reagan with
great fanfare.
   The surcharge has provoked a barrage of letters to lawmakers
even though it does not apply to 60 percent of all 32 million
Medicare beneficiaries who do not have enough income to pay federal
taxes.
   Of the 40 percent subject to the surcharge, only those couples
with annual incomes of $100,000 or so would be subject to the
maximum surcharge of $800 a person.
   Rep. Michael Bilirakis, D-Fla., a lead sponsor of the
legislation, acknowledged that many of his own constituents who
have complained mistakenly believe they will be subject to an
income tax surcharge.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>Administration Wants to Keep Control of Visits by Communists</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration says it wants to
preserve the right to control entry to the United States of anyone
who ever was a Communist.
   The stance was spelled out in a letter to Rep. Barney Frank,
D-Mass, who has led a six-year fight to change the current law and
limit the power of the government to keep out visitors from abroad.
   The National Education Association, a private group, distributed
a letter to Congress in support of Frank's bill. It said the
present law has been used to keep out Primo Levi, the Italian
chemist and novelist, Colombian novelist Gabriel Garcia Marquez and
Mexican novelist Carlos Fuentes.
   The letter from the administration, signed in the name of Joe D.
Whitley, acting associate attorney general, said, ``Unless our
reservations are addressed, the department cannot support the
enactment of this proposed legislation.''
   He asked for changes to Frank's bill that would permit the
attorney general to set conditions for the visit to the United
States of anyone who has ever belonged to a Communist party or to
one of its affiliates.
</TEXT>
