<FIRST>r i PM-Chile     04-19 0420</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chile,0436</SECOND>
<HEAD>Post-Strike Violence Leaves Two Dead, 138 Arrested, Blackouts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDUARDO GALLARDO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A general strike against the military
government turned violent as police battled demonstrators in
Santiago and other cities and about 50 bomb attacks blacked out
much of the capital.
   Police said they killed two ``extremists'' and arrested more
than 130 demonstrators on Tuesday before calm was restored at
midnight. Large areas of the capital and other cities had been left
without power for several hours.
   Demonstrators fought police in downtown Santiago during daylight
Tuesday and then at night in the slums that ring the city.
   The strike, called by the nation's largest union to protest the
incarceration of two labor leaders, failed to generate support from
workers but there were clashes between helmeted riot police and
demonstrators in Santiago and other cities.
   Police said six officers and a security agent were injured in
clashes but they did not report injuries among protesters.
Hospitals reported receiving ``numerous'' injuries.
   The Interior Ministry said 138 protesters were arrested
nationwide and that police resorted to using tear gas and water
cannon to scatter the mostly young demonstrators.
   At night, demonstrators blocked traffic at intersections in
Santiago's slums, erecting fire barricades. Local radio stations
said unidentified gunmen in speeding cars were seen shooting at
demonstrators manning the barricades.
   In the most serious incident, police said two ``extremists''
were killed in a clash with security forces when they were caught
planting a bomb near an electrical tower in northern Santiago.
   The strike was called by the opposition United Workers Central,
Chile's largest labor federation with 300,000 members. The union
said the strike was to press for the release of its president,
Manuel Bustos, and its vice president, Arturo Martinez.
   Both leaders have been banished in small provincial towns since
September after a court sentenced them to 541 days' internal exile
for calling another general strike in 1987.
   Tuesday's strike, however, seemed to have little effect as most
factories and businesses operated near normalcy, although school
attendance was notably lower than normal.
   The government pronounced the strike ``a total failure.''
   Labor Minister Guillermo Arthur said, ``There has been no strike
in Chile today.'' He said around 95 percent of the nation's 4.5
million workers were on the job in spite of a cutback in the public
transportation system.
   Several of the bomb blasts destroyed or damaged power towers,
blacking out large areas of Santiago and several other cities for
several hours until power could be restored.
</TEXT>
