<DOCNO> AP890419-0046 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-89 0528EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Italy-Fusion     04-19 0639</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Italy-Fusion,0661</SECOND>
<HEAD>Researchers in Italy Report New Approach To Cold Fusion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scientists Umberto Colombo and Francesco Scaramuzzi
say they achieved nuclear fusion at room temperature using a
different technique than the recent cold fusion experiments which
prompted their tests.
   Colombo, head of the National Agency for Alternative Energy at
Frascati, just outside Rome, and Scaramuzzi, who performed the
experiments at the agency, both emphasized that it was too early to
say if their process would prove practical for generating energy.
   Their experiments produced large emissions of neutrons but too
little energy to register, the two men reported.
   A neutron is an uncharged elementary particle of an atom.
Emissions of neutrons are evidence of fusion.
   Fusion produces energy when the cores of two hydrogen atoms
fuse. It is the process that powers the sun. Fission is
atom-splitting, the method employed by conventional nuclear power
plants.
   The Italians began their experiments after Stanley Pons, a
chemistry professor at the University of Utah, and his British
colleague, Martin Fleischmann of the University of Southampton,
announced to the world on March 23 that they achieved nuclear
fusion at room temperature using common laboratory equipment.
   Researchers have long sought a way to harness nuclear fusion.
Standard experiments have used extremely high temperatures.
   Pons and Fleischmann said their experiment ran for more than 100
hours and produced four times as much energy as it used.
   Their experiments used electrolysis, in which an electrical
current was used to herd hydrogen atoms into metal electrodes,
where the atoms were apparently forced to fuse because of proximity.
   Researcher Steven Jones of Brigham Young University in Utah says
he found evidence of only very low energy output in a similar
experiment.
   Scaramuzzi told reporters on Tuesday, ``After Jones' experiment,
I asked myself, how important is electrolysis? There must be more
than one road to fusion.''
   The Italian experiments did not use electrical current to
trigger the reaction, nor did they use ``heavy water,'' which
contains a heavy version of hydrogen called deuterium.
   Colombo reported, ``The experiment is totally different from
former ones. We have paved the way for a new road to fusion
research. What we don't know yet is if the energy generated is
sufficient to justify practical application.''
   Scaramuzzi, 60, said, ``If this experiment were not of such
great importance to the public, we would never have announced the
discovery at this point. We are still in a very preliminary phase.''
   He said that on two occasions they measured high emissions of
neutrons after placing a sample of the element titanium and
deuterium gas in a special metal tube and subjecting it to various
pressures and temperatures.
   The neutrons appeared in one case after applying high pressure
and low temperature, and in another at low pressure and room
temperature.
   Scaramuzzi said the energy output of his experiment at this
scale was too low to be registered.
   Pons meanwhile said Monday that further experiments yielded even
more energy than the earlier Pons-Fleischmann efforts and ran more
efficiently. He said a controlled fusion reaction was sustained for
more than 800 hours in a small flask containing heavy water and a
palladium electrode and that recent tests produced roughly eight
times the energy consumed.
   Pons said researchers measured the production of 20 to 30 watts
of electricity from the experiment, or about 67 watts per cubic
centimeter of electrode, compared to 26 watts per cubic centimeter
in the earlier experiments.
   He reported that more than 60 university and private
laboratories partly verified the claims he made last month with
Fleischmann.
   The official Czechoslovak news agency CTK said Tuesday that a
team of Czechoslovak physicists led by Pavol Povinc also produced
room-temperature fusion through the electrolysis method.
   The team, from the Comenius University's faculty of mathematics
in Bratislava, capital of Slovakia, said they achieved fusion on
Monday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890419-0047 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-89 0528EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-RitualSlayings     04-19 0593</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ritual Slayings,0614</SECOND>
<HEAD>Human Sacrifice Rituals Described In Mexican Courtroom</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note contents of 16th graf, ``The godfather ...'' and 19th graf
``We called ...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MATAMOROS, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Descriptions of dismemberment and a
skull being split open were read in court from statements of
accused members of an occult group of drug smugglers that
authorities said killed 15 people.
   Separately, the ``godfather'' of the group and his girlfriend
were among 11 people indicted Tuesday by a grand jury in McAllen,
Texas.
   Alfonso de Jesus Constanzo, Sara Aldrete and the others were
charged with conspiracy to import marijuana, importing marijuana,
conspiracy to possess with intent to distribute and possession with
intent to distribute, authorities said.
   Constanzo, Aldrete and four others remained at large.
   With Judge Francisco Salador Perez of the Fourth Federal Court
presiding late Tuesday, court officials here read aloud from the
statements given by the five men arrested in connection with the
killings. The victims included Mark Kilroy, a Texas student
abducted during a spring-break outing to Matamoros in March.
   The five stood together, handcuffed and silent during the
preliminary hearing.
   They smoked occasionally as they listened to the description of
the horrors that occurred during ceremonies in a wooden shack on a
ranch near where most of the killings took place.
   The accused said those ceremonies were part of a ritualistic
cult.
   Four of the men refused to corroborate or deny the written
statements, arguing that their attorney was not present. They
declined a court-appointed counsel's help.
   Defendant Elio Hernandez told reporters near him that the
statement read to him ``did not agree entirely with what I
declared.''
   The judge said that the accused can submit additional statements
or have their own attorneys later. He now has three days to
consider the evidence and decide whether to continue to hold them
without bail.
   The accused have identified Constanzo as the group's leader who
offered them ``luck and protection'' in exchange for the human
sacrifices.
   Besides Hernandez, those under arrest are his brother, Serafin
Hernandez; Sergio Martinez; David Serna; and ranch caretaker
Domingo Reyes.
   Reyes was the only person who ratified his original statement
that led police to the ranch and the discovery of the bodies.
   ``The godfather asked us for a gringo for a sacrifice,'' read
the statement by Serafin Hernandez.
   ``He said the brains had to be placed in a pot.''
   Serafin Hernandez described how they picked up Kilroy by
offering him a ride. The student later tried to escape, but was
caught and taken to the ranch blindfolded.
   Also described was how Kilroy was killed with a machete blow to
the back of the head:
   ``We called the godfather at the hotel and told him what he
wanted was ready. He came in the next day ... the godfather and
Elio and others were inside (the shack). We heard a noise like a
coconut being cut open and ... they took out his brains ... and
part of the spine, and they cut his legs.''
   Serna's statement described how the group once raided another
ranch, stealing nearly 660 pounds of marijuana and abducting three
people.
   They were brought back to the ranch tied and blindfolded.
   ``We dug a hole and the godfather threw them in still alive and
machine-gunned them.''
   Juan Benitez Ayala, commander of the Federal Judicial Police in
this border city, said four of the 15 men found buried were
randomly chosen human sacrifices. The rest probably were drug
traffickers the organization found necessary to eliminate, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
