<DOCNO> AP890419-0048 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-89 0411EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-Nielsens Bjt   04-19 0726</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nielsens, Bjt,0746</SECOND>
<HEAD>NBC Keeps Ratings Lead Amid Slumping Viewer Numbers</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic NY15</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NBC captured its fourth straight ratings
victory but the broadcast networks' audience continued to dwindle.
The networks blamed the scriptwriters' strike, cable and
independent TV stations, and negative reviews.
   The three networks' combined share of the prime-time TV audience
was 68 percent _ the lowest in television history and about 3
percent below last season, according to the A.C. Nielsen Co.
   Last year's five-month Writers Guild of America strike delayed
the usual September start of almost every series, forcing NBC, ABC
and CBS to produce ``writerproof'' programs such as news specials
and new productions of old scripts from series like ``Mission:
Impossible.''
   NBC escaped the brunt of the strike because it broadcast the
1988 Summer Olympics and the World Series, popular sports specials
unaffected by the labor dispute.
   It won all 30 weeks of the September-to-April season, the first
time any network has done so since 1963-64, and claimed three of
the four most popular series, Nielsen said Tuesday.
   The network's margin of victory _ 24 percent _ was the
second-largest in Nielsen ratings history, the network said. For
the 1956-1957 season, CBS had a 25.6 rating, 27 percent ahead of
NBC, which had a 20.1 rating.
   ``It's something we're all very proud of,'' said Robert Wright,
NBC's president and chief executive officer.
   ``What the writers' strike did is hurt the new product,'' said
David Poltrack, CBS' senior vice president of planning and
research. ``The strike had an impact. It was not an even impact. It
helps the established competition.''
   The strike also boosted the performance of the Fox Broadcasting
Corp., Poltrack said. ``It was during the strike period that
`Married With Children' and `America's Most Wanted' started to
produce big numbers,'' he said.
   Boosted by its situation comedy ``Roseanne,'' the season's
highest-rated new series, ABC finished in second place. CBS came in
last among the Big Three for the second consecutive year.
   ABC and CBS disputed NBC's calculations, saying the television
season really began Oct. 24. Although both networks reported the
same order of finish, their numbers depicted NBC's victory in less
overwhelming terms.
   Based on NBC's figures, the network had a yearly rating of 16.0,
followed by ABC with 12.9 and CBS with 12.6, or a combined 41.5.
Last year, the combined rating was 42.8. Since each rating point
equals the 904,000 households with televisions, the networks' loss
was an estimated 1.175 million homes.
   Led by No. 1 hit ``The Cosby Show'' and the situation comedies
``A Different World,'' ``Cheers,'' ``The Golden Girls'' and
``ALF,'' NBC had 13 of the top 20 programs last season.
   The ratings for the week ending April 16 _ the end of the TV
season _ had NBC as the winner with a 14.5 rating, followed by CBS
with 12.7 and ABC with 12.1.
   NBC has won 43 ratings weeks in a row and is just four weeks
from CBS' all-time consecutive win record. NBC last lost a week in
the ratings in June 1988.
   ``What we have now is one No. 1 and two No. 3s,'' said Werner
Michel, senior vice president for Bozell, Jacobs, Kenyon &amp; Eckhardt
advertising agency.
   ``It's never good for the industry to have one network so
dominant,'' he said. ``It limits your programming choice and your
media choice. You can't put everything on NBC.''
   But NBC, once the media's darling, came under attack from many
television critics who believed the network had turned to the
tawdry.
   Among the targets: the racy miniseries ``Favorite Son,'' the
lurid movie ``Full Exposure'' and Geraldo Rivera's sensational
documentary on devil worship.
   The season's most-watched miniseries was CBS' ``Lonesome Dove,''
the adaptation of novelist Larry McMurtry's account of a cattle
drive. In second was ABC's ``Women of Brewster Place,'' starring
Oprah Winfrey, and NBC's ``Brotherhood of the Rose.'' ``War and
Remembrance,'' ABC's $100 million epic miniseries, finished in
fourth.
   Alan Wurtzel, ABC's senior vice president of marketing and
research services, said his network was encouraged by its strong
showing on Friday and Tuesday nights, the latter anchored by
``Roseanne.''
   Still, he said the networks' overall losses likely will
continue. ``I expect we'll see a fairly similar decline next
year,'' he said. ``The loss will be consistent until the mid-'90s
when cable penetration levels off.''
</TEXT>
