<FIRST>r a PM-Obit-RuthBerle     04-19 0254</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Ruth Berle,0264</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ruth Berle, Wife of Milton Berle, Dead at 67</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY85</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ruth Berle, wife of comedian Milton Berle,
has died at age 67.
   Mrs. Berle died at Cedars-Sinai Medical Center on Tuesday
evening, said Tim Scerba, a publicist for the 80-year-old comedian.
She had suffered from cancer, he said.
   Mrs. Berle began work in the public relations field in New York
in the 1940s, taking on work for motion picture studios such as
Samuel Goldwyn Productions, United Artists, RKO and Eagle-Lion.
   She was involved in many philanthropic causes in Los Angeles,
including Democratic politics and S.H.A.R.E., an organization
working with mentally handicapped children.
   In 1968, she was a delegate from California to the Democratic
National Convention.
   She met Berle in 1951 and they were married two years later.
   ``Ruth has settled me down,'' Berle once said. ``I call her
Rocky _ my rock of Gibraltar.''
   Born May 14, 1921, in Portland, Maine, she grew up in Paterson,
N.J. During World War II, she served as a first lieutenant in the
Women's Army Corps and by war's end was a company commander and
captain.
   Milton Berle, known as ``Mr. Television,'' was host of ``Texaco
Star Theater,'' and ``The Milton Berle Show.'' His films include
``Tall, Dark and Handsome'' and ``It's a Mad Mad Mad Mad World.''
   In addition to her husband, survivors include an adopted son,
Bill; stepdaughter, Vicki Walton; mother; and brother.
   The family planned a private burial, with a memorial service to
be announced later.
</TEXT>
