<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     04-19 0364</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0375</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Off, Nikkei Hits Record High</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar fell today against the Japanese
yen, while the Tokyo Stock Exchange's key index rose slightly to
another record high.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues closed at
33,363.83, up 42.17 points, or 0.13 percent. The index set its
previous high of 33,321.66 points on Tuesday, when it edged up
13.33 points.
   The dollar closed at 131.88 yen, down 0.22 yen from Tuesday's
132.10-yen finish. It opened at 131.38 yen but generally moved up
during the day, while ranging from 131.35 yen to 131.95 yen.
   Traders said the currency's lower opening in Tokyo followed a
drop on overseas markets, where discouragement over U.S. economic
figures released late Tuesday in Washington led to dollar-selling.
   The U.S. Labor Department reported Tuesday that the nation's
consumer price index in March rose 0.5 percent, up from February's
0.4 percent, while the Commerce Department said U.S. housing starts
in March fell 5.4 percent to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of
1.397 million.
   ``But market players (in Tokyo) began buying back the dollar
toward the end of the morning session for their position
adjustments because they thought they had sold too much ahead of
the report,'' said a trader with Mitsubishi Bank, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   There were not enough dollar-buying incentives to push the
dollar above 132 yen, he added.
   On the stock market, the Nikkei index started higher following a
41.61-point gain in the Dow Jones industrial average in New York
overnight, said a dealer with Nomura Securities, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   ``Participants took the U.S. economic indicators positively as
showing a slowdown in the nation's economy,'' he said.
   Such a slowdown now would ease fears of inflation, prompt
expectations of lower interest rates and encourage stock
investment. Lower U.S. interest rates, however, make the dollar
less attractive to foreign investors.
   The dealer added that Japan's political uncertainties ``have
largely discouraged foreign and institutional investors, who hardly
participate these days. Major players are only individuals.''
   Today's trading was active, with first section volume estimated
at 1.4 billion shares, up from Tuesday's 1.1 billion. Among gainers
were steel and chemical issues.
</TEXT>
