<FIRST>r a PM-FusionTest     04-19 0593</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fusion Test,0609</SECOND>
<HEAD>More Developments On Cold Fusion Front</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE WILSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STANFORD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scientists at Stanford University say
their experiments with cold fusion prove the energy generated could
not have come from a chemical reaction as some skeptics have
suggested.
   The researchers revealed their findings Tuesday, one of several
announcements made around the world related to the discovery of
University of Utah chemist Stanley Pons and British colleague
Martin Fleischmann.
   _In Rome, Italian scientists said they achieved fusion at room
temperature with a different process than the one in the Utah
experiments, which used electrical currents in ``heavy water'' to
trigger the reaction. ``We have paved the way for a new road to
fusion research,'' said Umberto Colombo, head of the National
Agency for Alternative Energy.
   _In Czechoslovakia, a team of physicists said they also produced
room-temperature fusion.
   _In New Mexico, Pons said he wants to help Los Alamos National
Laboratory scientists duplicate his cold fusion experiments so the
lab will collaborate with him on research.
   The apparent discovery of cold fusion was announced March 23 by
Pons and Fleischmann, who set off an international debate about
whether the process was indeed fusion.
   Pons and Fleischmann said they had achieved fusion using
ordinary laboratory equipment at room temperatures. Standard
experiments have used extremely high temperatures, making them
impractical for large-scale energy production because they use more
energy than they produce.
   Since the announcement, scientists have been trying to duplicate
the experiment and its results. If fusion can be created as easily
as Pons and Fleischmann claim, scientists say, it could be a
relatively inexpensive and virtually inexhaustible energy source.
   The Stanford finding came from a team of seven researchers led
by Roert A. Huggins, professor of material sciences.
   Displaying a simple experiment with palladium electrodes in
tubes of heavy water and plain water in a plastic picnic basket,
Huggins said the energy generated was not the result of any known
chemical reaction.
   Huggins wouldn't speculate on why the experiment produced a 50
percent energy gain in heavy water, but he acknowledged the most
likely cause was some kind of fusion process.
   ``We're seeing excess heat that's above and beyond any possible
chemical reaction,'' he said. ``It means the effect is real and is
substantial.''
   The energy may result, however, from a different type of fusion
than is commonly known, he said.
   Huggins' team ran five experiments over two weeks, using a tube
of deuterium oxide, or heavy water, and a tube of plain water. If
the experiments produced the same results, they said, it would
indicate the energy was not from fusion.
   Instead, they found much higher temperatures from the heavy
water, which meant the energy was not a chemical reaction because
there is no essential chemical difference between the two kinds of
water.
   Last week, two graduate students at the Univeristy of Washington
said they had detected cold fusion in an experiment conducted with
heavy water, but they could not get the same results using ordinary
water.
   On Monday, Pons said the apparent cold fusion discovery had been
partly verified by more than 60 university and private
laboratories, but none has reported observing both the production
of neutrons and the high level of heat that he and Fleischmann
produced. The experiment at Stanford was not designed to measure
neutrons.
   Neutrons are a tell-tale sign of fusion, the process powering
the sun, in which tremendous amounts of energy are released when
hydrogen atoms fuse. In contrast, conventional nuclear power plants
use fission, the splitting of atoms.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890419-0053 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-89 0530EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Flight103     04-19 0539</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Flight 103,0553</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: Pan Am Documents State Many U.S. Diplomats Canceled Seats</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Large numbers of U.S. diplomats canceled seats on
Pan Am flights in the weeks before the bombing of Flight 103,
according to a U.S. Congressional panel that saw internal Pan Am
documents, a British newspaper reported today.
   The Independent, a respected daily, said documents sent to a
House of Representatives panel probing the Dec. 21 bombing show
that Christmas holiday traffic for U.S. embassies had been heavily
re-booked prior to the bombing.
   The report noted that relatives of those who died in the bombing
have been angry that warnings of a possible bombing of a Pan Am
flight from Frankfurt to the United States were not made public.
   All 259 people on Pan Am Flight 103 and 11 on the ground were
killed when the New York-bound Boeing 747 was blown up over the
Scottish town of Lockerbie. The flight had originated in Frankfurt,
West Germany.
   ``A private House of Representatives transportation subcommittee
memorandum on the documents, which has been seen by The
Independent, said that it had asked Pan Am for all internal
documents relating to security procedures and for information about
who knew of the threat,'' the paper wrote.
   ``Included among the documents it received were internal company
telegrams and memoranda. The subcommittee memo said that one Pan Am
internal request read that `specific details on lost revenue for
U.S. State Department officials' were required. A second was a
request for `public information guidelines' in view that about 80
percent of holiday traffic of embassy is re-booking.
   ``The subcommittee memo, dated 13 March, goes on to say that Pan
Am needed to be asked what were `the details of lost revenue since
Pan Am was obviously keeping track of threat-related
cancellations.'''
   The U.S. government has denied that its officials, acting on the
warnings, had thus avoided Pan Am flights, the report said.
   Copies of what The Independent described as a ``supposedly
secret'' alert bulletin from the U.S. Federal Aviation
Administration were posted on notice boards at the U.S. Embassy in
Moscow on or around Dec. 13.
   The FAA bulletin was drawn up after an anonymous caller to the
U.S. Embassy in Helsinki said a bomb attack would be made in the
two weeks after Dec. 5. The FAA bulletin was sent to embassies so
that they could inform foreign governments.
   Since the Lockerbie bombing, the United States and the Finnish
police have maintained that the telephoned warning was a hoax. But
no attempt was made to withdraw the bulletin in the days before the
bombing, The Independent said.
   Relatives of those who died on Flight 103 have maintained it was
inevitable that diplomats would act on the bulletin, warning
friends and relatives and canceling Pan Am reservations.
   On April 7, Clayton McManaway, the U.S. ambassador-at-large for
counterterrorism, told the U.S. Senate: ``That is not true,'' the
newspaper note.
   The report said McManaway pointed out then that 31 U.S.
government personnel died in the bombing.
   He added that the decision of the U.S. Embassy in Moscow to post
copies of the warning was not in accordance with U.S. government
policy and that steps were being taken to prevent it happening
again.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890419-0054 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-89 0622EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Contras     04-19 0371</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Contras,0384</SECOND>
<HEAD>Contras Charge Sandinistas Slaughter Rebel Backers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nicaraguan rebel leaders say the leftist government
has broken recent peace accords by killing dozens of Contra
supporters. The allegation received backing from the human rights
group Americas Watch.
   ``The Sandinista government is massacring supporters of the
resistance,'' Contra director Aristides Sanchez said at the group's
Miami headquarters Tuesday. ``They are wiping out our entire social
base.''
   With elections approaching, the Contras charged that the
Nicaraguan military has been slaughtering between 40 and 50
civilians during the past two months in northern Nicaragua, where
the U.S.-backed rebels once found their strongest support.
   Sandinista soldiers, the Contras said, killed 13 rebel
supporters in the town of Apantillo alone.
   In Washington, Americas Watch, which has frequently criticized
the Contras, backed up the Contra version of events.
   ``We have written the Nicaraguan government and are waiting to
see what they are doing about this,'' said spokesman Juan Mendez.
``We cannot dismiss them as isolated incidents any more.''
   The Contras withdrew from the northern region after a recent
series of peace accords, said Adolfo Calero, another of the seven
rebel leaders.
   But that withdrawal left rebel supporters open to repression, he
said.
   ``They are taking advantage of the truce and the peace
agreements to eliminate all our supporters,'' Calero said.
   Another charged raised at the Contra news conference was that
the Sandinistas have mined roads along the Honduran and Costa Rican
borders.
   Calero said Nicaragua's Supreme Electoral Council, set to
oversee planned national elections next year violates Sandinista
promises made at a meeting of Central American leaders in El
Salvador that a ``balanced'' commission would be created.
   He said Nicaraguan President Daniel Ortega and the national
assembly controlled by the Sandinistas are planning to appoint and
approve all five members. Two members were to be chosen by the
opposition.
   ``This is no way to initiate the electoral process in
Nicaragua,'' Calero said. ``And we expect the Central American
presidents to demand it be changed.''
   In Managua, Nicaragua, the defense ministry reported Tuesday
that Contra forces killed three people and injured two in an attack
on a home in the Rio Kama area, 400 miles southeast of Managua.
</TEXT>
