<DOCNO> AP890419-0055 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-89 0623EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     04-19 0505</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rain In Northeast, Thunderstorms In South</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A cold front dumped rain from western Tennessee to New England
today and showers and thunderstorms dampened parts of Texas,
Arkansas and Louisiana.
   Rain also fell over western Oregon, northwestern California and
southern Florida. Fair skies prevailed early this morning across
much of the rest of the nation.
   In West Virginia, Morgantown reported three-quarters of an inch
of rain and Parkersburg nearly six-tenths of an inch in the six
hours ending at 2 a.m. EDT.
   Fog developed along the central Gulf Coast, with dense fog in
southeastern Mississippi and southwest Alabama.
   On Tuesday, strong thunderstorms in the south-central U.S.
produced hail and gusting winds.
   South of Sherwood, Okla., hail was reported the size of golf
balls, and winds gusted to 70 mph near Pecos, Texas.
   The Southwest was hot Tuesday, with record temperatures for the
date in El Paso, Texas, which had a high of 94 degrees; Ely, Nev.,
81 degrees; Reno, Nev., 83 degrees; and Tucson, Ariz., 98 degrees.
   Phoenix registered 100 degrees, tying a record set in 1962.
Other ties: Taos, N.M., 76 degrees, and Winnemucca, Nev., 83
degrees.
   The nation's hottest spots Tuesday were Buckeye, Ariz., and
Laughlin, Nev., both at 102 degrees.
   Today's forecast: showers and thunderstorms scattered over
Florida, from North Carolina across the southern Appalachians and
the central Gulf Coast states to southeast Texas; strong
thunderstorms along the Gulf Coast from southeast Texas to southern
Mississippi; rain showers from southern New England to the middle
Atlantic Coast; and rain spread across the Pacific Northwest.
   High temperatures were expected in the 40s and 50s from the
Great Lakes region to New England; in the 80s from the southern
Atlantic Coast states across Florida and the Gulf Coast region, the
southern Rockies and portions of the central Rockies to inland
California; from 90 to 105 degrees in the desert Southwest and
inland southern California; and in the 90s over the Rio Grande
Valley of Texas. Much of the remainder of the nation was to have
high temperatures generally in the 60s and 70s.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 25
degrees at Hibbing, Minn., and International Falls, Minn., to 79
degrees at Yuma, Ariz.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 63 fair; Boston 42 rain; Buffalo 32 fair;
