<FIRST>r a PM-Asthma-Custody     04-19 0415</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Asthma-Custody,0426</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Removes Asthmatic Child From Home of Smoking Parents</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENTON, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 3-year-old girl with chronic asthma is
living in a foster home because a judge ruled her parents weren't
doing enough to keep her away from cigarette smoke.
   Caroline County social workers removed the girl from her
parent's home last month and she remains in a foster home. The
girl's name was not released.
   ``It's a critical situation,'' Circuit Judge J. Owen Wise said
during a juvenile court hearing March 17. Wise placed the child
under the authority of the social services department.
   ``It is not something that the social services or the medical
people are doing on a whim or caprice. They're afraid she's going
to die prematurely and unnecessarily if something isn't done,''
Wise said.
   Wise said the parents could regain custody of their daughter if
they make changes in their lives. He granted them full visitation
rights.
   The child was admitted to a hospital near her home on Maryland's
eastern shore, across the Chesapeake Bay from Baltimore, at least
half a dozen times over the past year or so, and on two occasions
was transferred to Johns Hopkins University Hospital in Baltimore.
Once, she was admitted to the intensive care unit for treatment of
serious respiratory problems associated with asthma.
   The child lived with her great-grandmother, her legal custodian
from March 1987 to March 1988. Delaware authorities had granted
custody to the relative while the family was living in that state
because the girl's parents could not afford to properly care for
her.
   But in March 1988, Caroline County authorities returned the
child to her parents, who had moved to Denton.
   In January, the child's father lost his job and the family moved
in with the great-grandmother. Until recently, the girl's parents
and great-grandmother smoked.
   Andrea Allen, a physician with Caroline County Health Services,
testified that on at least two occasions, the girl was in severe
respiratory distress when brought to the hospital.
   Ms. Allen said that tobacco, which can bring on an asthma
attack, may have been a critical factor.
   ``My particular concerns about this child include that the
family continued to smoke despite many warnings that this was not
appropriate,'' Ms. Allen said. ``I do know that they tried to smoke
outside the home or at least they were reporting that to us. But
because the smoke is carried on clothing and other articles and in
the car, this simply is not measure enough.''
</TEXT>
