<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Higher, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose against nearly all major
currencies in light European trading early today. Gold bullion fell.
   Barring any unexpected events, dealers said they expected little
movement in exchange rates throughout the day.
   The dollar fell Tuesday in reaction to a U.S. Labor Department
report that consumer prices rose 0.5 percent in March, which was in
line with expectations and diminished concern of a rise in U.S.
interest rates.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar fell 0.22 Japanese yen to a closing 131.88 yen.
Later, in London, it edged up to 131.90 yen.
   Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late Tuesday:
   _ 1.8572 West German marks, up from 1.8528
   _ 1.6320 Swiss francs, up from 1.6283
   _ 6.2885 French francs, up from 6.2750
   _ 2.0952 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0935
   _ 1,362.50 Italian lire, down from 1,366.95
   _ 1.1860 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1848
   In London, the British pound fell to $1.7120 from $1.7185 late
Tuesday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $383.15 a troy ounce,
down from $383.25 bid late Tuesday. At midmorning today, the city's
five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $382.90.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $382.70, down from $384 bid late
Tuesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $2.43 to close at a bid $384.25.
   Silver bullion fell in London to a bid price of $5.77 a troy
ounce, down from $5.78 bid late Tuesday.
