<FIRST>u i PM-Malaysia 1stLd-Writethru   04-19 0487</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Malaysia, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0486,0500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition Leader Freed After 18-Month Detention Without Trial</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with Kit Siang comments, details.
No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARI S. MANIAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The country's leading opposition
politician, Lim Kit Siang, was released from prison today after
being held without charge for 18 months.
   With the release of Lim and his son Lim Guan Eng from Kamunting
Detention Camp, 120 miles north of this capital, the
Malay-dominated government has freed all 106 people it arrested
during an October 1987 crackdown.
   The government that year angered many ethnic Chinese, who
generally maintain their separate culture and language, by
assigning non-Chinese speaking teachers to Chinese primary schools.
   Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad, himself a Malay, has said the
1987 arrests of opposition politicians, environmentalists, trade
unionists, church workers, educators and others was necessary to
prevent Malay-Chinese rioting.
   But Kit Siang described the last 18 months as ``a nightmare for
democratic rights in Malaysia.''
   His primary concern now, he said, ``is to do all I can to
restore public confidence in democracy and restore Malaysia's image
abroad.''
   Both Kit Siang, who is Secretary-General of the opposition
Democratic Action Party, and his son are members of Parliament and
ethnic Chinese.
   Fellow Parliament members Vethamuthu David and Karpal Singh were
released a few months ago but were told they could not speak to the
press, that they have to report to police if they leave their
hometown, are prohibited from addressing public gatherings and must
report to the authorities every month.
   Mahathir has said that through their actions and speeches those
arrested in 1987 had increased racial tension in Malaysia, where
government policy promotes Malays' economic standing in a country
long dominated by Chinese businessmen.
   Every business in the country must be partially owned by Malays,
who also are given tax breaks for starting their own companies.
Universities teach in Malay, which has been named the national
language, and Islam has been named the state religion.
   The country's 17 million population is 55 percent Malay and 37
percent Chinese, with most of the remainder Indian.
   The races in this former British colony have argued periodically
over language, cultural and other differences, but there has been
no major unrest since 500 people died in Malay-Chinese rioting in
1969.
   When Mahathir became prime minister in July 1981, 550 people
were being held under the Internal Security Act, which allows
imprisonment without trial. Mahathir called for a review and
released most of them.
   Deputy Home Affairs Minister Megat Junid Megat Ayub says 70
people are still held without trial under the act.
   Lee Lam Thye, also an ethnic Chinese and a member of parliament
who has been the acting leader of the opposition and secretary
general in Kit Siang's absence, called on the government ``to
release all the other internal security act detainees or charge
them in an open court of law.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
