<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-89 0728EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Spill-BirdRehab 1stLd-Writethru a0450 04-19 0636</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Spill-Bird Rehab, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0450,0655</SECOND>
<HEAD>Center Works To Save Oiled Birds</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS to Cullowhee sted Collowhee in 3rd graf.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Tanker Spill, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL JENKINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VALDEZ, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While the effort to clean oil-drenched
beaches sputters to life, volunteers armed with dish soap are
wearily trying to save birds marked for death by sticky goo from
the Exxon Valdez.
   Outside a makeshift rehabilitation center in a college
dormitory, already cleaned cormorants gingerly spread their wings
to dry in the sun. Ducks bob in plywood-sided tanks. The smell of
fish used as food permeates the air.
   ``The ones that make it this far, into those tanks, usually make
it,'' said Mike Masson, a volunteer from Cullowhee, N.C. ``If
they're in there they'll probably be OK.''
   Many do not survive after reaching the center, run by the
International Bird Rescue Research Center, a California-based
non-profit corporation.
   The center's executive director, Alice Berkner, said 349
oil-coated birds have been brought in since the tanker rammed Bligh
Reef on March 24, spilling more than 10 million gallons of North
Slope crude into Prince William Sound.
   Of the 349, 136 died from the oil's toxic effects, exposure,
dehydration or loss of bouyancy. Twenty-two have been returned to
the wild. Many are being held at the center because they might
return to the oil-contaminated areas.
   By Tuesday, the Coast Guard had logged 1,850 birds found dead in
the sound since the spill. But the true number of dead birds and
animals will never be known because of the sound's vast distances
and remote shorelines.
   Ms. Berkner said as the oil has spread, the effort to save birds
has widened. She said the organization has opened a cleaning center
in Seward and she was going to Kodiak to open another.
   Luckily, there were few ducks and shorebirds in the sound when
the tanker hit the rocks. It was before the spring arrival of
waterfowl.
   Ms. Berkner was unsure how birds migrating into the sound now
might be affected.
   ``I think right now, let's wait and see,'' she said. ``We're
hoping the slick will break up. ... We're preparing for the worst
and hoping for the best.''
   For Ms. Berkner, this spill is not the first.
   Her first was in 1971, after two Chevron tankers collided in San
Francisco Bay.
   ``I just went down and helped for two weeks. That two weeks
turned into 18 years,'' she said.
   In Prince William Sound, the birds are picked up in the sound by
43 boats under contract to Exxon. The vessels also pick up dead
birds for disposal.
   Once aboard the vessels, the birds are kept warm and given
liquids. Each night, the day's haul is transferred to the cleanup
center.
   In Valdez, the birds are checked for injuries, banded and held
for washing.
   The workers use a popular dishwashing liquid.
   Inside the center, activity seems constant as seven paid staff
members and the 20 or so volunteers rush to clean birds.
   Carpeted floors are covered with plastic. Notes are taped to
walls.
   In the ``dirty bird'' room, candidates for cleaning wait in
plywood enclosures with coarse wire floors. The boxes are covered
with sheets to give the birds privacy.
   ``It takes two to 12 tubs of water to clean the birds,'' said
Mary Scott, coordinator for the volunteers. Just rinsing the birds
can take 45 minutes, she said.
   In the ``clean bird'' room, the birds are held in covered
enclosures warmed by commercial pet dryers.
   Then they are observed in the tanks outside to ensure they can
float and will not succumb to hypothermia.
   The tanks are an attraction for visitors and workers.
   ``This is what makes it worthwhile _ coming out here and
watching the silly birds eating and splashing around,'' Ms. Scott
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890419-0064 </DOCNO>
