<FIRST>r i PM-Israel     04-19 0393</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel,0404</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soldiers Wound 17 in Gaza</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers shot and wounded at least 17
Palestinians in clashes today, including 11 children who suffered
mostly head injuries from rubber and plastic bullets, Arab hospital
officials said.
   Today's violence occurred as soldiers and police beefed up
security in the occupied lands and inside Israel to prevent riots
or attacks on Jews during the seven-day Jewish Passover holiday,
which begins tonight.
   A public opinion survey published by a newspaper indicated 65
percent of Israelis supported a peace plan by Prime Minister
Yitzhak Shamir that calls for Arabs in the West Bank and Gaza Strip
to elect representatives for peace talks.
   However, the Al Hamishmar newspaper said that Jewish settlers in
the occupied lands have formed a committee seeking to stop the
election plan, which they claim would ``bring about a Palestinian
state.''
   In the Gaza Strip, soldiers clashed with stone-throwing youths
today in the Khan Yunis and Nusseirat refugee camps, the village of
Beit Hanoun and a neighborhood in Gaza City.
   Arab hospital officials said the wounded included six chidren
age 14 or younger who were hit with rubber bullets in the head and
face. Five other youths were struck with plastic or rubber bullets
in other parts of the body.
   The officials said six people ages 17 to 30 also were injured
with plastic bullets.
   In Arab east Jerusalem, police detained 27 Palestinians accused
of involvement in stone-throwing riots after midnight, in which
three policemen and two Arabs were injured, said the Jerusalem
police spokesman, Uzi Sandori.
   In the 16-month uprising, 439 Palestinians have been killed,
most shot by soldiers quelling stone-throwing protests. Eighteen
Israelis also have died.
   The Yediot Ahronot newspaper said it conducted the public
opinion survey on Shamir's plan April 12-16 in face-to-face
interviews with a random sample of 656 Israelis. Sixty-five percent
said they supported the elections plan and 31 percent were opposed,
while 4 percent said they had no view, the newspaper said. No
margin of error was given for the poll.
   A Western relief official in Gaza City said that about 40
percent of the wounded in the Palestinian revolt are now 15 and
younger.
   ``In the beginning of the uprising, the average age of those
getting shot was much higher,'' said the official, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
</TEXT>
