<SECOND>PM-Bush-Arrest,0189</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Who Claimed He Could Breach Bush Security Freed on Bail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who claimed he could breach President
Bush's security was freed on $50,000 bond and ordered to undergo a
four-month psychiatric review.
   U.S. Magistrate Steven Pepe on Tuesday scheduled Richard
Gregory's arraignment on a federal misdemeanor charge for May 3.
   Gregory, 37, of Macomb County's Clinton Township, was arrested
Monday when he showed up at Selfridge Air National Guard Base near
Mount Clemens. Bush had departed from there after speaking in
Hamtramck that day.
   Gregory had called the White House earlier and left his car
telephone number, said Jim Hughes, head of the Detroit Secret
Service office. He said he could breach Bush's security and that it
``involved a man wearing a business suit and carrying a cellular
telephone that would actually be an explosive device,'' Hughes said.
   Police traced the telephone number and were on the lookout for
Gregory when he showed up at the gate wearing a suit and carrying a
car phone and briefcase, Hughes said. Neither the briefcase nor the
telephone contained explosives.
