<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-89 0830EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-ChristianScienceTrial 2ndLd-Writethru a0514 04-19 0479</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Christian Science Trial, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0514,0486</SECOND>
<HEAD>Couple Convicted For Failing To Treat Ill Daughter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 3rd graf to restore time element</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SARASOTA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Christian Science couple was found
guilty of murder for allowing their 7-year-old diabetic daughter to
die without medical attention because of their religious beliefs.
   William Hermanson, 42, and his wife, Christine, 38, could be
sentenced to three to seven years in prison under state sentencing
guidelines. They were allowed to remain free until sentencing. No
sentencing date has been set.
   A jury found the Hermansons guilty Tuesday of third-degree
murder and child abuse in the 1986 death of their daughter, Amy.
They had rejected a plea bargain agreement for 15 years' probation
in exchange for a plea of guilty or no contest.
   ``We will be filing motions for a new trial,'' said defense
attorney Charles Arnold. He said he was ``disappointed and
surprised'' at the verdict.
   The Hermansons were the first Christian Scientists in 20 years
prosecuted in the United States for denying a child medical care
for religious reasons, church representatives said. Five other
religious exemption cases are pending, three in California, one
each in Arizona and Massachusetts.
   The defense said the case was about religious freedom and cited
a 1975 Florida law that protects parents who withhold medical
treatment from their sick children if they are ``legitimately
practicing'' their religious beliefs.
   Prosecutors contended it was murder, saying the girl died after
her parents ignored pleas to take her to a doctor and relied
instead on prayer to heal her untreated diabetes.
   Christian Scientists rely on prayer instead of medicine to care
for the ill and may call on church-accredited ``practitioners''
with expertise in spiritual healing. However, members may seek
medical assistance without fear of sanctions.
   Nathan Talbot, church spokesman from Boston, said the conviction
would tend to unify Christian Scientists.
   The church must ``do a fuller job of helping society understand
that it has a wonderful gift in spiritual healing and it would be a
loss for all of us to prosecute out of existence spiritual
healing,'' he said.
   But Rita Swan, a former Christian Scientist from Iowa who began
a campaign to fight religious exemption laws after losing a son to
meningitis 12 years ago, called the verdict significant.
   ``It signals to the nation that society does not approve of this
behavior, and Christian Scientists had better wake up and listen,''
she said. ``These jurors could not accept the notion that a child
should be allowed to die of diabetes for which, everybody knows,
there is a standard, very effective treatment.''
   Last week, with the jury out of the room, a witness testified
that both parents had sought medical treatment for themselves but
not for their daughter. The jury never heard that testimony because
the judge ruled that prosecutors had improperly withheld the
information from defense attorneys.
</TEXT>
