<DOCNO> AP890419-0068 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-89 0855EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Sudan-Attack     04-19 0522</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sudan-Attack,0536</SECOND>
<HEAD>First U.N. Relief Convoy Ambushed; Eight Reported Killed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIDRIKKE SCHANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attackers ambushed the first U.N. convoy
bringing relief supplies to rebel-held southern Sudan, destroying
the lead vehicle and reportedly killing eight rebel escorts, U.N.
officials said today.
   Diane Weathers, a U.N. World Food Program spokeswoman, said a
driver and two assistants also were wounded in the Tuesday
afternoon attack 14 miles west of the Sudan People's Liberation
Army base at Kapoeta.
   The 14-truck convoy was carrying 100 tons of food and relief
supplies to the town of Torit, 100 miles west of Kapoeta.
   It was the first relief convoy to Torit under Operation
Lifeline-Sudan, the U.N.-organized effort to stock more than
100,000 tons of food and supplies in southern Sudan before rain in
May makes transportation virtually impossible.
   The effort is intended to avert another tragedy like that in
1988, when relief officials say about 500,000 people died from
drought.
   The operation began April 1 after the government and the rebels
agreed to allow aid to move unhampered through rebel-held and
government-controlled land.
   U.N. officials in Nairobi did not say who they believed was
responsible for Tuesday's ambush, but they said it was unlikely
Sudan People's Liberation Army rebels would attack their own
members.
   The Sudan People's Liberation Army took up arms against the
Moslem-dominated government in 1983, demanding greater autonomy and
economic development for the predominantly Christian and animist
south.
   A French monitor for the World Food Program was riding with the
convoy when it was attacked and reported the incident Tuesday night
to U.N. officials, said Ms. Weathers.
   Eight rebel escorts, members of the People's Liberation Army's
Sudan Relief and Rehabilitation Association, were killed by
automatic weapon fire, and the lead vehicle was destroyed by ``some
sort of missile,'' said Paul Mitchell, a U.N. spokesman. Mitchell
did not know whether the rebel escorts were armed.
   He said that because of the attack, Operation Lifeline's
overland route to Torit from Kapoeta would be suspended. He said an
airlift from the Ugandan city of Entebbe would begin Friday to
Torit, which was captured by rebels in March.
   Ms. Weathers said in the last three weeks, Torit's population
has soared from 3,000 to 25,000 as displaced Sudanese seeking
shelter and food pour in. She said the U.N. expected the population
to grow to as many as 50,000.
   Ms. Weathers said that while Tuesday's attack interrupted the
overland relief operation to Torit, the remainder of the aid
operation would continue.
   The United Nations planned to move 25,000 tons of food and
supplies before rains begin in mid-May, but to date U.N. convoys
have moved only 120 tons of food to Kapoeta from Kenya, said Ms.
Weathers.
   The Norwegian People's Aid, in conjunction with the
California-based World Vision relief agency and the U.S. Agency for
International Development, has trucked several thousand tons of
relief supplies to Kapoeta since October in another relief
operation.
   From Uganda, a joint World Food Program-Catholic Relief Services
airlift has carried 3,000 tons of relief supplies to the city of
Juba, home to an estimated 300,000 war refugees and residents.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
