<FIRST>r i PM-Italy-Walesa 1stLd-Writethru a0509 04-19 0385</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Italy-Walesa, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0509,0392</SECOND>
<HEAD>Solidarity Leader Arrives in Rome to Meet Pope</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to UPDATE with pope's remarks. Pickup graf
6 pvs, ``On Monday...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEPHEN R. WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa flashed the victory
sign as he arrived today to meet with countryman Pope John Paul II
and seek Western aid for Poland in the wake of the historic
reconcilation with his government.
   The pope, speaking to a group of Polish pilgrims at his general
audience, hailed the accords legalizing Walesa's mass labor
movement. He offered prayers to the Madonna of Jasna Gora, Poland's
holiest shrine, so that all Poles will have the ``courage, wisdom
and calm'' to forge Poland's new course.
   Leaders of Italy's three main trade unions met Walesa at Rome's
Leonardo da Vinci Airport along with the ambassador, Josef Wiejacz,
who presented Walesa with a bouquet of red and white roses, the
colors of Poland.
   Noting the presence of the ambassador, Walesa said, ``This is a
sign of the accord and should be a good sign so that we can go
forward together.''
   The Italian trip came a day after Walesa held a symbolic
reconciliation with Poland's leader, Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski, who
declared martial law in December 1981 to crush the Solidarity labor
movement.
   Walesa will meet John Paul on Thursday and also will meet with
the Italian president, premier and foreign minister during his
three-day stay. Walesa is expected to ask for aid to help rebuild
Poland's battered economy.
   On Monday, a court in Warsaw restored the legal status of
Solidarity after a seven-year ban.
   ``For this victory to be complete, we now have to take care of
real issues and to get down to work together,'' the gray-suited
Walesa told a throng of journalists and well-wishers at the airport
today.
   Walesa flew in on a LOT Polish Airlines flight from Warsaw,
accompanied by his wife, Danuta, and the Roman Catholic bishop of
Gdansk, Tadeusz Goclowski.
   It was a triumphal return for Walesa, who last visited Rome in
January 1981, in Solidarity's heyday, when the pope gave his warm
endorsement to Solidarity, the first independent labor movement in
the Soviet bloc. The two men met again in 1983 and 1987 during
pilgrimages by John Paul to his homeland.
</TEXT>
