<FIRST>r a PM-Volkswagen     04-19 0202</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Volkswagen,0209</SECOND>
<HEAD>Volkswagen Racial Discrimination Case Settled</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Black former employees of a closed Volkswagen
plant have until May 26 to file a claim to participate in a
proposed $718,000 settlement of a 6-year-old racial discrimination
suit.
   Volkswagen of America Inc. and the United Auto Workers agreed to
settle a racial discrimination lawsuit without admitting any of the
allegations filed on behalf of about 800 former employees.
   U.S. District Judge Gustave Diamond scheduled a June 13 hearing
to consider approving the settlement.
   Under terms reached March 24, the American subsidiary of the
West German auto company would pay $670,000, and the union would
pay $48,000 without admitting any guilt, said Tom McDonald, VW
spokesman in Troy, Mich.
   Volkswagen also agreed to pay $250,000 in lawyers' fees.
   Citing declining sales of its Golf and Jetta models, Volkswagen
last year closed the Westmoreland County facility, its lone U.S.
assembly plant.
   If the plaintiffs accept the settlement, individual payments
would range from $70,000 to a supervisor who said he was harassed
on the job, to $200 for hourly workers who were fired before their
90-day probations expired.
   The plaintiffs had been seeking $70 million under the class
action suit, filed in 1983.
</TEXT>
