<DOCNO> AP890419-0081 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-89 1037EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Film-Violence     04-19 0330</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Film-Violence,0336</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mass. High Court Says Paramount Not Liable for Post-Film Violence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER B. DALY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paramount Pictures and a movie theater can't be
held responsible for the death of a teen-ager stabbed by a young
man who had just seen a 1979 film about city gangs, the
Massachusetts Supreme Court has ruled.
   The victim's family sued Paramount and Saxon Theater Corp.,
seeking damages on the grounds of wrongful death. It charged that
Paramount and the theater knew ``The Warriors'' was inciting
violence around the country.
   Three days before the Boston slaying, according to court
records, two other youths were killed near theaters showing the
film in Palm Springs and Oxnard, Calif. That same week, Paramount
officers advised theaters showing the film to hire security guards
and offered to pay for them.
   The Massachusetts high court upheld the dismissal of the
family's lawsuit by a lower court on the ground that the
movie-maker and theater company had no ``special relationship'' to
the dead youth and therefore had no duty to protect him from his
attacker. In addition, the court rejected the family's contention
that ``The Warriors'' was an incitement to violence.
   ``Although the film is rife with violent scenes, it does not at
any point exhort, urge, entreat, solicit or overtly advocate or
encourage unlawful or violent activity on the part of viewers,''
Justice Francis O'Connor wrote. ``It does not create the likelihood
of inciting or producing `imminent lawless action' that would strip
the film of First Amendment protection.''
   William Yakubowicz filed the lawsuit in 1981 on behalf of his
dead son, Martin, 16. The youth was stabbed Feb. 15, 1979, at a
subway station several miles from the theater by Michael Barrett,
who was returning from seeing ``The Warriors'' at the Saxon Theater.
   Barrett, who sat through two showings of the movie, taunted
Yakubowicz on the subway, imitating a line from the movie _ ``I
want you, I'm going to get you.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
