<FIRST>r a PM-Deaths 1stLd-Writethru a0503 04-19 1190</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Deaths, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0503,1239</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS to UPDATE with Du Maurier, a0543, and Bond, a0522; another
PMs separate moved as a0485 on Berle, with LaserPhoto NY85.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Daphne du Maurier</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dame Daphne du Maurier, who became one of the
century's most popular writers by mixing romance and the
supernatural in ``Rebecca'' and other novels, died in her sleep
today at age 81.
   The author of such popular classics as ``Frenchman's Creek'' and
``The Birds'' died at her home in the village of Par, in Cornwall,
southwest England, said Monty Baker-Munton, her executor. He did
not know the cause of death.
   ``Rebecca,'' her most famous work, was published in 1938. It was
filmed starring Laurence Olivier and Joan Fontaine, and was
reprinted 39 times, selling more than 1 million copies in hard
cover alone.
   Born in London on May 13, 1907, du Maurier was one of three
daughters of the renowned actor Sir Gerald du Maurier. She was
educated by tutors in Paris and at 21 published her first articles
and short stories. Her first novel, ``The Loving Spirit'' in 1931,
captivated a young British army major, Frederick A.M. Browning, who
courted and married her in 1932.
   Widowed in 1965, du Maurier had for many years lived a secluded
existence on the wild Cornish coast that inspired the settings for
many of her works. She shunned publicity. She spent the better part
of her life writing best-sellers in Menabilly, the family mansion
on the Cornish coast.
   Baker-Munton said that at du Maurier's request her funeral would
be private, with no memorial service or flowers, and only close
family and friends attending. He said she would be cremated.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>David Bond</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Character actor David Bond, who appeared on
Broadway, in motion pictures and on some of the most popular TV
shows of the 1950s and '60s, died Sunday at age 74 of complications
from leukemia.
   Born Alfred Allegro, Bond appeared on Broadway in ``Othello''
and ``Accidentally Yours'' before moving west in the 1940s to make
motion pictures.
   He was seen in such films as ``The Late George Apley,'' ``The
Private Affairs of Bel Ami,'' ``Joan of Arc,'' ``The Great
Caruso,'' ``Julius Caesar'' and ``House Calls.''
   His television credits included regular appearances on such
series as ``Dragnet,'' ``The Twilight Zone,'' ``Dobie Gillis'' and
``The Untouchables.''
   Bond died at Humana Hospital in West Hills.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Ruth Berle</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ruth Berle, wife of comedian Milton Berle and
an active Democrat and philanthropist, died Tuesday at age 67.
   Mrs. Berle had suffered from cancer, said Tim Scerba, a
publicist for the 80-year-old comedian.
   Mrs. Berle began work in the public relations field in New York
in the 1940s, taking on work for motion picture studios such as
Samuel Goldwyn Productions, United Artists, RKO and Eagle-Lion.
   She met Berle in 1951 and they were married two years later.
   In 1968, she was a delegate from California to the Democratic
National Convention.
   Her philanthropic causes included S.H.A.R.E., an organization
working with mentally handicapped children.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Thomas McPherson Brown</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thomas McPherson Brown, author of a
controversial theory on the treatment and cause of rheumatoid
arthritis, died Monday following a long illness. He was 82.
   Brown was on the faculty of the George Washington University
School of Medicine in Washington for 22 years before he founded the
Arthritis Institute at the National Hospital in Arlington in 1970.
   He was best known for his promotion of antibiotic treatment of
rheumatoid arthritis, a disease that he believed is caused by a
type of bacteria. He said in a recently published book, ``The Road
Back,'' that antibiotics have been used to successfully treat
thousands of arthritis sufferers.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Masahiro Yoshino</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Masahiro Yoshino, an award-winning newspaper
columnist, died Tuesday after being beaten by two youths. He was 56.
   Masahiro Yoshino of the national newspaper Mainichi Shimbun, won
a Japan Press Club award in 1987 for his column ``Pieces from
Recent Events'' and an award of the Japan Newspaper Editors and
Publishers Association in 1964 for his coverage of organized
violence by gangsters.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Robert Ketter</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robert L. Ketter, a former president of the
state University of New York at Buffalo and director of the
National Center for Earthquake Engineering Research, died Tuesday
of a heart attack at age 60.
   Ketter served as university president from 1970 to 1982.
   After leaving his post as university president, he was
instrumental in the formation of the earthquake center,
headquartered at the school, and was a frequent spokesman on
earthquake construction.
   Ketter was particularly known for his view that a major
earthquake is due in the eastern United States.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Cecil Leeson</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MUNCIE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cecil Leeson, a music educator who was
widely credited with the rise of the saxophone from obscurity to
its status as a legitimate concert instrument, died Monday. He was
86.
   In 1937, Leeson was the first saxophonist to play New York
City's Town Hall in a performance that was the first major
saxophone concert in the country. He also was one of the first
musicians to experiment with recording music, and was one of the
first saxophone soloists to appear with major American symphony
orchestras.
   Leeson wrote original music, and more than 50 works for
saxophone were written for him by composers including Leon Stein,
Edvard Moritz, Paul Creston and Garland Anderson.
   The World Saxophone Congress in 1970 honored Leeson for 50 years
of pioneering and contributing to the establishment of the
saxophone in the field of music.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Edward M. Brecher</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CORNWALL, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Edward M. Brecher, a writer who once
argued in favor of the right to end one's life, was found dead at
his home Saturday in what was ruled a suicide. He was 77.
   In 1947, he became an associate editor of Consumer Reports and
four years later he joined the U.N. Technical Assistance
Administration as an editor. He worked mainly as a free-lance
writer since 1952.
   Brecher was the author of numerous books and articles on
medical, scientific and social subjects. For much of his career, he
collaborated on books and articles with his wife, Ruth Ernestine
Cook Brecher, who died in 1966. They received the Albert Lasker
Award for medical journalism in 1963.
   He wrote ``Opting for Suicide'' for The New York Times Magazine
in 1979 after he had contracted cancer of the colon the previous
year.
</TEXT>
<UNK>Mary Freemont-Smith_</UNK>
<DATELINE>NEWTON, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mary Freemont-Smith, an author, reporter
and nationally known tennis player in the 1920s, died Sunday after
a long illness. She was 92.
   Mrs. Freemont-Smith won the U.S. Eastern States Women's Singles
Championship in 1920, 1924 and 1927. She was also the Greater
Philadelphia Women's Singles Champion in 1919, 1923 and 1926, and
won the Ladies Singles Championship of Bermuda in 1924.
   In the 1920s she was ranked No. 7 among the nation's women
singles tennis players.
   She was a staff writer and reporter for several years for the
Philadelphia Bulletin. She also wrote several books, including
``The Child on His Knees,'' ``Foam'' and ``Songs of Youth.''
</TEXT>
