<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-89 1110EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Sudan-Relief 1stLd-Writethru a0415 04-19 0716</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sudan-Relief, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0415,0738</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bureaucracy, Slow Donations Hamper Sudan Relief</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 9 grafs to ADD attack on convoy. Pickup 6th graf
pvs, ``U.N. organizers...'' TRIMS thereafter.</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DALIA BALIGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bureaucracy, slow donor support, bad
planning and the civil war have forced organizers to scale down a
U.N. relief effort to save millions of people in the south from
starvation or malnutrition.
   Attackers on Tuesday ambushed the first convoy bringing supplies
to rebel-held southern Sudan, destroying the lead vehicle and
killing eight rebel escorts, U.N. officials in Nairobi, Kenya,
reported today.
   Even before the ambush, organizers said Operation Lifeline-Sudan
now expects to provide less than half the 100,000 tons of relief
goods believed to be necessary if a second consecutive summer
disaster is to be avoided.
   When the relief effort began April 1, the United Nations planned
to stockpile supplies at strategic points in southern and
southwestern Sudan for people escaping famine caused by the
6-year-long civil war in the region.
   Relief goods must be in place before the summer rains turn much
of the rural south into lakes and isolate areas where the refugees
gather.
   Almost three weeks after the starting date, no deliveries have
been made by trains or Nile River barge convoys, the project's bulk
carriers. Airlifts have been delayed because planes promised by the
United States and other Western donors have not arrived.
   Diane Weathers, a U.N. World Food Program spokeswoman, said the
14-truck convoy to the town of Torit was attacked Tuesday afternoon
14 miles west of a rebel base at Kapoeta.
   U.N. officials in Nairobi did not say who they believe was
responsible for the ambush, but they said it was unlikely rebels
were responsible because of the rebel escort.
   The officials said that overland route would be suspended but
other relief operations would move forward.
   U.N. organizers have given up their original goal of completing
the $132 million operation by the end of April and say it will
continue as long as allowed by the rains, which normally begin in
May.
   Food has been stored in some areas of the three southern
regions, but supplies in other towns are precariously low and the
possibility of replenishing them appears slim.
   Project director Bryan Wannop, local head of the U.N.
Development Program, insisted ``there are signs of momentum
gathering'' and expressed hope that half the 100,000 tons of food
and medicine would be within reach of 2.3 million southerners by
the end of April.
   Only about 26,000 tons are in the stockpiles now, he said.
   U.N. officials say 100,000 face starvation without emergency
supplies. Relief agencies estimated 250,000-500,000 southerners
died in 1988 from the war and the famine it created.
   To attract international attention, the U.N. Children's Fund
flew in actress Audrey Hepburn, its goodwill ambassador, and some
of the bad planning became evident.
   In Khartoum, she was driven around aimlessly for an hour by
escorts who had not been told her schedule.
   Operation Lifeline-Sudan sometimes appears to face an endless
list of problems.
   After promising two military C-130 transport for the airlift,
the United States backed out because American officers thought the
planes might be exposed to hostile fire.
   The Khartoum office of the U.S. Agency for International
Development said it would charter two of the cargo jets but there
is no indication when that will be done.
   Shortages of fuel have grounded available planes and disabled
trucks.
   Bureaucracy contributes to the bottlenecks with such policies as
requiring relief workers to obtain travel permits.
   Customs problems continue despite Prime Minister Sadek Mahdi's
promises at the March conference to eliminate them.
   Sudan's cumbersome bureaucratic pace was slowed even more by the
advent April 7 of Ramadan, the holy month when Moslems abstain from
food and drink in daylight hours.
   Khartoum and the rest of northern Sudan are Arab and
predominantly Moslem. The civil war grew out of demands by black
southerners, most of whom are Christians or animists, for autonomy
and a better economic deal.
   Richard Reid, regional director of UNICEF for the Middle East
and North Africa, said: ``There have been lots of disappointments:
that the donor community has been slow in responding, that the
military actions have not diminished, disappointments with the
logistical and mechanical obstacles.''
</TEXT>
