<FIRST>r a PM-SunkenShip     04-19 0298</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sunken Ship,0305</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coast Guard Searches for Two Men Missing Since Ship Sank Monday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE DREYFOUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two crewmen missing since their freighter sank
Monday morning might still be alive because the area they are
believed to be drifting in is warmed by the Gulf Stream, Coast
Guard officials said today.
   Twenty-three sailors were rescued after the Star of Alexandria
sank in story seas about 400 miles southeast of Cape Cod. A U.S.
Coast Guard cutter was to continue searching for the two men at
least through the day, said Petty Officer Jeff Crawley.
   On Tuesday, a search plane reported spotting one missing
crewman, but it was not clear whether he was alive. Crawley said
rescuers have not found any further sign of him.
   ``We feel they're still out there or else we wouldn't be
searching,'' said Chief Petty Officer Joe Gibson of the Coast
Guard's New York headquarters.
   Crawley said officials believe the men may still be alive
because of warm currents. One of the men was wearing a life jacket
when he was swept out of a life raft, survivors said. They said the
other man may have injured himself jumping from the ship.
   It was unclear what caused the ship to sink, said Petty Officer
Gary Rives.
   The Ravenscraig, a freighter, picked up the 23 multinational
crew members Monday after rescue planes spotted a lifeboat and a
life raft and guided the 950-foot vessel to them, Gibson said. An
empty life raft also was recovered.
   The men suffered only minor injuries.
   The 500-foot Star of Alexandria was bound for New York City from
Athens, Greece, when crew members reported about 9 a.m. that it
began taking on water in 12-foot seas and winds of 30-35 mph,
Gibson said.
</TEXT>
