<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--NASAResignation     04-19 0128</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--NASA Resignation,0129</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shuttle Expert Resigning To Join Aerospace Company</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HUNTSVILLE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leader of the team that redesigned
faulty space shuttle booster rockets is leaving the space agency to
join an aerospace firm.
   John Thomas, special assistant to the director of the Marshall
Space Flight Center, will become site director for Lockheed Corp.
at the Kennedy Space Center. Thomas, 52, has worked for the Natinal
Aeronautics and Space Administration for 28 years.
   He helped pinpoint a failed booster rocket seal as the cause of
the January 28, 1986, explosion that killed the seven-member crew
of Challenger. In May 1986, he was named manager of the program
that redesigned the boosters. The solid fuel rockets, with new
joint seals, have since flown successfully three times.
