<FIRST>u i PM-StadiumDisaster 2ndLd-Writethru   04-19 0736</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Stadium Disaster, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0512,0756</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Say Drunkenness Factor In Disaster; Coverup Charged</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to UPDATE with report of earlier arrests
for drunkeness. Pickup 5th, `To relieve...'' Inserts 2 grafs after 10th,
``None of...' with reax of Soviet player. Pickup 11th, `News reports...''
TRIMS.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WEST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A councilman in Liverpool said today that police,
who have largely blamed the weekend's soccer disaster on
hooliganism and drunkeness, are trying to cover up their own
incompetence.
   The charge came while police and government officials launched
inquiries to determine how a surging crowd was allowed to crush and
suffocate people at the soccer match, leaving 95 dead.
   The Times of London today quoted police officials as saying they
were disgusted by reports portraying Saturday's disaster at
Hillsborough stadium in Sheffield as a consequence of their failure
to control the crowd.
   Paul Middup, chairman of the South Yorkshire Police Federation,
the local police union chapter, claimed drunkenness contributed to
the uncontrolled crush of Liverpool fans outside the stadium just
as the match between Liverpool and Nottingham Forest was beginning.
   South Yorkshire police said today that some fans were arrested
before the game for public order offenses but refused to give any
details.
   To relieve the dangerous crush outside the stadium, police
ordered that a locked gate be opened. The fans poured into a
standing-room ``terrace'' area already crowded with other Liverpool
fans, and victims were trampled or crushed to death against a
10-foot-high steel-mesh fence.
   ``We are quite convinced that a lot of the fans _ many, many
hundreds of them outside that gate _ had been drinking very
heavily,'' he said on British Broadcasting Corp. television.
   Given the behavior police faced outside the stadium, Middup
said, ``I don't know what we are supposed to do and why it should
all be our fault.''
   He also said officers saw people picking up victims' belongings.
The Times said other police officers reported seeing Liverpool fans
picking the pockets of the dead.
   Liverpool City Council leader Keva Coombe called the police
allegations ``baseless, malicious and wicked'' and said they ``are
contradicted by the observations of thousands of people who were
present, from all sections of society.''
   ``None of these allegations were made at the time and any lawyer
will know that they have the hallmarks of an attempt to create a
cover story to cover for their incompetence,'' he said.
   In another development today, Soviet soccer star Oleg Blokhin,
who plays for an Austrian team, condemned the ``deplorable
conditions'' of the Sheffield stadium, the official Soviet news
agency Tass reported from Moscow.
   ``I believe it is an outright crime to pack spectators into
standing sectors like sardines in a can,'' Blokhin was quoted as
saying.
   The disaster has focused attention on England's antiquated
soccer stadiums and the riot fences located in standing-room-only
areas near the soccer goals. News reports have centered on
speculation the deaths may have been caused by the decision of
South Yorkshire police Supt. Roger Marshall to order the gate
unlocked.
   Nine survivors of Saturday's disaster are suing South Yorkshire
police and the owners of the stadium, alleging negligence.
   Police officials quoted by The Times expressed disgust at the
behavior of Liverpool fans as officers attended to the victims.
   The paper quoted one unnamed senior police officer as saying:
``As we struggled in appalling conditions to save lives, fans
standing further up ... were openly urinating on us and the bodies
of the dead.
   ``As policemen on the pitch tried to save the injured, they were
hampered by other Liverpool fans running up, kicking and punching
them,'' the officer said.
   On Tuesday, a senior judge, Sir Peter Taylor, began a
government-ordered inquiry into the disaster by touring the stadium.
   Taylor said it was too early to pinpoint major issues of the
inquiry but said he would look at the effect of liquor on the fans'
behavior.
   The death toll rose Tuesday to 95 with the death of a
hospitalized 14-year-old boy. Nineteen injured fans remained
hospitalized today, nine in intensive care, hospital officials said.
   British soccer fans have a reputation for violence _ rioting
Liverpool fans are blamed for Belgium's 1985 Heysel stadium
disaster when 39 mostly Italian fans died. As a result, rival fans
have been segregated and fenced in at Hillsborough and other
British grounds to keep them from fighting and running onto the
field.
</TEXT>
