<FIRST>r i PM-Iran-Iraq     04-19 0318</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iran-Iraq,0326</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Chief Arrives In Geneva For New Round Of Iran-Iraq Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HANNS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.N. Secretary General Javier Perez de Cuellar
arrived today to oversee a new round of peace talks between Iran
and Iraq, but negotiators for both sides said they are not prepared
to compromise.
   At an airport press conference, Perez de Cuellar acknowledged
that the adversaries are ``are still rather far apart'' but said it
is important to keep the eight-month process going.
   The two countries have been trying to work out a permanent peace
accord since they signed a cease-fire in August, ending eight years
of war that killed or injured at least 1 million people.
   Perez de Cuellar declined to predict the outcome of the new
negotiations. However, he said the mere fact that the foreign
ministers of Iran and Iraq agreed to come to Geneva showed their
interest in reaching an agreement.
   Before leaving Tehran early today, Iranian Foreign Minister Ali
Akbar Velayati said Iran would not yield in its demand that Iraq
first withdraw its troops from Iranian territory.
   Iran claims that Iraqi forces still hold 1,065 square miles of
Iranian territory. By U.N. estimates, however, only about 260
square miles remain under Iraqi control.
   On Tuesday, Foreign Minister Tariq Aziz of Iraq accused Iran of
sabotaging the talks by ``procrastination, maneuvering and
insincerity'' and warned that the negotiations ``could eventually
collapse.'' He was due in Geneva today.
   The talks are scheduled to start Thursday afternoon at the
Palais des Nations, the U.N. Office in Geneva, after separate
meetings between Perez de Cuellar and each of the two ministers.
The U.N. chief said the duration of the talks depended on the two
sides.
   Iraq has been pressing for early dredging of the Shatt-Al-Arab
waterway along the border. The channel, Iraq's outlet to the sea,
is clogged by sunken ships, weapons, and silt.
