<FIRST>r w PM-Shoreham-IRS 1stLd-Writethru a0446 04-19 0357</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Shoreham-IRS, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0446,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>IRS Approves Plan for Writeoff to Mothball Controversial Nuke Plant</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs lead to CORRECT by deleting reference to action before
licensing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Long Island Lighting Co. expects to write
off about $2.8 billion in losses if shareholders approve a deal to
scrap the controversial Shoreham nuclear power plant.
   The utility announced Tuesday that it had received permission
from the Internal Revenue Service to deduct such losses. The IRS
had earlier permitted such a deduction under a deal that collapsed
last year.
   The IRS ruling came one day after the Nuclear Regulatory
Commission staff reported that the $5.5 billion plant meets all
federal safety requirements and is ``operationally ready.'' NRC
Chairman Lando Zech tentatively set a vote on the full-power
license for Thursday and all indications are the license will be
granted.
   However, the action may be largely symbolic. Under the latest
shutdown plan, LILCO has agreed not to put the license to use until
its shareholders vote on the negotiated settlement with the New
York state Public Service Commission, the New York and Long Island
Power Authorities, and LILCO's board of directors.
   Under the new agreement, Shoreham would be sold to the state for
$1 in exchange for a decade of annual rate increases of up to 5
percent to ensure financial stability for the company.
   The shareholders must vote on or before June 15, and LILCO
Chairman William J. Catacosinos told the NRC Monday that the
utility's board will recommend that shareholders approve the deal.
   LILCO and the state would then seek to have Shoreham's license
transferred to the Long Island Power Authority. The New York Power
Authority would oversee decommissioning and dismantling of the
plant.
   The plant was begun more than 20 years ago and finally completed
in 1985. Opponents have battled it, with both New York and Suffolk
County officials refusing to participate in emergency planning.
   The state and county officials contended that no emergency plan
would have been workable on Long Island, where the plant is
situated, because of the geography, highway system and population
concentration.
</TEXT>
