<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-89 1208EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Britain-OilRig     04-19 0347</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Oil Rig,0357</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Field Shut Down After Explosion on Rig</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A North Sea oil field was closed following a gas
leak and explosion at a Shell platform that forced evacuation of at
least 170 workers and halted production of 472,000 barrels of oil a
day, the company said today.
   A spokeswoman for Shell U.K. Exploration and Production said
there were no injuries in Tuesday's explosion on Shell's Cormorant
Alpha platform.
   She said the affected Brent field produces about a quarter of
the British sector's daily oil production.
   Shell U.K. Exploration and Production is the unit of the Royal
Dutch-Shell Group of Companies that operates the Brent oil
production and transport system.
   The Brent system, which is made up of seven platforms, including
Cormorant Alpha, was producing 472,000 barrels of oil a day that
moved through the Cormorant Alpha platform to a loading terminal
off the coast of Scotland, Shell said.
   The Cormorant Alpha platform itself produces 40,000 barrels a
day.
   The leak on the Cormorant Alpha platform, which lies about 100
miles northeast of Lerwick in Shetland, occurred during
installation of an emergency shutdown valve.
   A Shell spokesman said he didn't know how long the field would
be shut down. He said an investigation into the cause of the
explosion was under way.
   A spokesman with Britain's Department of Energy said the
department would issongress-Oil Spill. Developing.
   By H. Josef Hebert. LaserPhoto upcoming; LaserGraphic NY11.
</TEXT>
