<FIRST>u a PM-TerroristThreat 1stLd-Writethru a0534 04-19 0307</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Terrorist Threat, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0534,0311</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newspaper: Atlantic City Police Prepared For Possible Terrorist Attack</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS 3 grafs with Casino Association comment.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two men believed to be planning a terrorist
attack on Atlantic City have prompted a full-scale alert by state
and local police, a newspaper reported today.
   The Star-Ledger of Newark, citing unidentified sources in the
casino industry and law enforcement, reported that the FBI advised
local authorities that the men were being dispatched from an
unspecified Arab country to launch a terrorist assault on an
unspecified target in Atlantic City.
   The attack reportedly was to be a retaliation against the United
States for its April 14, 1986, bombing of Libyan leader Moammar
Gadhafi's headquarters. The attack killed Gadhafi's infant daughter.
   Sources told the newspaper that the terrorists were supposed to
be traveling from New York to the casino resort with accomplices
ready to help them escape through Mexico.
   The ``operating window'' for the assault was reported to be
April 14 through April 20 _ Thursday.
   State Police Superintendent Col. Clinton Pagano refused to
confirm or deny the alert.
   However, marked State Police cars have taken up positions on the
three main entrance roads into Atlantic City and nonuniformed State
Police detectives strengthened their surveillance at the city's 12
casinos, the newspaper reported.
   The FBI and Atlantic City Police Chief Joseph Pasquale would not
comment.
   ``The industry has no comment on any law enforcement activities
in and around Atlantic City,'' said Thomas Carver, president of the
Atlantic City Casino Association.
   Carver refused to say whether casinos had beefed up security or
police had added patrols. He would not speculate on the effects the
newspaper report would have on visitors.
   ``I think the weather has more to do with the attendance in
Atlantic City that anything else,'' Carver said.
</TEXT>
