<DOCNO> AP890419-0100 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-89 1234EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r k BC-EditorialRdp 3Takes   04-19 0915</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Editorial Rdp, 3 Takes,0954</SECOND>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are excerpts from recent editorials in newspapers
throughout the nation.
   April 18
   Los Angeles Times on House Speaker Jim Wright:
   House Speaker Jim Wright (D-Texas) stands accused by the House
Ethics Committee of 69 violations of the rules, including an
alleged ``scheme to evade'' the limits on outside earnings.
   To be sure, Wright has only been accused. He has not been
convicted of anything. But that is not the point. The point is that
as a leader of the House, Wright has failed the ... standards of
ethical conduct (that Congress set) for its members.
   By failing that test, Wright has broken the bond of trust and
confidence he needs to continue as an effective officer of the
House. ...
   Wright should resign his speakership now. ...
   These are not idle charges. If they were, 12 members of the
Ethis Committee _ six Democrats and six Republicans _ would not
have voted unanimously to issue its report finding reason to
believe Wright violated the rules. ...
   Most important to him, Wright said, is to defend his personal
reputation and personal honor. ... But only by resigning the
speakership can he conduct that battle without paralyzing the work
of Congress for weeks and months to come.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   April 18
   St. Louis Post-Dispatch on President Bush's education proposals:
   For someone who wants to be known as the education president,
George Bush has pretty feeble proposals in his first education
budget.
   Both in his inaugural address and again last week, the president
declared that the nation has more will than wallet, but when it
comes to making progress in education, Washington will have to open
its wallet wider than ... Bush proposes.
   The administration's education package has worthwhile goals. ..
. Unfortunately, to pay for these aims, the president proposes $441
million _ not much by Washington standards and certainly not enough
to make a dent in any of his targeted areas, much less in all of
them.
   Instead of throwing pennies at such problems, ... Bush would be
better advised to restore some of the cuts made by the Reagan
administration. ...
   But if ... Bush wants to make his mark on education, he will
have to rethink how much the nation can spend on improving its
schools _ and whether it can afford not to.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   April 12
   Aberdeen (S.D.) American News on the minimum wage:
   When we first considered the minimum wage issue, we thought it
was obvious that the wage should be raised. After reading articles
from several sources, however, we discovered there is no easy
answer. ...
   An American Economics Association survey found that 90 percent
of its members agree that a minimum wage increase results in more
unemployment among young and unskilled workers.
   These jobs will be lost because employers will decide to have
fewer employees since their wages will be higher. ...
   The worst part of this situation is that those the higher wage
is intended to help _ those with the fewest job skills _ will be
the first to be unemployed. ...
   It is impossible to tell those earning minimum wage that they
are making enough money, but the decision may easily turn into a
choice between a low-paying job or no job. Either way, no one wins.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   April 12
   The News-Review, Roseburg, Ore., on housing policies:
   There is ample evidence that Secretary Jack Kemp's Department of
Housing and Urban Development is fostering a new and important
spirit of cooperation with Congress. ...
   For instance, ... Kemp has expressed great interest in a
comprehensive housing bill introduced in the Senate earlier this
month with broad bipartisan support. ...
   HUD's new policies emphasize the importance of helping
low-income families to work actively toward solving their own
housing problems, rather than being the passive recipients of
federal largesse.
   Part of (Kemp's) master plan is the creation of federal
enterprise zones to attract businesses to poverty-stricken inner
cities and rural areas. ...
   Another important part of the overall housing plan is the
concept of urban homesteading, which enables people living in
public housing to buy their own homes. ...
   HUD is now working on a plan to provide temporary accommodation
for the homeless in unused federal buildings throughout the nation.
...
   These common-sense policies bring self-respect, dignity, and
above all, hope, to a section of the population which too often
finds itself trapped in a cycle of despair and poverty.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   April 12
   Bridgeton (N.J.) Evening News on the Oliver North trial:
   It's a bit ironic that while he blustered with great macho
before Congress ... (Oliver North) now plays the part of a meek
little thing who knew what he did was ``wrong but didn't know it
was illegal.'' His crocodile tears now ... are a bit hard to
believe.
   There is no doubt, however, that Oliver North, macho or crybaby,
is the fall guy in the Contra case.
   While it's true that others are still to be tried, the top of
the administration, such as former President Ronald Reagan, has
wiggled out of it. The same might be said for President ... Bush,
who, while not a major villain in the case, apparently had some
involvement.
   (North) probably didn't know that his blind loyalty would leave
him holding the bag. But the choice was his and none of his
powerful friends will step forward to serve his time or pay his
fines if he is convicted.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
