<DOCNO> AP890419-0102 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-89 1241EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r k BC-EditorialRdp 2ndAdd   04-19 0912</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Editorial Rdp, 2nd Add,0951</SECOND>
<HEAD>UNDATED: larger culprits.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   April 17
   The Milwaukee Journal on the British soccer tragedy:
   A soccer match, a time for recreation and merriment, instead
turned into a maelstrom, as nearly 100 persons were killed in the
crush of spectators at a match Saturday in Sheffield, England.
   The episode teaches important lessons about both the importance
and danger of sports, and it demonstrates the need for measures to
prevent a recurrence.
   It occurred as fans surged forward in overcrowded stands. The
victims were crushed and suffocated in a ``terrace,'' or
standing-room-only pen, at the end of the stadium. Thousands of
eager, excited fans had gathered at the stadium hoping to watch the
game. ...
   For too many Britons, sports is also something to fight about.
English soccer clubs were banned from European tournaments in 1985
after 39 people were killed in Belgium when backers of a British
team rioted during a match with an Italian team.
   If U.S. sports has been marred by drugs (and, now, possibly,
gambling), British soccer has been marred by violence.
   While hooliganism in the stands has been an occasional problem
during football, baseball and other games in this country, crowd
control is taken seriously by most big-time sports executives here,
as it should be. It obviously needs to be taken more seriously in
Britain.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   April 18
   Topeka (Kan.) Capital-Journal on the British soccer tragedy:
   The carnage is senseless, and the immediate reaction to such
devastation is to seek out someone to blame.
   The finger has been pointed first at the guards who opened the
gates to the fans. Certainly hindsight raises questions about their
decision, although there is evidence that the decision was made out
of fear of a similar crunch at the turnstiles.
   England has demonstrated the ugly consequences when crowds get
out of hand.
   The lesson should serve as a reminder that patience is important
in wait-your-turn situations. It also should make officials
involved in such operations re-examine the way crowds are handled
and accommodated.
   It may save lives.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   April 17
   The Morning News Tribune, Tacoma, Wash., on Pentagon procurement:
   The conviction ... of two Teledyne Electronics executives for
their roles in the Pentagon procurement scandal sends a clear,
strong signal to other corporation officials: They will be held
accountable when they know about wrongdoing and allow it to
continue.
   The executives, found guilty of conspiracy and wire fraud, face
long prison sentences _ up to 40 years _ and large fines.
Prosecutors argued that the two were aware a consultant was paying
a Navy procurement official for inside information that led to
Teledyne landing a $24 million contract.
   The significance of the conviction, according to assistant U.S.
attorney Joseph Aronica, is that it tells executives ``they cannot
put things into motion and feign ignorance and attempt to wash
their hands of guilt.''
   Although the company itself already has agreed to pay $4.3
million in penalties, this kind of corruption can best be addressed
by holding the top people personally accountable. Shareholders end
up footing the bill for fines; prison time, however, is a real
attention-getter.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   April 17
   Hattiesburg (Miss.) American on school drinking water:
   A report on the safety of school drinking water released last
week by the Environmental Protection Agency gives every one of us
reason for concern. Federal studies suggest that water from at
least 10 percent of faucets in each school contains high lead
levels; 20 parts per billion poses a health risk.
   What's more, the EPA said at least 1 million lead-contaminated
drinking fountains may be operating in U.S. schools _ some with up
to 400 times the amount of lead considered safe by the EPA.
   The culprits are old and new plumbing and drinking fountains
that are lead-lined or have lead solder. The danger is particularly
great in fountains or faucets that are used intermittenly and thus
allow the water to stand in the pipes, as in the case in schools.
The EPA is recommending that at least some of the fountains in
every school in the nation be tested. ...
   This is a potentially serious problem, but it is a problem that
can be dealt with. The answer lies in testing those fountains now
and taking quick action to remove any that reveal dangerous levels
of lead.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   April 14
   Owatonna (Minn.) People's Press on smokers suing tobacco
companies:
   Smokers who die from lung cancer and their survivors may sue
tobacco companies, the Minnesota Supreme Court has ruled. ...
   That is not to say these suits have particular merit, however,
or that the plaintiffs should be awarded any damages.
   John Forster, 46, died of lung cancer in 1985, but not before
suing R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Co. for causing his cancer.
   The truth of the matter is that John Forster had 25 years of
warnings before he finally died of cancer. ...
   R.J. Reynolds took certain actions that may have led to his
death, it's true. But so did John Forster. There is an element of
personal responsibility here.
   Perhaps it was not his fault that he became addicted. To be
sure, it is not his widow's fault. We would not deny him or his
family human compassion.
   But we cannot use lawsuits to vent our frustrations or anger at
the hand we are dealt in life, or the hand we draw.
   We make mistakes, and we live with them _ and sometimes, sadly,
we die with them.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Editorial Rdp</NOTE>
