<DOCNO> AP890419-0105 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-89 1243EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Hitler     04-19 0751</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hitler,0774</SECOND>
<HEAD>Media Stumble Through Presentation of Notorious Centennial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West German media have stumbled
through an awkward observance of Adolf Hitler's birth 100 years
ago, reflecting a hesitance among many to come to grips with the
once-revered Fuehrer.
   The unsavory anniversary has been noted in a disjointed series
of newspaper portraits, historical analyses and opinion polls that
explain only pieces of the phenomenon that brought death for
millions during World War II and the Holocaust, and the enduring
division of Europe.
   One radio network in Hesse state planned a discussion of
residual right-wing extremist tendencies for Thursday's anniversary
of Hitler's birth in the Austrian village of Braunau, on West
Germany's southern border.
   But other media seemed more poised to react to expected
demonstrations by the neo-Nazi fringe than to put the occasion into
perspective for a nation still branded by crimes committed before
many people were born.
   The ZDF television network announced two months ago it would not
have any documentaries on the anniversary, which it said was ``not
the right day to remember a criminal.''
   Newspapers and magazines across the entire political spectrum
have made virtually no mention of plans by neo-Nazi leaders like
Michael Kuehnen to celebrate Hitler's centennial.
   Federal officials in the capital have been careful to avoid
discussion of the infamous occasion.
   Interior Ministry spokesman Michael-Andreas Butz was asked what
steps federal forces have taken to ensure the safety of potential
targets of neo-Nazi actions. ``We have taken adequate precautions
where needed,'' he replied, declining to elaborate.
   Among the press reviews of Hitler's role in German history, the
most comprehensive and critical analysis has been offered by Der
Spiegel magazine.
   The glossy weekly devoted its April 10 cover and 20 pages to try
to explain ``The terrorist of the century'' and how he has affected
today's Germany.
   Spiegel published in detail the results of a nationwide opinion
poll conducted in March by the respected Emnid Institute of
Bielefeld.
   Responses by the 2,200 West Germans polled indicated widespread
uncertainty about how to assess Hitler, as well as some worrisome
indications of latent anti-Semitism and positive views toward the
dictator.
   An astounding 38 percent of those polled replied ``yes'' to the
question: ``If not for the war and the Holocaust, would Hitler have
been a great German statesman?''
   The poll also revealed that 46 percent of the respondents, said
by the Emnid Institute to represent accurately West German voters,
consider the Third Reich to have had some positive influences.
   Asked to evaluate their attitude toward Jews in West Germany, 18
percent described their views as negative and 33 percent chose zero
on the scale that ranged from minus 5 for very negative attitudes
to plus 5 for very positive.
   The complex bundle of nationalist feelings carried by many West
Germans was illustrated by reaction to the statement ``I am proud
to be a German,'' to which only 27 percent of the respondents fully
agreed.
   The poll also suggested that most West Germans believe the
division of Germany is permanent, and that more than two thirds of
the respondents would like to be done with ``the past.''
   Quick, a weekly picture magazine, also carried a photo essay on
Hitler and his legacy, with similar poll results indicating strong
pockets of right-wing extremism in West Germany and substantial
numbers of citizens _ 18 percent _ who believe their nation was
better off under the Third Reich.
   Frankfurter Rundschau newspaper reported a few days earlier that
two West German journalists have written the first book since the
fall of the Nazi dictatorship to examine how the German press aided
Hitler's rise to power and his march through Europe.
   Other prominent newspapers carried recent articles by historians
and jurists recounting Hitler's dictatorship and contrasting it
with a recent rise in ultra-rightist politics.
   The left-leaning magazine Tempo reported Wednesday it had
learned of plans by extremists to break windows at Jewish-owned
businesses, send aloft a helium balloon emblazoned with the
forbidden swastika and to lay a wreath at the Moenchengladbach
birthplace of Nazi propaganda minister Josef Goebbels.
   Tempo spokesman Carl-Eduard Meyer told The Associated Press the
magazine decided to report the details to alert possible victims,
not to inform would-be agitators.
   Austrian police prepared to seal off access to Hitler's
birthplace in the village of Braunau to prevent incidents.
   But Butz, the West German Interior Ministry spokesman, said
police reported only throngs of journalists at the scene as of
midday Wednesday.
</TEXT>
