<FIRST>r w PM-Bush-Jordan 3rdLd-Writethru a0561 04-19 0862</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Jordan, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0561,860</SECOND>
<HEAD>EDS: Inserts new grafs 14-15 with briefing on meeting, picks up 15th
graf pvs: Jordan's role xxx</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Calling for ``fresh thinking'' on resolving
the Middle East conflict, President Bush said today that he and
Jordan's King Hussein agreed to work toward the structuring of a
``serious negotiating process'' to achieve an Arab-Israeli
settlement.
   Bush issued the statement after a meeting of more than an hour
with Hussein.
   The two then traveled by helicopter to Mount Vernon, Va., for a
tour of the home of George Washington and a boat ride on the
Potomac River.
   With Hussein standing at his side, Bush said, ``His Majesty
committed Jordan to this task and I commit the United States to
this task.''
   ``The time has come to encourage fresh thinking, to avoid
sterile debate and to focus on the difficult but critical work of
structuring a serious negotiating process,'' he added.
   Bush said that during the meeting he reaffirmed his view that
``properly designed and mutually acceptable elections'' in the West
Bank and Gaza Strip could, as an initial step, help lead to
negotiations on the final status of the territories.
   He added that the United States remains committed to bringing
about a comprehensive settlement through negotiations based on U.N.
resolutions which establish the principle of peace for Israel in
return for Israeli withdrawal from occupied territories.
   Hussein, in turn, praised the United States for opening a
dialogue with the Palestine Liberation Organization and said that
this, coupled with the PLO's renunciation of terrorism last
December, had improved prospects for peace.
   He expressed hope for more flexibility on Israel's part.
   ``Peace can neither be negotiated nor achieved without PLO
participation,'' Hussein said.
   Both leaders expressed support for the concept of a United
Nations-sponsored conference on Middle East, with Bush emphasizing
the long-standing U.S. view that any such conference should
facilitate direct negotiations between the parties.
   Earlier, while the two posed for photographers in the Oval
Office, Hussein was asked whether the time is ripe for a
breakthrough in the peace process.
   ``I believe it is,'' he said. ``It's never been as ripe as now.''
   Before the talks, Bush was hopeful that Hussein would show
interest in an Israeli proposal for ending the negotiating impasse
through elections in the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Asked whether his optimistic statements meant he was supporting
the Israeli plan, Hussein said, ``Not necessarily.''
   Later, a senior administration official said Hussein ``certainly
did not rject the idea'' of Palestinian elections in the occupied
territories.
   The official, who declined to be identified, said Hussein
expressed ``some concerns'' about the Israeli proposal but ``felt,
however, reassured and encouraged about the directions'' after Bush
and Secretary of State James A. Baker III explained the U.S.
approach.
   Jordan's role in the Middle East peace process has diminished
considerably since last summer, when Hussein severed administrative
and legal ties with Palestinians living in the West Bank.
   But a senior U.S. official who briefed reporters on Tuesday said
Jordan's proximity to the West Bank makes a Jordanian role in
resolving the Palestinian issue inevitable.
   ``There is no way in the world that one can conceive of a peace
process moving forward without the active involvement of King
Hussein,'' said the official, insisting on anonymity.
   After a morning meeting with Bush and a luncheon with Vice
President Dan Quayle, Hussein was to be guest of honor at a White
House dinner tonight. Meetings with congressional leaders also were
on his schedule.
   Two weeks ago, Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir proposed
during a visit here that Palestinians in the West Bank and Gaza
Strip elect representatives to negotiate with Israel on limited
self-government.
   The Bush administration has endorsed the proposal on the
condition that the elections lead to negotiations on the final
status of the two territories.
   The senior U.S. official said the proposal represents an attempt
to end the impasse in the Arab-Israeli conflict.
   ``We're talking about trying to get things off dead center,
which is where we find the situation in the Middle East at the
present time,'' the official said. ``And we see, in the elections
proposal, depending on how it is developed and fleshed out, the
possibility of turning a situation from a conflict situation to one
of greater political dialogue.''
   The Palestine Liberation Organization has expressed support for
elections only if they are preceded by the withdrawal of Israeli
troops.
   The senior official described Hussein as a ``valued friend'' of
the United States and noted that the administration has proposed an
increase in military sales to Jordan from $10 million to $48
million next year. Economic assistance would rise from $15 million
to $35 million.
   Jordan administered the West Bank until 1967, when Israel seized
the territory during the Middle East war. But until last summer,
Jordan continued to play a dominant role in the area, paying the
salaries of thousands of municipal employees there and funding a
sizeable aid program.
   Hussein's decision to dismantle Jordan's ties with the West Bank
was widely interpreted as a challenge to the PLO, which has long
demanded total control of the territory.
</TEXT>
