<FIRST>r a PM-Ship-Boardwalk     04-19 0210</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ship-Boardwalk,0217</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cruise Ship Hits Boardwalk</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADEIRA BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A cruise ship rammed into a
boardwalk, crunching a 35-foot section and damaging a waterside
restaurant.
   No injuries were reported in Tuesday's accident, which sent
dozens of people scrambling to safety.
   It was the second time in two months that a ship owned by Europa
Cruise Line Inc. was involved in an accident in the same area.
   ``There was mass hysterics,'' said Tom Murphy, who was sitting
with his family at the Fisherman's Landing restaurant when they saw
the ship headed for them. ``I said: Everybody, let's get out of
here,' and we just dove out of the way.''
   Seconds later, their corner table was crushed beneath pilings
and planks. The Europa Sun pulled away from the boardwalk and
docked safely within a few minutes.
   Europa officials said strong currents contributed to the crash,
just as they said currents contributed to a March 11 accident
involving the Sun's sister ship, the Europa Star. That accident
damaged a commercial fishing boat.
   The Coast Guard found no mechanical problems with the vessel and
allowed it to leave on an evening cruise a few hours later, Coast
Guard Lt. Charles Brantley said. An investigation should take about
a week, he said.
</TEXT>
