<FIRST>u i PM-Germany-Bomb     04-19 0567</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Germany-Bomb,0581</SECOND>
<HEAD>Third Bomb Found In Germany; Possible Link To Flight 103</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said today that a third
bomb has been found in the investigation of two alleged Palestinian
terrorists and that the case may be linked to the bombing of Pan Am
Flight 103.
   The federal Parliament's news service said in a brief report
that the latest bomb discovered in the probe was hidden in a
television set in an apartment in the Duesseldorf suburb of Neuss.
   ``There is a possible connection between the bomb found
(Thursday) and the crash of the jet over the Scottish city of
Lockerbie on Dec. 21,'' the news report said without elaborating.
No one answered the telephone at the Parliament information office
tonight when the AP called for more details.
   The bomb was found by police in a followup search of the
apartment Thursday, said Alexander Prechtel, spokesman for the
federal prosecutor's office in Karlsruhe. But he said suggestions
linking the Palestinian case and the Pan Am bombing that killed 270
people are ``nothing but speculation.''
   The bomb discovered in the television set was seized from the
same apartment where two other explosive devices disguised to look
like electronics equipment were found last week, Prechtel said.
   One of those bombs, hidden in a radio, blew up Monday at the
Wiesbaden headquarters of the federal police force while two
disposal experts were trying to disarm it. Officer Hans-Juergen
Sonntag, 35, died of his injuries from the blast, and a 29-year-old
colleague who has not yet been publicly identified remained in
critical condition at a Frankfurt hospital today.
   An employee of the federal police force, the Bundeskriminalamt,
said there was no one available tonight to answer questions about
the case.
   The Palestinians, alleged members of the Popular Front for the
Liberation of Palestine-General Command, were arrested in October
in what police called the biggest weapons bust in the nation's
history.
   British investigators probing the Pan Am bombing over Lockerbie,
Scotland, have said the plane was blown up in the sky by plastic
explosives hidden in a radio-cassette player.
   A radio-bomb containing the same Czechoslovak-made plastic
explosives was among the weapons seized during the October raid,
and authorities confirmed that the bomb that blew up Monday also
appeared to have been hidden in a radio.
   The Pan Am investigation has been handled by West German
officials with extreme caution because of persistent British and
U.S. media reports saying that the bomb was planted on the aircraft
in Frankfurt.
   Asked about the Parliament news service report, Prechtel
disputed its suggestion that the probe of the two suspected agents
of the Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine-General
Command has turned up indications those suspects were involved with
the Lockerbie disaster.
   ``I know about that being said, but that is nothing but
speculation,'' he said. ``They can't say it's not connected, so
they speculate that it is. But we have no evidence that it is
connected to Lockerbie _ only the theoretic possibility exists.''
   Police arrested 14 suspects in the October raids but only two,
Hafez Kassem Dalkamoni and Abdul Fattah Ghandanfar, remain in
custody.
   Prechtel said authorities expected to file charges against the
two within a few months. They are suspected of forming terrorist
cells in West Germany, illegal possession of weapons and bomb
attacks on U.S. military trains in August 1987 and April 1988,
Prechtel said.
</TEXT>
