<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Taiwan-China     04-19 0195</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Taiwan-China,0201</SECOND>
<HEAD>300 Chinese Seeking Better Jobs Caught in Taiwan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Security forces this year have caught 300
mainland Chinese who sneaked into Taiwan in search of a better
life, the Defense Ministry said Wednesday.
   Lt. Gen. Lee Chen-lin, deputy chief of the armed forces general
staff, told the lawmaking Legislative Yuan all of the Chinese were
sent back to China on fishing boats they used to enter Taiwan after
officials determined they weren't spies.
   Most of the Chinese were caught after authorities received
reports from villagers of suspicious strangers, he said.
   On Tuesday, police reported the arrest of 58 Chinese who said
they came to Taiwan to look for jobs.
   Taiwan is suffering from an acute labor shortage, and a worker
can earn the equivalent of $555 a month, compared with about $25 in
China.
   Lee said there also has been an increase in the number of
Chinese fishing boats that have entered Taiwan's territorial waters
since July 1987 when the Nationalist government ended 38 years of
martial law.
   The Nationalists, defeated in a civl war on the China mainland
in 1949, are technically still at war with the Communists.
