<HEAD>Protestant Man Found Killed; Catholic Wounded in Attack</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with ID of slain man. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nephew of a Protestant
militant who turned police informer was found shot to death today,
and gunmen seriously wounded a Roman Catholic man in another part
of city, police said.
   Authorities declined to speculate on whether the attacks were
linked, and no group immediately claimed responsibility for them.
   A passerby found the body of Francis Galbraith on the edge of
Victoria Park near the shipyards of East Belfast, police said. He
had gunshot wounds in the head. Galbraith, 29, was a nephew of Joe
Bennett, a former high-ranking officer in the outlawed Ulster
Volunteer Force, police said.
   Bennett, who left Northern Ireland after turning state's
evidence against 16 suspected paramilitary associates in 1983, is
serving a prison sentence in England for armed robbery. Fourteen of
the men were convicted on a range of charges including murder, but
all were freed on appeal.
   Police said the shooting of the 24-year-old Catholic man by two
unidentified gunmen in a side street off north Belfast's Antrim
Road bore the hallmarks of an attack by militant Protestants. The
victim was not identified.
