<FIRST>r i PM-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru a0540 04-19 0651</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0540,0672</SECOND>
<HEAD>Christian Legislators Urge Cease-Fire; Aoun Reportedly Rejects It</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 4 grafs after 6th graf pvs, ``I was...'' to UPDATE with
French efforts to reach cease-fire. Pickup 7th graf pvs, ``In Beirut...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A newspaper said today that the army
commander opposed a call by Christian parliamentarians to halt
weeks of fighting between Moslem and Christian gunners.
   Battles raged through the night. However, no new casualties were
reported from the exchanges between Gen. Michel Aoun's 20,000
Christian army units and an alliance of Syrian and Druse forces.
   By police count, 270 people have been killed and 975 wounded
since the current round of hostilities broke out March 8.
   The French navy ship Rance, carrying 78 wounded in the Lebanon
fighting, arrived in Larnaca, Cyprus, today. The casualties were
being flown from Cyprus to Paris for treatment.
   French sailors carried the wounded down a gangplank to
ambulances. The patients, lying under white sheets, crossed their
arms over their eyes to block the brilliant Mediterranean sunshine.
   ``I was sitting at home and a shell just smashed into our
house,'' said Hammed Khalil, a 22-year-old student from Beirut
University College. He suffered a fractured shoulder.
   In Paris, President Francois Mitterrand was calling world
leaders in an effort to generate international pressure for a
cease-fire.
   Mitterrand spoke Tuesday with President Bush, Prime Minister
Margaret Thatcher of Britian, President Chadli Bendjedid of Algeria
and President Hosni Mubarak of Egypt. He planned to speak later
today with Chancellor Helmut Kohl of West Germany and Prime
Minister Felipe Gonzalez of Spain.
   France has encouraged U.N. Secretary General Javier Perez de
Cuellar to make a trip to Syria or Tunisia to negotiate a
cease-fire, officials said.
   The French take a special interest in Lebanon because they ruled
it from the end of World War I until independence in 1943.
   In Beirut, a police spokesman said an unidentified assailant
fired a rocket-propelled grenade overnight at the residence of
Christian parliamentary deputy Edmond Rizk in Christian east Beirut.
   The grenade damaged Rizk's apartment, but no casualties were
reported, said the spokesman.
   The attack came a few hours after Rizk, a Maronite, read a
statement issued by 23 Christian legislators demanding a cease-fire.
   It did not set a deadline for the proposed truce but said Aoun's
army would be ``responsible for implementing it in areas under its
control...and the Syrian army would be responsible for implementing
it in its areas of deployment and control.''
   Beirut's daily paper An-Nahar, in a front-page report, said Aoun
opposed the cease-fire. Aoun was quoted as saying in response to
Rizk's statement: ``The people are best represented by the people.
Ask the people.''
   An-Nahar said Aoun, a 53-year-old Maronite, believes that
parliamentary deputies ``do not represent the people.''
   Lebanon's unicameral 99-seat house was elected in 1972 for a
four-year term. The civil war, which erupted in 1975, has prevented
parliamentary elections, and only 75 of the seats are filled.
   Acting Prime Minister Salim Hoss, who heads the Moslem Cabinet
in Lebanon's dual government, welcomed the statement by the
Christian parliamentarians, saying he hoped it ``would lead to
further positive steps.''
   Aoun, who heads the Christian Cabinet, has rejected several
cease-fire appeals because they did not include direct reference to
Syria's 40,000 troops as a main party to the present conflict.
   An-Nahar said Aoun ``insists that the battle is against
Damascus.''
   A Christian government source, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said Aoun was prepared to ``accept a security committee
to oversee a cease-fire only if it included a Syrian
representative.''
   The cease-fire call also was rejected by the Lebanese Forces
alliance of right-wing Christian militias.
   ``One cannot compare between freedom and humiliation,'' the
militia said in a statement. ``Our right in regaining our freedom
and sovereignty is sacred.''
   The latest battles broke out shortly after Aoun ordered a
blockade of Moslem militia-run ports.
</TEXT>
