<FIRST>r a AM-BRF--FreeRent     04-19 0190</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Free Rent,170</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Offered Free Rent to Live in Public Housing Projects</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FAIRFAX, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fairfax County officials hope a plan to
offer free rent to police who agree to live in public housing
projects will help fight drug activity in the units.
   Housing officials fear a crackdown on drug dealers in nearby
Washington, D.C., will drive illegal drug trade into the county.
``We saw the increased drug activity in the district and were
concerned about the spillover into our public housing,'' said Mary
A. Stevens, spokeswoman for the county housing department.
   ``Several months ago, we felt the need to develop a program.
This is an ongoing response, and if we can think of something good
tomorrow, we'll add it to our list,'' she added Tuesday. She said
at least one police officer has moved into one of the 900 public
housing units.
   The housing authority began hiring off-duty officers in October
to patrol the grounds of the projects, at a cost through February
of $38,000. Housing officials have asked the county supervisors to
approve $250,000 to hire more off-duty officers and improve
security around the complexes.
