<FIRST>u i PM-Obit-DuMaurier 3rdLd-Writethru a0543 04-19 0842</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Du Maurier, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0543,0868</SECOND>
<HEAD>Daphne du Maurier, Famed Romance Novelist, Dead at 81</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs graf 11, `She spent...' to clarify that family did not
own mansion. Subs graf 19, `The story...' to CORRECT that story is about
woman, not man. Pickup 20th graf, `Histories, biographies...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCUS ELIASON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dame Daphne du Maurier, who became one of the
century's most popular writers by mixing romance and the
supernatural in ``Rebecca'' and other novels, died today. She was
81.
   Monty Baker-Munton, a family friend, trustee and executor, said
he did not know the cause of death. ``For the last fortnight (two
weeks) she'd just been in a gentle decline,'' he said.
   The author, who also wrote such popular classics as
``Frenchman's Creek'' and ``The Birds,'' died in her sleep at her
home in the village of Par, in Cornwall, southwest England,
Baker-Munton told The Associated Press.
   Baker-Munton said that at the novelist's request, her funeral
would be private, with no memorial service or flowers and only
close family and friends attending. He said the venue was not being
disclosed.
   He said she would be cremated.
   Widowed in 1965, Mrs. du Maurier for many years lived a secluded
existence on the wild Cornish coast that inspired the settings for
many of her works.
   She remained fit enough until a few weeks ago to take her dog
for daily walks at the beach.
   Friendly and kind to her neighbors, she shunned publicity.
   ``She was a wonderful person with a great sense of fun. She
never took herself too seriously. There was no grandeur about her
famousness,'' said Baker-Munton's wife, Maureen, who knew her 44
years.
   ``I can't say I really like people,'' Mrs. du Maurier once
remarked. ``Perhaps that's why I always preferred to create my own
instead of mixing with real ones.''
   She spent the better part of her life producing bestsellers in
Menabilly, the mansion on the Cornish coast where the family lived.
   Many of her novels were filmed, including ``The Birds,''
directed by Alfred Hitchcock. But she herself waited until the age
of 64 before consenting to face a television interviewer.
   Born in London on May 13, 1907, Daphne du Maurier was one of
three daughters of the renowned actor Sir Gerald du Maurier.
   She was educated by private tutors in Paris and at age 21
published her first articles and short stories. Her publisher told
her: ``Write a novel,'' so she produced ``The Loving Spirit'' in
1931.
   The novel captivated a young British army major and led to a
storybook courtship.
   The officer, Frederick A. M. Browning, resolved to meet the
author and journeyed to Par to find her. They met in 1932, married
a few months later, and in the same year she published her second
novel, ``I'll Never Be Young Again.'' She was just 25.
   ``It was rather woman's magazine-y,'' she remarked afterward.
   ``Jamaica Inn,'' another hit, followed in 1936, and then came
``Rebecca,'' her most famous work. Published in 1938, it became an
instant hit, was turned into a film by Hitchcock starring Laurence
Olivier and Joan Fontaine, and was reprinted 39 times, selling more
than 1 million copies in hard cover alone.
   The story is about a young woman who marries an enigmatic
widower and moves to his large country house, where she discovers
that mystery surrounds his first wife's death. Trying to solve the
mystery against the wishes of a sinister housekeeper, she is drawn
into a terrifying psychological labyrinth.
   Histories, biographies, two plays and more novels followed, and
altogether six of her novels were filmed.
   Browning became commander of British Airborne Forces in World
War II and then treasurer to Prince Philip, husband of Queen
Elizabeth II.
   Lady Browning, as she became known when her husband was made a
lord, wrote much of her work at Menabilly, the ancient Georgian
manor the couple rented.
   Menabilly inspired Manderley, the name of the mansion in
``Rebecca.'' Oliver Cromwell's troops gutted the house during the
English Civil War, and legend had it that a cavalier was bricked up
alive in one of Menabilly's gray stone buttresses.
   Her favorite hideaway was a gardener's hut, where, she said,
``I'd sit for hours on end, chain-smoking, chewing mints and
tapping away at my typewriter.''
   Angular, sharp-eyed, usually wearing slacks and sweaters, she
would prowl the grounds of Menabilly or answer stacks of fan mail.
   After her husband died in 1965, she lived alone at Menabilly
except for two Yorkshire terriers. Her son and two daughters
visited frequently.
   In 1969 the queen made her a Dame Commander of the Order of the
British Empire, entitling her to call herself Dame Daphne.
   That year she had to leave Menabilly when its owner returned,
and she rented Kilmarth, her home in Par. There she wrote ``The
House on the Strand.''
   Menabilly still stands and is inhabited.
   In 1971 she published ``Not After Midnight,'' a collection of
five novellas containing her special mix of romance and the eerie.
   In 1981 she published an autobiography, ``Growing Pains.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
