<FIRST>r w AM-EnergyPolicy     04-19 0307</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Energy Policy,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Group Urges Creation of Special Energy Agency</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration should create a
special agency to steer high-priority energy projects, such as
power plant or pipeline construction, around legal and regulatory
obstacles, an energy organization said Wednesday.
   In a broad assessment of American energy prospects, the United
States Energy Association said the special agency could enhance the
nation's energy security by eliminating what it called
unnecessarily long lead times for major projects.
   It said the agency could be fashioned along the lines of the
energy mobilization board proposed by then-President Carter as part
of a 1979 energy program. The board was never created.
   Jack Bowen, first vice chairman of the energy association, said
in presenting the proposal to the group's annual meeting that a
mobilization board would enable project developers to sidestep
unnecessary legal and regulatory obstacles.
   ``What it means is that no one can kill you with regulatory
delays,'' he said. ``It goes up or down on its merits. The lawyers
may not like it, but it's something we've got to do.''
   Bowen's group is comprised of about 100 private and public
energy-related organizations whose members represent virtually
every segment of the energy industry.
   Among the group's other recommendations:
   _Develop an integrated national energy strategy.
   _Increase energy conservation, encourage greater energy
efficiency and expand the use of renewable energy sources.
   _Increase domestic oil and natural gas production and increase
the use of natural gas and coal as a means of reducing the nation's
reliance on foreign oil.
   _Encourage the construction of nuclear power plants.
   Henson Moore, the Energy Department's deputy secretary, said in
a speech to the association that the department was moving to
fashion a comprehensive energy strategy but that it might not be
ready by the target date of April 1990.
</TEXT>
