<HEAD>State Department Condemns Slaying of El Salvador Official</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department condemned the
assassination of El Salvador's attorney general on Wednesday as a
``brutal, despicable killing'' and charged that the act was
designed to provoke further violence.
   ``We condemn this terrorism,'' said State Department spokeswoman
Margaret Tutwiler.
   The official, Roberto Garcia Alvarado, was assassinated by
unidentified assailants as he drove to his office in the capital of
San Salvador. A bomb was placed on the roof of Garcia's Jeep
Cherokee when it stopped at a traffic light.
   Although Ms. Tutwiler noted no one had claimed responsiblity for
the attack, she said leftist guerrillas battling the U.S.-backed
government have ``engaged in many acts of terror in recent months.''
   ``This brutal, despicable killing follows by five days the
bombing attack upon the home of Vice President-elect (Francisco)
Merino,'' Ms. Tutwiler said, adding that bombing injured a child in
the home.
   Ms. Tutwiler said such attacks amounted to ``a campaign of
terror against the people and democratic instutitions of El
Salvador.
   ``We condemn this terror, as should all civilized peoples and
nations. This campaign is clearly designed to provoke a violent
reaction,'' she said.
