<FIRST>r a PM-MoneyLaundering     04-19 0336</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Money Laundering,0344</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defendant Pleads Guilty In Money Laundering Scheme</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The major defendant in a money-laundering
case that includes the Yugoslav consul general in Chicago and a
U.S. branch of a major Yugoslav bank faces up to 75 years in prison
and a $7.25 million fine.
   Hubert Francis Cole, 44, of Carrollton, Texas, pleaded guilty
Tuesday to charges of conspiracy to defraud the United States,
failure to fie currency reports and violating arms export
regulations.
   Cole, a self-described financial consultant, also pleaded guilty
to attempting to launder $2 million in cash he was waiting to pick
up at Philadelphia International Airport when he was arrested Dec.
1.
   The government, in return for Cole's agreement to cooperate with
the investigation and testify, dropped charges of money laundering
and interstate travel in aid of racketeering.
   U.S. District Judge Jan E. DuBois did not set a date for
sentencing.
   Also charged in the case are: Bahrudin Bijedic, the Yugoslav
consul general in Chicago; Vjekoslov Spanjol, a naturalized U.S.
citizen from Plano, Texas; Vinko Mir of New York, chairman of the
board of LBS Bank of New York Inc., the U.S. branch of a major
Yugoslav bank; and the bank itself.
   The defendants are charged for their alleged participation in a
scheme to launder $1.4 million supplied by undercover agents posing
as mobsters in 1987 and 1988. Bijedic allegedly supplied consular
seals that prohibited officials from examining bundles of cash.
   On Monday, U.S. Attorney General Dick Thornburgh asked that a
federal judge privately review surveillance tapes of conversations
between Bijedic, Mir and Spanjol. Thornburgh argued that public
disclosure of the tapes would harm national security since they
contained ``sensitive information concerning United States
intelligence sources and methods.''
   In December, Cole and Spanjol were denied bail after prosecutors
played a tape recording made by an undercover customs agent in
which Cole boasted of his ability to tap into the computers of
defense contractors.
   Cole also described Spanjol as the second-ranking Yugoslavian
intelligence agent in the United States.
</TEXT>
