<FIRST>r i AM-Chess     04-19 0512</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chess,0527</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kasparov Wins Adjourned Game, Moves a Half-Point Behind Ljubojevic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOODMAN</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BARCELONA, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   World chess champion Garri Kasparov won
his adjourned 16th round game Wednesday in the Chess World Cup and
closed to a half-point of the leader, Ljubomir Ljubojevic of
Yugoslavia, with one round left.
   In the endgame, Kasparov, playing black, outmaneuvered Spanish
grandmaster Miguel Illescas. Facing an unstoppable checkmate,
Illescas resigned.
   With the 17th and final round scheduled for Thursday, Ljubojevic
has 10{ points out of a possible 15 and may become the first player
in 7{ years to score more points than Kasparov in a competition.
   Kasparov, 26, is in second place with 10 points. Another Soviet
grandmaster, Valery Salov, is third with 9{ points.
   ``Before the tournament the big question was whether Kasparov
would put in a wonderful performance and push his rating above
Bobby Fischer to become the highest ranked player in history,''
said Leontxo Garcia, a Spanish chess commentator. ``Now the
question is whether Kasparov will be able to catch Ljubojevic.''
   In the final round, Ljubojevic, 38, will play with the
disadvantageous black pieces against British grandmaster Nigel
Short, the third-ranked player in the world, while Kasparov will
face off with white against former world champion Boris Spassky of
France.
   But Kasparov is likely to face difficulties in facing Spassky,
who has the reputation of one of the hardest players to defeat. A
win scores one point and a draw a half point.
   The World Cup, a series of six tournaments held over two years
featuring a prize fund of $1.2 million, is regarded as the second
most important event in chess after the individual world
championship.
   Each of 25 eligible grandmasters plays in four of the six
competitions. The Barcelona event is fourth in the cycle.
   Kasparov won the second and thrid events in Belfort, France, and
Iceland, and is leading the competition. Former world champion
Anatoly Karpov, who won the first tournament in Brussels, Belgium,
is in second place.
   If Kasparov defeats Spassky and Ljubojevic only draws with
Short, they will tie for first place in the tournament.
   But a draw in his game Thursday will be enough to give
Ljubojevic a victory in the separate World Cup points table,
because Illescas is only competing in Barcelona as a representative
of the host country and is not eligible for the World Cup.
   When the World Cup calculations are made, all results against
Illescas will be taken out. Ljubojevic, who drew Illescas in the
eighth round, will have a half-point deducted from his final score,
and Kasparov will lose a whole point.
   Kasparov has trailed in Barcelona from the start. He scored only
two draws in his first three games, going down in the third round
to Soviet grandmaster Artur Yusupov.
   In the other game completed Wednesday, Alexander Belyavsky of
the Soviet Union defeated U.S. grandmaster Yasser Seirawan.
   The final round will feature a battle between Salov, 24, and
Viktor Korchnoi, a 58-year-old Soviet defector who plays for
Switzerland. Korchnoi is fourth with nine points, a half-point
behind Salov.
</TEXT>
