<FIRST>r a AM-People     04-19 0638</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People,0667</SECOND>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Capitol Records won the right to begin
exclusive distribution of a new ``comeback'' album by Donny Osmond
in a court dispute between the record company and another record
producer.
   Former Lt. Gov. Mike Curb, head of Curb Records, had contended
he gained exclusive rights to distribute the song ``Soldier of
Love'' and other songs Osmond recently recorded.
   But U.S. District Judge Robert Takasugi ruled Tuesday that a
March 6 agreement gave Capitol the right to distribute the new
album.
   Distribution will begin this week, said Capitol attorney Howard
King.
   He argued Osmond's attempt at a music comeback would be
jeopardized if distribution were delayed.
   Osmond, as part of the Osmond Brothers and later with his
sister, Marie, became a teen idol in the 1970s with such songs as
``Puppy Love,'' ``I'm Leaving It All Up to You'' and ``Paper
Roses.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SOUTH BEND, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former baseball Commissioner Peter
Ueberroth, who failed in a bid to buy Eastern Airlines, will
deliver the commencement address May 21 at the University of Notre
Dame.
   Ueberroth will receive an honorary doctor of laws degree during
the ceremonies marking the university's 144th graduation day.
   The honorary doctor of laws degree will be the first granted by
Notre Dame to a secondary school teacher, university president
Edward A. Malloy said Wendesday.
   Notre Dame will also grant an honorary degree to Karen McKibbin,
who teaches chemistry and biology at LaSalle High School in South
Bend and was selected Indiana's teacher of the year for 1989.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amid emotional scenes, the audience at London's
Covent Garden Royal Opera House welcomed back Spanish tenor Jose
Carreras after his recovery from leukemia.
   The audience rose and cheered Tuesday night as Carreras, 42,
appeared on stage for a two-hour song recital. The crowd demanded
encore after encore, stamped and applauded and showered the stage
with flowers.
   Carreras, who says he is fully recovered and ``100 percent
perfect,'' was clearly affected by the warmth of his reception.
   His leukemia was diagnosed in 1987. At one time doctors gave him
a 10 percent chance of recovery, but after bone marrow transplants
and chemotherapy he was pronounced fit and made his comeback before
150,000 opera lovers in Barcelona last July.
   Carreras, who now devotes part of his income to an international
foundation he has set up to fight leukemia, bowed out with a
bouquet of red roses presented on stage by Royal Opera chief Jeremy
Isaacs.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>OWENSBORO, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six-year-old Barbara Bush can't yet read,
but she recognized the signature of the first lady when a letter
arrived from the White House.
   ``She was just tickled to death,'' said the child's grandmother,
Doretta Bush.
   The Owensboro youngster wrote first lady Barbara Bush in March
after studying in school about who lives in the White House. On
Friday she received a reply.
   Barbara can write her name, but she can't read yet, said Terri
Hanley, home-school coordinator at Foust Elementary School, where
Barbara attends kindergarten.
   To compose her letter, Barbara dictated its contents to her
teacher, Judy Dixon. The child then copied the letter and mailed it
and a photograph to Mrs. Bush.
   What did she say to the first lady?
   ``I love her,'' Barbara said. ``She's sweet and pretty.''
   She also told Mrs. Bush she hopes they can meet one day.
   Mrs. Bush's letter read: ``Dear Barbara, How much I appreciated
your nice message of support and friendship. Your words mean so
much to the President and me. We are both very grateful.''
   It was signed: ``Warmly, Barbara Bush.'' A personal message was
handwritten across the bottom: ``How wonderful to have the same
name. I loved your picture.''
   Barbara said she knows that the first lady works. Her
occupation? ``Shopping,'' Barbara said.
</TEXT>
