<FIRST>r w AM-PublicBroadcasting     04-19 0600</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Public Broadcasting,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Public Broadcasting Helps Fight Social Ills, Head Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Public broadcasting is a highly cost-effective
way of helping solve national problems, Corporation for Public
Broadcasting officials said Wednesday in defending a request for
increased program funds and money to replace an aging satellite.
   Corporation president Donald Ledwig told a House Appropriations
subcommittee that every dollar of federal funding to the
organization now attracts nearly $6 in donations in corporate and
audience donations.
   Ledwig also cited educational programs on public radio and
television and the 13,000 hours a year in programming for the
classroom that now reach 101 million TV viewers and more than 10
million radio listeners each week.
   ``Now is not the time to retreat,'' he said, when ``the public
looks increasingly to public broadcasting to meet its needs for
quality programming.''
   He said that each federal dollar spent on an AIDS awareness
program, for example, ``might save this committee thousands of
dollars treating that patient.''
   The Corporation for Public Broadcasting is a private, nonprofit
organization created by Congress to support public broadcasting. It
passes on about 71 percent of its operating budget to public radio
and television stations. It gets its federal money two years in
advance and is seeking $265 million for fiscal 1992.
   The Bush administration wants to freeze the corporation's
appropriation at the 1991 level of $242 million and not provide any
new money to replace a 10-year-old satellite that is expected to
die in 1991.
   Congress has authorized $200 million for the satellite, but has
appropriated just $56.8 million of that amount, in 1991.
   Ledwig said failure to replace the satellite would have a severe
impact on programming funds that would have to be diverted to
satellite construction.
   He also said congressional support for the full $265 million
request ``is critical if CPB is to continue to increase the high
standards of public broadcasting and to tap deeper into the
potential that it holds for addressing many of this nation's most
pressing problems.''
   If the budget is frozen _ which means a cut, when inflation is
counted _ the corporation loses the $6 in donations for each dollar
cut, Ledwig said.
   Federal funds ``are the key dollars that bring in the others''
he said.
   Outlining something of a domino effect, Ledwig said that if the
corporation's budget is cut, ``We start losing quality of the
programming, we start losing audience, and we start losing
contributions.''
   The three subcommittee members in attendance each praised public
broadcasting, but said it would be very difficult to increase
spending given the current federal budget pinch.
   Subcommittee chairman William Natcher, D-Ky., asked how Ledwig
could justify a request for a 9.5 percent spending hike.
   Ledwig said the corporation was ``acutely aware'' of the
competing demands on Congress for federal dollars.
   ``I believe, however, that federal support for public
broadcasting is one of the most cost-effective means to address a
number of critical problems facing the nation today.''
   He said the corporation's 4.3 percent for administrative costs
was the lowest of any agency in the government.
   Rep. Neal Smith, D-Iowa, said he thought public broadcasters may
be trying to mimic commercial television by paying high salaries to
on-air personalities and $15,000 appearance fees to guests.
   Smith was particularly concerned that Louis Rukeyser, host of
the popular ``Wall Street Week'' program, was being paid in six
figures.
   ``Can you justify giving sombody three times as much salary ...
than we pay a Supreme Court justice?'' Smith asked.
   Ledwig said the show does not receive any funds from the
corporation.
</TEXT>
