<FIRST>r i AM-SAfrica-Violence     04-19 0256</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SAfrica-Violence,0265</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fourteen More Killed in Black Factional Conflict</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five days of factional
fighting in Natal Province has killed 14 blacks, including four who
were ambushed by gunmen after getting off a bus, police and
witnesses said Wednesday.
   More than 1,200 people have died during fighting between black
factions since mid-1987, according to local groups. They say 165 of
those victims were killed in the first three months of this year.
   Six people were killed Tuesday night in Shongeni Valley between
the southeastern cities of Durban and Pietermaritzburg, the
provincial capital, police said without providing details.
Journalists saw three of the bodies.
   Two men and two women were killed Monday night in Taylor's Halt,
a township outside Pietermaritzburg, police also said.
   Witnesses and families said those victims had just alighted from
a bus when gunmen sprang from the bush and fired at them. They said
several other people were wounded.
   Residents said a man and a 13-year-old boy were shot in the same
area Monday night and two other teen-agers were shot to death in
their home outside Pietermaritzburg on Friday.
   The main combatants in the fighting are the banned United
Democratic Front, the country's largest anti-apartheid coalition,
and Inkatha, the political group of Zulu leader Mangosuthu
Buthelezi.
   Both groups oppose apartheid, but their tactics differ. The
front favors protests, boycotts, sanctions and other
confrontational methods that Inkatha does not endorse.
   Some anti-apartheid activists accuse Buthelezi of collaborating
with the white-run government because he participates in the black
homeland system.
</TEXT>
