<FIRST>r i AM-Walesa     04-19 0554</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Walesa,0571</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pope Expresses Hope for Poland as Walesa Arrives in Rome</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY BETH SHERIDAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II prayed for Poland on Wednesday as
Lech Walesa, his Solidarity union made legal again by the communist
government, arrived to seek economic aid for his country and thank
the pontiff for his help.
   At his public audience, John Paul said in a prayer for success
of his homeland's new political course:
   ``I pray to you, Lady of Jasna Gora ... the country will have
new possibilities and that transformations will take place in the
social, political, economic and moral life of the entire society.''
His reference was to Poland's holiest shrine.
   Solidarity, which Walesa founded in 1980 as the Soviet bloc's
first independent trade union, regained official status Monday.
   Walesa had a symbolic reconciliation Tuesday with the Polish
leader, Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski, who declared martial law in
December 1981 to crush Solidarity.
   At Leonardo da Vinci Airport, he told reporters: ``There is a
great accord between society and the government. It is a political
victory for all of us in Polish society, but for this victory to be
complete we now have to take care of real issues and to get down to
work together.''
   The Polish government agreed in two months of negotiations with
an opposition delegation led by Solidarity to legalize the union
and create a freely elected Senate as a second house of the Sejm,
or parliament.
   Poland hopes the result will be financial help from the West and
Solidarity's cooperation in confronting the national economic
crisis.
   Walesa met with Bishop Fiorenzo Angelini, chief of the Vatican
medical mission, and thanked him for aid the office gave Solidarity
medical programs. Angelini pledged another $30,000.
   Later, Walesa attended a crowded Mass celebrated by four Polish
bishops at St. Marian in Trastevere church. As the faithful
received communion, two people unfurled a red-and-white Solidarity
banner.
   The Solidarity leader has said he wants to encourage Western aid
for Poland during his three-day visit to Italy, which includes
meetings with politicians and labor leaders.
   In John Paul's first public comment on the legalization of
Solidarity, the pontiff prayed Wednesday that all involved in
Poland's new political course would ``continue to demonstrate the
courage, wisdom and calm indispensable to serving the public good.''
   Addressing the Madonna of Jasna Gora, he said: ``Today I want to
thank you, oh Mother, for all the good that has grown from the
experiences of that period'' when Solidarity was suppressed and
outlawed.
   ``I give to your maternal care Solidarity, which today, after
the new legalization of April 17, can return to activity.''
   Walesa said he would ask John Paul on Thursday ``to give his
blessing to this difficult task of reform'' and said the pope ``has
always been with us.''
   John Paul warmly endorsed Solidarity when he met Walesa in
January 1981 at the Vatican. The pontiff and the shipyard
electrician met again during papal trips to Poland in 1983, the
year Walesa won the Nobel Peace Prize, and 1987.
   The church is a major force in Poland, a devoutly Roman Catholic
country despite its communist government, and church
representatives participated in the negotiations.
   In a clear illustration of Solidarity's change in status, the
Polish ambassador to Italy met Walesa at the airport.
</TEXT>
