<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-89 1628EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon     04-19 0541</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon,0559</SECOND>
<HEAD>Aoun Says U.S. Not Doing Enough to Stop Fighting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Christian army commander, Gen. Michel
Aoun, said Wednesday the United States was involved in ``a
conspiracy of silence'' by failing to halt Syrian attacks on
Lebanon's Christian heartland.
   Aoun addressed about 1,200 Christians who braved intermittent
rocket and artillery barrages and marched to the presidential
palace in suburban Baabda to support Aoun's ``war of liberation''
against Syria's 40,000 troops in Lebanon.
   Christian parliamentarians have called for a cease-fire in the
fighting with the Syrians and their Druse Moslem militia allies.
   But the demonstrators rejected the suggestion, highlighting a
split in the Christian camp. The demonstrators burned an effigy of
Syrian President Hafez Assad and chanted ``Death to Assad!''
   Police say 270 people have been killed and 975 wounded since the
latest round of fighting flared March 8. Most victims have been
civilians.
   Several rounds of rocket and mortar fire struck Christian east
Beirut and Moslem west Beirut on Wednesday, but there were no
reports of casualties.
   Only a handful of people ventured outside, and radio stations
said the relative calm was no more than a ``warriors' rest.''
   ``America's secretary of state says the United States is
incapable of doing anything to help Lebanon. This is the plot.
America is not incapable, but America is taking part in a
conspiracy of silence regarding the destruction of Lebanon by
Syria,'' Aoun said.
   He was commenting on Secretary of State James A. Baker III's
remarks Tuesday before the Senate Foreign Relations Committee.
Baker said: ``We make a lot of statements and sometimes it is
frustrating to think that is really about all we can do.
   ``I don't know what else, frankly, we can do. We have scant
influence with the Syrians,'' Baker said.
   Aoun said sarcastically, ``Maybe Syria has become so powerful
that America is scared of it.''
   In Washington, State Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler
said the United States would support ``any efforts'' by U.N.
Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar to help negotiate a
cease-fire.
   France, which has close ties to the Lebanese and ruled the
country until 1943, suggested Perez de Cuellar travel to Syria or
Tunisia to work out a cease-fire. The U.N. chief said he was not
considering any such initiative as long as efforts by the 22-member
Arab League continue.
   The latest hostilities broke out after Aoun ordered a blockade
of militia-run ports that deprive the treasury of $100 million a
year in tax revenue.
   Druse warlord Walid Jumblatt retaliated by shelling the
310-square-mile Christian enclave. The Syrians later joined the
shelling.
   Beirut and its surroundings have been without electricity since
Sunday, when power plants ran out of fuel oil. The stations also
have been severely damaged in the bombardments.
   Water supplies also have stopped. Bread and other vital
commodities have become scarce. The shortages and shelling have
forced thousands of people to flee to south and east Lebanon or
leave the country altogether.
   The French navy ship Rance carried 78 severely wounded Lebanese
to Larnaca, Cyprus, on Wednesday. Fifty-three of the casualties
were flown to Paris aboard a special French hospital plane. The
others needed another day of quiet before they could be moved,
doctors said.
</TEXT>
