<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-89 1910EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-US-Israel     04-19 0396</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Israel,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chairman of House Panel Questions Aid to Israel Because of Shootings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of a House foreign operations
panel on Wednesday questioned U.S. aid to Israel in light of
incidents in which Israeli soldiers have shot fleeing Palestinian
demonstrators in the back.
   ``When is that stupid practice going to end?'' asked David Obey,
D-Wis., who heads the House Subcommittee on Foreign Operations,
which appropriates foreign aid money.
   ``I don't want to take responsibility for giving one dime to a
country whose military forces are firing at people in retreat,''
Obey said angrily at a hearing on the Bush administration's 1990
aid request for Israel and other Middle Eastern countries.
   It is rare for a congressman to make such bluntly critical
comments in public about Israel.
   The administration is asking to maintain the same level of aid
to Israel _ $3 billion, the most of any foreign nation.
   Obey said he had raised his concerns with the Bush
administration and with Israel and all he had received were
``words.''
   A State Department official who handles U.S. ties with the
Middle East, Deputy Assistant Secretary of State Ned Walker, said
the administration continues to urge Israel to stop the practice.
``We're not satisfied,'' he said.
   But Walker also expressed sympathy for the Israeli soldiers,
saying he had been in the Israeli-occupied Gaza Strip and seen them
having to deal with violent Palestinian demonstrators. ``It's
difficult for them,'' he said of the soldiers.
   More than 400 Palestinians have been killed in a violent
uprising launched 17 months ago to protest Israel's 21-year rule of
the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Walker praised some recent Israeli measures such as the release
of more than 450 Palestinian inmates, the unsealing of some houses
blocked by Israeli forces as punitive measures, and the restoration
of loudspeakers to Arab mosques. But he said Israel's ``record is
still mixed,'' as shown by last week's shooting by security forces
of at least five Palestinians in the West Bank village of Nahalin.
   Israeli military regulations allow soldiers to shoot plastic
bullets at demonstrators fleeing the scene of a violent
demonstration. Israeli spokesmen say plastic bullets are less
lethal than other ammunition, but dozens of Palestinians have been
killed _ some shot in the back _ because soldiers fired from closer
than the required distance.
</TEXT>
