<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-89 1911EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-HomelessMarch     04-19 0529</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Homeless March,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Coalition Announces Plans for Huge October Demonstration</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 60 national organizations announced
plans Wednesday for a huge march on Washington Oct. 7 to demand
more federal housing assistance for the nation's homeless.
   ``This isn't a march so much as it is a calling forth of the
human spirit,'' declared a tearful Valerie Harper, the actress and
longtime homeless activist. ``It's an expression of who we are as
human beings.''
   She addressed a marathon news conference at which dozens of
prominent civil rights, labor, church and anti-poverty leaders
announced the creation of a ``Housing Now!'' umbrella organization
and plans for the march in October.
   At least 63 nationwide organizations are participating. They
include the AFL-CIO, the U.S. Conference of Mayors, the YWCA of the
United States, the Southern Christian Leadership Conference, the
National Urban League, the National Organization for Women, the
National Senior Citizens Council and the National Rainbow
Coalition, headed by The Rev. Jesse Jackson.
   Barry Zigas, a principal organizer of the march and president of
the National Low-Income Housing Coalition, predicted that
``hundreds of thousands'' of people would participate.
   Famed homeless activist Mitch Snyder noted that ``I was 6 years
old when Congress passed legislation calling for safe and
affordable housing for all Americans. Well, I'm 45 now. And it's
time to remind one another that the wealthiest nation on Earth has
the resources, but simply lacks the will, to get the job done.''
   Alexandria, Va., Mayor James P. Moran Jr., speaking for the U.S.
Conference of Mayors, blamed the homeless problem on the
abandonment of the federal housing assistance policies of the 1960s
and 1970s. ``If we had continued those policies,'' he said, ``about
1.8 million more households would be receiving housing assistance _
or enough to accommodate 4 million people. It's no coincidence that
there are 3 million homeless in this country,'' he declared.
   Since 1981, budget authority for all federal housing assistance
programs has been cut by more than 75 percent _ from $32 billion to
less than $8 billion a year, according to the new coalition. It
said only about 1 out of every 4 eligible poor renters actually
receives a federal housing subsidy.
   Moran noted also that the Department of Housing and Urban
Development estimates than more than 24 million people spend more
than half of their income on housing. ``That's a disgrace,'' he
said.
   The joint ``call to action'' issued by the coalition complained
that ``Congress hides behind the budget deficit when it comes to
housing our people. We call on Congress to recognize housing as the
immediate national priority it must become.''
   ``We cannot deny,'' said actor Jon Voight, ``that wherever we
step, we step over a human being lying helplessly in our streets.
Unless we act now, our streets will be littered with them.''
   ``We are sitting on our hands, and more and more people are
suffering,'' said Louisa Stark, president of the National Coalition
for the Homeless. She cited a recent MIT study which indicated that
by the year 2,000, there will be an estimated 19 million homeless
Americans, barring a change in policy.
</TEXT>
