<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-89 1911EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Elderly-Drugs     04-19 0575</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Elderly-Drugs,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>HHS Official Says Medicare Computer System Could Guard Against Drug
Reactions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new prescription drug benefit program being
readied for 32 million Medicare beneficiaries offers a golden
opportunity to include safeguards against adverse reactions that
hospitalize at least 200,000 elderly people a year, witnesses told
a House panel Wednesday.
   Richard Kusserow, inspector general for the Department of Health
and Human Services, told the committee that it would be ``stupid''
for Congress to be so insistent on enforcing an arbitrary deadline
for setting up a computer-based billing system that it closes off
the possibility of building in the safeguards.
   The idea, he said, is to program the Medicare computer system
that will link the nation's pharmacies so that the pharmacist
filling a doctor's prescription will be able to tell on the spot
whether the patient is taking another drug that could react with
the new one.
   Some private pharmacy chains already use such programs, often
citing them in advertising as a reason to shop at a particular
pharmacy.
   Kusserow was called before the subcommittee of the Select
Committee on Aging to elaborate on a study that has found the
Medicare program paid at least $500 million in 1987 for hospital
admissions that were related to an adverse prescription drug
reaction or an overdose.
   He told the panel that is a conservative figure because
hospitals do not always flag drug reaction cases in the records
they submit for Medicare reimbursements.
   Preliminary results from the report released previously found
that the elderly account for 200,000, or 39 percent, of all
hospitalizations from drug reactions and half of deaths from such
reactions.
   Kusserow, who has referred to the situation as ``America's other
drug problem,'' said he is concerned that the Health Care Financing
Administration is feeling so much congressional pressure to meet
have a prescription drug billing system up and running well before
the 1991 startup of the program that it will design a system that
precludes adding computerized crosschecks of various medications a
Medicare beneficiary may already be taking.
   ``I think that would be stupid and I would hate to see that
happen,'' he said.
   Beginning in 1991, Medicare will pay 50 percent of drug costs
after a $600 annual deductible. The government payment rises to 60
percent the following year and 80 percent in 1993 _ also after a
$600 deduction.
   Suggesting that Congress was not entirely clear in the
instructions it gave HCFA on how to set up a national system to
keep track of Medicare drug claims, Kusserow said, ``My concern is
that we will rush ahead to create a data base driven solely by
financial record-keeping concerns and neglect the quality of care
issue.''
   Heading off drug reactions before they occur would save money in
the long run by cutting down hospitalization costs for treating the
victims of such episodes, he said.
   Almost all adverse prescription drug reactions stem from
patients not properly following directions for taking the medicine
or taking different medicines that can react with each other _
either drugs they are prescribed by different physicians or by a
single physician who doesn't know any better.
   Food and Drug Administrator Frank Young supported Kusserow in
calling for a HCFA computer system that provides a way to
crosscheck prescriptions.
   ``We think this is a golden opportunity,'' said Young. ``We fear
it may be implemented without including a way to do this.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
