<FIRST>r a AM-CruseSentencing     04-19 0436</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cruse Sentencing,0447</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Weighs Life Or Death For Shopping Center Killer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IKE FLORES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BARTOW, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prosecutor asked jurors Wednesday to
reject defense claims of temporary insanity and recommend the death
penalty for a man convicted of killing six people in a shopping
center shooting spree.
   William Cruse left ``a killing field'' behind him in the two
Palm Bay shopping centers where he also tried to kill 24 others in
1987, State Attorney Norm Wolfinger told jurors.
   ``May God have mercy on the defendant's soul for his cruel and
atrocious and uncaring acts,'' Wolfinger said in his final
argument. ``Evidence has shown that this defendant has forfeited
his right to live on Earth.
   ``He is a cold, calculating killer. He deserves to die.''
   Cruse demonstrated that he was in total control of his mental
faculties when he methodically tracked down and shot at his victims
repeatedly, some of them while they lay wounded and moaning,
Wolfinger said.
   There was premeditation because ``his plan was to kill, kill,
kill. He meant to do it and he did it,'' he said.
   Public defenders representing the 61-year-old former librarian
were to present their final arguments later.
   The jurors who convicted Cruse on April 5 of 32 counts of
murder, attempted murder and kidnapping now have to recommend his
punishment: death or life in prison without possibility of parole
for 25 years. The verdict can be by simple majority rather than
unanimously.
   Circuit Judge John Antoon said he would give ``great weight'' to
the panel's recommendation, but he does not have to accept it in
passing either sentence.
   The state attorney held up a shotgun used in the wounding of a
teen-ager across the street from Cruse's house. Wolfinger pumped
the weapon several times in front of the jury. He then held up the
semiautomatic assault rifle used in the shopping center rampage,
popping in a 30-round clip several times.
   Anticipating defense arguments that Cruse was insane at the time
of the April 23, 1987, shootout, the prosecutor said: ``There has
never been any disagreement over mental illness. The only
disagreement is its effect'' and how much of a role it played in
the crimes.
   The defense tried to present ``every conceivable, so-called
bizarre incident'' in Cruse's life, Wolfinger said, and it wanted
the jury to feel that ``he should be relieved of all responsibility
for that crime.''
   As to arguments about the defendant's delusions over
homosexuality, Wolfinger said: ``What we have here is a man who
can't accept the doubts of his own masculinity ... and blamed it on
everyone else.''
</TEXT>
