<FIRST>r a AM-GuthrieSign     04-19 0435</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Guthrie Sign,0448</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sign Saying `Woody Guthrie Was No Hero' Torn Down in Singer's Hometown</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OKEMAH, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The tearing down of a sign declaring
``Woody Guthrie Was No Hero'' in the folk singer's hometown has
refueled longstanding debate over how locals should remember
Okemah's most famous native son.
   David Cox, a reporter for the weekly Okemah News Leader, faces a
$54 fine for tearing down the sign last week on the American Legion
building across the street from the newspaper office.
   The sign was put up by funeral director Bart Webb, a former city
councilman and a member of the Legion. Webb filed the municipal
complaint against Cox alleging destruction of private property.
Cox, 26, said he plans to represent himself at a May 8 hearing.
   The incident is the latest in a dispute that has raged for years
in the town of 3,500, with Guthrie's detractors saying he was a
Communist and his admirers saying the man who penned ``This Land is
Your Land'' ought to be honored.
   Tensions are expected to heighten with the scheduled appearance
of Guthrie's son, Arlo, in an April 29 concert at Okemah's Crystal
Theater. Arlo Guthrie has never performed in his father's hometown.
   Webb's 2-foot-by-3-foot sign reprints a recent editorial from
The Oklahoma Constitution, a conservative Oklahoma City tabloid.
The newspaper, under the headline ``Woody Was No Hero,'' calls
Guthrie a ``militant atheist.''
   The sign was replaced after it was torn down, but it was gone
again Wednesday. Cox said he doesn't know who removed it this time.
   Patricia Cheatham, wife of American Legion commander Max
Cheatham, said the Legion post will meet Thursday to discuss
whether the sign should be displayed at the Legion hall. The sign
also was posted elsewhere around town, she said, but Cox said he
hadn't seen it anywhere else.
   Webb would not consent to a telephone interview, a spokeswoman
at his funeral home said Wednesday.
   Mrs. Cheatham described Webb as ``very patriotic.'' He was
defeated in his bid for a second city council term earlier this
month.
   Mrs. Cheatham said until recent years most townspeople ignored
Guthrie, who died in 1967. A movie about his life, ``Bound For
Glory,'' rekindled some interest, she said.
   Guthrie's house was demolished years ago and remains a pile of
debris on an overgrown lot a few blocks from downtown. But a town
water tower visible from Interstate 40 proclaims Okemah as the home
of Woody Guthrie.
   Arlo Guthrie's appearance coincides with the release of an album
taped in December by local musicians and school children as a
tribute to the Dust Bowl balladeer.
</TEXT>
