<FIRST>r a AM-StabbingSuspect     04-19 0310</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Stabbing Suspect,0317</SECOND>
<HEAD>Student Sought In Stabbings of Three</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN K. PAULSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ARVADA, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A high school bodybuilder with a history of
violent crimes was sought Wednesday for stabbing his former
girlfriend, the girl's mother and a 2-year-old child.
   The girl's mother and the child were in critical condition
Wednesday. The mother was in a coma; police said they were unable
to estimate how many times she had been cut.
   Police said the suspect, Carlos Frederick Yeazel, walked away
last week from a group home where state authorities recently placed
him.
   Yeazel, 18, was being sought for the stabbing Tuesday of Kathy
Mitchell, 50; Connie Mitchell, her 17-year-old daughter; and
2-year-old Rachelle Pottorf, who was staying at a day-care center
Kathy Mitchell ran in her home.
   The attack occurred after Yeazel and Connie Mitchell broke off a
months-long relationship, said police in this bedroom community
northwest of Denver. Connie Mitchell had cuts on her arms and legs,
officials said.
   ``He (Yeazel) has an extensive history of violent crimes,'' said
Lt. Ted Mink, adding that he could not disclose the charges because
they were brought against a juvenile.
   Yeazel, who was born in Colombia and was adopted by an American
family in 1985, told his friends that while in Colombia he used
cocaine ``because it was easier to get than food,'' said Teresa
Salins, mother of an Arvada High School student.
   Mink said there was no evidence that Yeazel used cocaine in the
United States.
   He also said there was no evidence Yeazel used steroids,
although several high school students told authorities he was an
enthusiastic bodybuilder and they believed he used them. Friends
said Yeazel gave up using cocaine because of his passion for
bodybuilding, but said they believe he began using steroids, a drug
used by some athletes to build muscle bulk.
