<SECOND>AM-Pushy Dealer,0302</SECOND>
<UNK>Drug Dealer Nabbed When He Insists On Selling To Police Detectives</UNK>
<DATELINE>MUNCIE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Detective Robert Pyle had to turn down his
police radio so he could hear the man outside his unmarked car
offering to sell him cocaine.
   Pyle, a Delaware County police officer, and Muncie police Lt.
Anthony Mench, who was riding with him, chuckled and followed the
man to a house, where he went inside and came out with drugs.
   Then they arrested Larry Dewayne Wilkerson, 30, on a charge of
cocaine dealing.
   The two officers were patrolling a neighborhood about 11:30 p.m.
Tuesday when they dispersed some teen-agers loitering at a liquor
store parking lot. Soon afterward, Wilkerson began following them
in a car, blinking its headlights, Pyle said.
   Pyle pulled over; the other car pulled over, but nobody got out
of either car. Pyle headed on, and Wilkerson started blinking his
lights again.
   The detective said he turned around and pulled up alongside
Wilkerson, who asked who they were looking for.
   Pyle mentioned the name of a suspected drug dealer; Wilkerson
said he knew where Pyle could get cocaine.
   Pyle and Mench said they followed Wilkerson, chuckling most of
the way. They thought Wilkerson would eventually figure out they
were in a police car, but Wilkerson ``pulled over and hopped out of
his car and got into ours.''
   The two officers concealed their police radios and shotguns and
gave Wilkerson $20.
   Pyle said Wilkerson had them drive to a house; Wilkerson went
inside and emerged with the cocaine. Pyle grabbed the cocaine;
Mench pulled his gun on Wilkerson.
   Wilkerson couldn't believe he was being nabbed, Pyle said. He
kept insisting he was just ``a nice guy who was trying to help you
guys out.''
