<FIRST>r i AM-Chile     04-19 0397</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chile,0408</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government To Prosecute Labor Leaders Who Called General Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The military government on Wednesday said
it is prosecuting the labor leaders who called a general strike
that prompted bombings, demonstrations, and hundreds of arrests.
   Organizers called Tuesday's strike, which the government
labelled ``a total failure,'' to demand the return of two other
labor leaders banished to provincial towns for helping to organize
a similar protest in 1987.
   Interior Minister Carlos Caceres said Wednesday the government
is asking a Santiago court to try the labor leaders because ``we
cannot allow this kind of actions.''
   Named in the government's legal action were the acting president
of the United Central Workers, Diego Olivares; and four other
leaders, Nicanor Araya, Sergio Aguirre, Manuel Jimeenez and Moises
Labrana.
   The labor federation called the general strike. It failed to
attract major support from workers but prompted daylong
demonstrations in downtown Santiago and widespread violence in its
slums.
   Police on Wednesday corrected an official report, saying one
suspected guerrilla _ not two _ were killed Tuesday night in a
clash with security agents. Police said the second man is at a
local hospital in critical condition.
   The secret police said the clash occurred when agents caught the
men as they planted a bomb to blow up an electric power pylon in a
working-class district on the outskirts of Santiago.
   Police spokesman Gabriel Ormenno said 412 people were arrested
around the country in the demonstrations. Most of them were to be
released, but 157 remained jailed Wednesday. Officials said 12 were
charged with breaking anti-terrorist law and will be tried.
   Some Santiago neighborhoods remained without power Wednesday
because of the bombing of at least 13 electric towers the day
before. Police said more than 50 bombs went off in Santiago alone,
leaving two men injured and damaging banks, government buildings, a
telephone company office and other facilities.
   Olivares said his labor movement was not responsible for the
violence, which he said had ``dubious origin.'' Leftist groups
opposed to the military government of President Gen. Augusto
Pinochet have bombed power facilities in the past.
   The labor leader said he and his colleagues ``will face with
responsibility any actions by the government against our
organization.''
   The sentence they face will depend on the charges a prosecutor
files within the next few days. They could face banishment like
their two colleagues.
</TEXT>
