<FIRST>r a AM-Escape-Aftermath     04-19 0344</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Escape-Aftermath,0355</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Prison Tightens Security After Copter Escape Attempt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A web of overhead cables covered some open areas of
a federal prison Wednesday as the warden sought to tighten security
in the wake of a failed escape attempt by helicopter.
   Warden John Clark ordered the cables strung over the
high-security exercise courtyard at the Metropolitan Correctional
Center where drug smuggler Benjamin ``Barry'' Kramer hopped on a
hovering helicopter Monday. The aircraft snagged a 14-foot security
fence around the courtyard and crashed.
   Kramer was in satisfactory condition Wednesday at Jackson
Memorial Hospital and the pilot, Charles Clayton Stevens, was in
good condition. Both suffered broken legs. They have been charged
with escape-related counts.
   In the next few months, the entire 48-acre complex which holds
about 1,000 prisoners southwest of Miami will have cables strung
between the roofs of buildings and utility poles.
   ``If a helicopter tries to land, it will be tangled in the
cable,'' Clark said.
   Money to secure the prison against aerial escapes had been
requested from the Department of Justice before Kramer's attempted
breakout, Clark said.
   ``It's an expensive proposition, but after this, I think we'll
get the money for it,'' Clark said.
   Clark said the crash that foiled the escape was caused by the
novice pilot's miscalculation in trying to fly out of the 50-foot
by 200-foot exercise yard.
   Two inmates jumped over the fence to help pull Stevens from the
rubble, Clark said.
   ``At first, we thought they may have been involved in the escape
attempt and (they) were placed in lock-up,'' he said.
   Stevens and Kramer would not have gotten far if the 37-year-old
helicopter had not crashed because U.S. Customs and police planes
would have been sent after them immediately, Clark said.
   The U.S. Marshal's Office was trying to determine how Kramer, of
Hallandale, a champion offshore powerboat racer convicted of drug
smuggling, got in touch with Stevens, a diver in Gold Beach, Ore.
Stevens was just learning to fly a helicopter and had less than 40
hours flying experience on an airplane.
</TEXT>
