<FIRST>r a AM-TaiwaneseBoat     04-19 0271</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Taiwanese Boat,0277</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coast Guard Cutter Pursues Taiwanese Vessel Suspected of Illegal
Fishing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Taiwanese boat suspected of illegal
salmon fishing off the Aleutian Islands steamed toward home
Wednesday, trailed by a Coast Guard cutter seeking permission from
Taiwan to board the vessel.
   ``It's going its way, and we're following,'' said Greg Robinson,
a Coast Guard spokesman in Juneau.
   Because the boat, the Cyi Yang No. 1, is in international
waters, the Coast Guard can't board it without permission, Robinson
said.
   The incident began Sunday when the crew of the Cyi Yang warned
the Jarvis, a Coast Guard cutter on patrol five miles away, that
driftnets were in the water and that it should stay away, said Bill
Woolf, an aide to Sen. Frank Murkowski, R-Alaska.
   Upon learning that it had communicated with a Coast Guard
vessel, the squid boat abandoned its nets and headed southwest,
toward Taiwan, Woolf said. The Jarvis pursued the boat, which did
not respond to demands that it stop.
   Robinson said the encounter took place about 450 miles from
legal fishing waters, about 400 miles southwest of the far end of
the Aleutian chain. By midday Wednesday, the vessels were 1,100
miles southwest of Adak, he said.
   Woolf said Wednesday that a Taiwanese government official had
called the senator to apologize for the incident and to say that
Taiwan will allow the vessel to be boarded.
   The official told Murkowski the Taiwanese government is
attempting to contact the ship's owner to order it to stop, Woolf
said. Robinson said that information had not been relayed to the
Coast Guard by midmorning.
</TEXT>
