<FIRST>r a AM-FusionCommittee     04-19 0279</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fusion Committee,0287</SECOND>
<HEAD>Utah Governor Signs Bill Appropriating $5 Million for Research</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PEG McENTEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Norm Bangerter signed legislation on
Wednesday appropriating $5 million for cold fusion research and
creating a nine-member committee to oversee the work and its
potential practical application.
   Bangerter charged the panel, comprised of members representing
industry, law, education and the state, to ``make a hard-nosed
evaluation of this process, to make sure the money, when it's
spent, is spent wisely and prudently.''
   At the same time, the governor asked committee members to use
their resources to protect Utah's investment in the research.
   The committee was formed following the March 23 news conference
in which University of Utah researcher B. Stanley Pons and his
British colleague, Martin Fleischmann, announced they had sustained
a room temperature fusion reaction.
   A special session of the Legislature appropriated the $5 million
for further research and development.
   Committee Chairman Raymond L. Hixson, chief executive of the
Bonneville Pacific Corp., said the committee would meet Wednesday
to set an agenda.
   ``Our task is to try to move (cold fusion) from basic research
to practical application,'' he said. ``But first, we need to get as
broad an understanding of this process as we can.''
   It was too soon to say when funds would begin to be released, or
where, Hixson said.
   He said the committee hoped to meet with Pons and Fleischmann to
discuss their research, and eventually with scientists from other
institutions conducting similar work.
   Bangerter said he had recently returned from a tour of Japan,
Taiwan and Korea, where he found a great interest and enthusiasm
for the fusion research.
</TEXT>
