<FIRST>r a AM-FounderingShip     04-19 0314</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Foundering Ship,0324</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coast Guard Plans At Least Another Day Of Searching</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE LOCKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The search for two crewmen swept into the sea
after their ship sank continued a third day Wednesday, with
rescuers holding out hope that the temperate water of the Gulf
Stream might help the men survive.
   Spotters aboard a Coast Guard airplane were directing the Coast
Guard cutter Chilula in an area about 400 miles southeast of Cape
Cod, said Coast Guard Petty Officer Jeff Crawley.
   The cutter was carrying the 23 sailors who were rescued after
the freighter Star of Alexandria sank in stormy seas Monday morning.
   The crew of a search plane reported spotting one of the missing
crewmen Tuesday, but found no further signs, Crawley said.
   ``Both crewmen are being presumed to be alive,'' he said.
``They're near the Gulf Stream. The water temperature isn't that
cold.''
   Survivors said one of the missing men jumped overboard from the
sinking ship and appeared to be injured. The other was wearing a
life jacket when he was washed off a life raft.
   The 23 multinational crew members were picked up by the
freighter Ravenscraig, which was diverted to the scene the after
rescue planes spotted a life boat and a life raft. A second life
raft was recovered but was empty, Crawley said.
   The Chilula arrived at the search area Tuesday to collect the
rescued crewmen from the 950-foot Ravenscraig.
   Crawley said officials still didn't know what made the Star of
Alexandria sink.
   ``They had reported they were taking on water, why we don't
know,'' he said.
   The 500-foot freighter was bound for New York City from Athens,
Greece.
   The Star of Alexandria was registered in England and designed to
carry bulk freight. The ship is owned by Caribene Investments Ltd.
of Gibraltar, according to Bureau Veritas, a Paris-based shipping
registry.
