<SECOND>AM-Highway Killings,0332</SECOND>
<HEAD>11th Woman Feared Victim in Highway Killings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW BEDFORD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 34-year-old woman who disappeared
last summer may be the 11th victim of a serial killer or killers,
Bristol County authorities said Wednesday.
   The remains of eight women between the ages of 25 and 36 have
been found since July along highways near this port city 40 miles
south of Boston. Two other women are missing and feared dead.
   ``We are looking at the possibility of there being another
victim,'' said Jim Martin, spokesman for Bristol County District
Attorney Ronald Pina.
   Pina previously identified two of the missing women as Christina
Monteiro, 20, who vanished last May, and Sandra Botelho, 25, who
disappeared Aug. 11.
   The Boston Globe, citing unnamed sources, reported Wednesday
that the third missing woman was Marilyn Roberts, daughter of a
retired New Bedford police officer. Martin would not confirm the
identity but said the woman's family had provided information to
the district attorney.
   ``The family has said they have not seen or heard from her since
last summer,'' Martin said. ``They filed a missing person report
with the New Bedford police.''
   The Standard-Times of New Bedford reported that 34-year-old
Marilyn J. Roberts was initially reported missing in April 1988,
but was seen in the city in June. Her family reported her missing
again in December after reports of the highway killings.
   Roberts had ties to the city's drug community, as did the eight
victims and the two other missing women, The Globe and The Standard
Times reported.
   The Standard-Times said Roberts was a heroin addict and had been
arrested on drug charges in 1984 and 1985, but unlike some of the
other victims, she had no record of prostitution.
   A grand jury, which was first convenced in February to hear
evidence in the case, is scheduled to reconvene on April 27.
   The investigation has produced four suspects, but no arrests
have been made.
