<FIRST>r w AM-ParentalLeave     04-19 0198</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Parental Leave,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Unpaid Leave Bill Approved</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate Labor and Human Resources approved
a bill Wednesday to require large employers to provide up to 10
weeks of unpaid leave for parents of new babies.
   The vote was 10-6.
   The bill, similar to a measure awaiting House floor action, also
would require employers to make 10 weeks available for workers to
care for a seriously ill child or parent.
   And it would require them to grant up to 13 weeks a year unpaid
leave in the even of serious illness of the employee.
   The bill, sponsored by Sen. Chris Dodd, D-Conn., would apply to
employers of 20 or more people.
   Similar Dodd legislation cleared the committee last year, but
failed to overcome an informal filibuster mounted by Republican
opponents on the floor.
   Parental leave legislation is a main part of the overall
Democratic domestic agenda this year _ along the minimum wage,
federal child care and health care for the uninsured.
   Party leaders have agreed informally that the House will go
first this year with its version of the parental leave bill.
Parental leave legislation was not considered by the full House
last year.
