<FIRST>r w AM-AbortionAds     04-19 0679</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Abortion Ads,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Ad Campaigns in Abortion Fight</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One week before the Supreme Court hears
arguments in a key abortion-rights case, an abortion rights group
Wednesday took to the airwaves with a $2 million ad campaign while
an anti-abortion group said it plans to run newspaper ads next week
to stir America's grass roots.
   The National Abortion Rights Action League Wednesday began
running television, radio and newspaper ads to present their side
and build on the energy displayed at an abortion-rights march that
drew at least 300,000 to the nation's Capitol earlier this month.
   Meantime, the American Civil Liberties Union plans on Thursday
to deliver more than 200,000 letters to the Justice Department on
Thursday asking the department to drop its attempt to persuade the
Supreme Court to overturn the landmark 1973 decision legalizing
abortion.
   The NARAL ads are designed ``to awaken America's pro-choice
majority _ the sleeping giant that is just now hearing the alarm,''
said Kate Michelman, executive director of NARAL.
   The ads were being run in four state capital cities _
Sacramento, Calif.; Des Moines, Iowa; Raleigh, N.C.; and Austin,
Texas. On Sunday, the ads will begin in Washington, D.C., and
nationally on Cable News Network, she said.
   NARAL's ads warn that without safe, legal abortions, women will
be forced to turn to ``back alley'' abortions, and say the choice
of whether to have an abortion should be made by women and their
families, not the government.
   Michelman said the ad campaign is a first of its kind for the
group, warranted by the imminent danger to abortion rights posed by
a Missouri case that will be heard by the high court.
   Though many doubt the court in this case will reverse its
landmark Roe vs. Wade ruling that legalized first-trimester
abortions, many say the court could allow states to impose more
restrictions on abortions.
   Oral arguments are scheduled for April 26.
   The National Right to Life Committee said it is planning to run
a four-page insert in USA Today on April 25 and to run the ad in
other papers around the country after that, said Dan Donehey, a
spokesman for the group.
   Donehey, who estimated the cost of the campaign at $150,000,
said the ads will include information on the types of abortion
procedures performed, the developmental characteristics of a fetus,
the effect of abortion on women and profiles of women who carried
babies to term instead of aborting them.
   Michelman said her group's ad campaign is not intended to lobby
the Supreme Court, but she said the court ``is not immune to the
social values and political environment of the country.''
   Leonard Dinegar, a National Right to Life Committee spokesman,
said his group isn't trying to sway the high court, but wants to
take advantage of the attention it has focused on the abortion
issue.
   ``This is the best time to educate people on the issue because
it's so hot right now,'' he said. etters,xxx
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department filed a brief with the Supreme Court
regarding the Missouri case of Webster vs. Reproductive Health
Services that not only asked the top court to uphold a Missouri law
but asked that it upend the 1973 Roe vs. Wade decision as well.
   Actor Ed Asner, actress Polly Bergen, Rep. Pat Schroeder,
D-Colo, and ACLU executive director Ira Glasser will present the
