<FIRST>r i AM-Hamadi     04-19 0321</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hamadi,0331</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Allows New Witness at Hijacker's Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE BOEHMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge delayed final arguments
Wednesday in the trial of confessed TWA hijacker Mohammed Ali
Hamadi and allowed his attorney to call a new witness to the stand.
   Rainer Hamm, lawyer for the family of Robert D. Stethem,
objected to bringing in the new witness and accused defense
lawmakers of intentionally delaying the trial, which began July 5,
1988.
   Chief Judge Heiner Mueckenberger dismissed the objection and
scheduled testimony from the witness, a reporter for the BBC, for
Monday and postponed the trial until then.
   The judge at the courtroom in Preungesheim Prison in Frankfurt
had hoped to begin hearing closing arguments by the prosecution
Wednesday.
   Hamadi's lawyer, Hans-Burkhardt Steck, told the court he wanted
BBC reporter John Simpson, who was in Algiers, Algeria, during the
hijacking of TWA Flight 847 in June 1985 ``to give an account of
what went on in Algiers'' when the plane was forced to land there.
   Hamadi, a Lebanese Shiite Moslem, is charged with air piracy and
murder in the hijacking in which 23-year-old Stethem was shot to
death and 39 Americans were held hostage for 17 days.
   The plane, seized on a flight from Athens to Rome on June 14,
1985, shuttled between Beirut and Algiers before returning to the
Lebanese capital for the third time.
   Stethem, the only casualty, was shot when the plane landed the
second time at Beirut.
   Hamadi's lawyer said Simpson was in Algiers during both landings
of TWA Flight 847.
   He said the defense hoped Simpson could refute earlier testimony
by a West German federal police investigator that Hamadi and his
accomplice ``made threats and had a heated argument with Algiers
control tower to obtain fuel'' for a return flight to Beirut.
   Stethem's parents, Richard and Patricia Stethem of Waldorf, Md.,
have attended the trial since it began.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
