<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-89 2039EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     04-19 0473</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0485</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sri Lanka Cease-Fire Ends, No Accord with Sinhalese Radicals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government's weeklong cease-fire
ended Wednesday with Sinhalese radicals demanding a pullout of
Indian troops and new elections before any peace talks.
   ``It is pointless carrying a gun in one hand and calling for
peace talks with the other,'' said a statement issued by the
People's Liberation Front, the main militant group of the majority
Sinhalese.
   The government extended the cease-fire to both ethnic Tamil
rebels fighting for a homeland and militant Sinhalese who want
tougher measures against the Tamils. Despite escalated violence
that left 100 people dead over the past week, Tamil militants said
Saturday they were ready for talks on ending their six-year-long
insurgency.
   President Ranasinghe Premadasa ordered suspension of military
operations against the extremists to give them a chance to
surrender and join the political mainstream.
   Militant Sinhalese said talks should wait until new
parliamentary and presidential elections are held and Indian troops
leave the country. They also demanded disbanding of vigilante
groups blamed for killing suspected militants in the
Sinhalese-dominated south.
   The government reacted by calling on the militants to hold
preliminary negotiations anyway.
   ``It is appropriate that an informal discussion is held on
preliminary issues that would ... create a basis of trust as a
prerequisite for a dialogue,'' said Foreign Minister Ranjan
Wijeratna. He made no comment on the militant demands.
   The Tamil militants have appointed Anton Balasingham, a Sri
Lankan-born Tamil who is a British citizen, to start the peace
talks. Balasingham, the recently named head of the rebels'
political section, is expected to arrive soon from London,
according to presidential spokesman Evans Cooray. No date has been
announced for the talks.
   Military officials said 233 Sinhalese radicals surrendered
during the cease-fire. No Tamil militants surrendered, they said.
   Sinhalese extremists launched their anti-government campaign in
1987 after former President Junius R. Jayewardene signed an
India-sponsored peace accord with Tamil rebels. The Sinhalese
radicals said the pact, which called for greater Tamil autonomy,
made too many concessions to the Tamils.
   The rebels later renounced the accord and began fighting Indian
peacekeeping troops sent to Sri Lanka to promote the plan. India
became involved in the ethnic tensions of this island off its
southern coast because of the sympathies of its own 60 million
Tamils for the rebels.
   Tamils, who are mostly Hindu, comprise 18 percent of Sri Lanka's
16 million people. They complain of discrimination in jobs and
education and demand a northeastern homeland.
   Sri Lanka's government and military has been dominated by the
Sinhalese since the island, formerly called Ceylon, became
independent from Britain in 1948. Sinhalese, who are predominantly
Buddhists, make up 75 percent of the population.
   About 12,600 people have died in the ethnic violence over the
past six years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
