<FIRST>r w AM-Philippines-Bases     04-19 0320</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Philippines-Bases,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Optimism on US Base Pact</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the U.S. Pacific Command said
Wednesday he is ``cautiously optimistic'' that the Philippines will
agree to a new pact on U.S. bases there but acknowledged that
political sentiment against the facilities is growing.
   Adm. Huntington Hardisty, commander-in-chief of the U.S. Pacific
Command, said he believes the two countries can agree on an
extension to the pact when the lease expires on the six bases
expires in 1991.
   ``Everyone has an interest in the United States remaining in the
Philippines,'' Hardisty told the Senate Armed Services Committee.
``We're good friends, we're good allies and I hope that
relationship will continue.''
   The admiral said he was ``cautiously optimistic that in 1991 we
can reach a favorable renegotiation of the military base
agreement.''
   But under questioning from Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., Hardisty
said he concurred with Philippine Vice President Salvador Laurel's
statement that political opposition to the bases is increasing.
   ``I don't disagree with that assessment but I think reason will
prevail in 1991,'' he said. ``I think we've seen a lot of rhetoric
and a lot of posturing against the Aquino government.''
   Hardisty added that Laurel ``has a political agenda as well.''
   Laurel resigned as foreign secretary in September 1987, citing
differences with President Corazon Aquino over the 20-year battle
against a communist insurgency and other issues, including economic
development in the poor nation.
   Laurel, who was in Washington this week, said that although the
public favors the U.S. presence, a strong anti-American sentiment
is growing in the Philippine Senate. According to law, two-thirds
of the 23-member Senate must ratify a U.S.-Philippine treaty on
military bases.
   Presently, the United States maintains Clark Air Base and Subic
Bay Naval Base, two of its largest facilities overseas, and four
smaller installations. More than 60,000 Filipinos are employed at
the bases, where about 40,000 U.S. troops and their dependents are
stationed.
</TEXT>
