<FIRST>r a AM-LandingProblem     04-19 0221</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Landing Problem,0227</SECOND>
<HEAD>Corporate Jet Lands At O'Hare After Apparent Nose-Gear Problem</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Amoco Corp. jet carrying the company's
president and five other people landed safely Wednesday after
circling for nearly five hours because of a problem with its nose
landing gear, officials said.
   The Gulfstream III twin-engine jet took off about 5:30 a.m. from
Midway Airport with three company executives, including President
H. Laurance Fuller, and three crew members en route to Asia by way
of Anchorage, Alaska, said Amoco spokesman Mike Thompson.
   ``It landed without incident at 10:32 a.m.,'' at O'Hare
International Airport, said Federal Aviation Administration
spokesman Mort Edelstein.
   ``The nose gear never retracted,'' Edelstein said. ``They
requested a flyby from the control tower, and they looked with
binoculars and said `no, it has not retracted.'''
   The $19 million jet circled Midway for about 4{ hours in 40-mile
circles to burn off fuel before heading to O'Hare for the landing,
Edelstein said.
   ``It's a standard thing to do,'' he said. ``In the case of a
crash, there's a better chance for survival'' if the fuel tanks are
empty.
   He said pilots prefer the additional emergency equipment and
longer runways that make O'Hare safer for emergency landings.
   Edelstein said the nose-gear failure could have been caused by a
mechanic forgetting to take out a pin.
</TEXT>
