<FIRST>r a AM-TerroristicThreat     04-19 0465</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Terroristic Threat,0480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Despite Reported Terrorist Threat, Life As Usual In Atlantic City</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Law enforcement officials refused
Wednesday to confirm published reports of a planned terrorist
attack here, but some resort patrons said they noticed tighter
security in the city's 12 casinos.
   Casino operators and Boardwalk vendors reported business as
usual despite reports that police were looking for two Arab men
planning a terrorist attack. The reports were linked to anonymous
sources in Wednesday's editions of The Star-Ledger of Newark and
The Press of Atlantic City.
   State police on Wednesday monitored the three main roads into
Atlantic City. Plainclothes State Police detectives increased their
surveillance of casinos, according to the two newspapers.
   The assault was scheduled sometime from April 14 to April 20,
the newspapers said. Authorities said the attack was to be in
retaliation for the U.S. bombing on April 15, 1986, of Libyan
leader Moammar Gadhafi's headquarters, according to the newspapers.
   Two weeks ago, a British newspaper reported that Libya planned
attacks on U.S. airlines and other American targets to mark the
anniversary of the bombing.
   Libya's news agency JANA has denied the reports, which were tied
to a senior U.S. intelligence official.
   Spokesmen for the FBI and Atlantic City Police Chief Joseph
Pasquale declined to comment on the case. State Police
Superintendent Col. Clinton Pagano refused to comment on whether
his force was on alert.
   U.S. Attorney Samuel A. Alito declined comment Wednesday, but
noted that one year ago, alleged terrorist Yu Kikumura was arrested
on the New Jersey Turnpike.
   In February, Kikumura was sentenced to 30 years in prison on
explosives and weapons charges.
   ``I think we showed he was going to carry out his bombing
mission on April 14,'' Alito said. ``We are now just about a year
later. Whatever inferences anybody wants to draw from that they
can.''
   Thomas Carver, president of the Atlantic City Casino
Association, refused to say whether casinos had increased security
or police had added patrols. He also declined to speculate on the
effects the newspaper report would have on visitors.
   ``I think the weather has more to do with the attendance in
Atlantic City than anything else,'' Carver said.
   Operators of some Boardwalk businesses and casinos said the
customer flow was normal Wednesday.
   Circe Stein, manager of Duke Mack's, a popular restaurant on the
Boardwalk, said some of her customers noticed additional security
measures at casinos and on the highways. But she said there was no
decrease in patrons.
   ``We're still working our tails off,'' she said.
   At TropWorld Casino and Entertainment Resort, business was
``absolutely status quo for Wednesdays,'' said casino spokesman Jim
Wise.
   ``It's absolutely business as usual,'' said Trump Plaza
spokesman Gary Selesner. ``We are not aware of any cancellations
due to the bomb threat.''
</TEXT>
