<FIRST>r a AM-ArtisticProtest     04-19 0338</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Artistic Protest,0346</SECOND>
<HEAD>Students Stage Whimsical Protests Over School Leader</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   WINSTON-SALEM, N.C. (AP) _ Students at the North Carolina School
of the Arts staged a ``Bard-a-thon'' as well as mime and dance
shows and an oboe concert to demonstrate their unhappiness with the
school's chancellor.
   After months of complaints by faculty and students, Chancellor
Jane Milley has resigned, effective June 30, from the top job at
the school, part of the University of North Carolina System.
   The school's Faculty Council voted 11-0 last March to call for
her resignation; the council had taken a no-confidence vote in
November, too, in which it was joined by 85 of 89 faculty members.
   The university system's Board of Governors voted this month to
give Ms. Milley, 48, a paid leave of absence and then appoint her
as a music instructor, beginning Jan. 1, at a salary of $58,600, or
$6,000 higher than the music dean's. Her chancellor's salary is
$86,000.
   However, students at the school said they didn't like the deal;
this week, they took to the streets.
   First, a student sat in the chancellor's parking space and
played an oboe.
   Next, students staged the ``Bard-a-thon'' _ a reading of
Shakespeare's 154 sonnets and 13 plays. Other performance protests
included chamber music concerts, interpretive dance in front of a
banner proclaiming ``Milley Must Go,'' and juggling.
   On Tuesday, Peter Hedges, a former drama student at the school,
stood on a outdoor stage and read telegrams from Oscar-nominee Tom
Hulce, television star Tim Guinee and Broadway actress Joan Allen
in support of the students.
   ``We're not trying to railroad her out of town,'' said Nathan
``Cory'' Seymour, 26, a graduate student in technical direction and
production management and one of the organizers of the protest.
``We just want her to relinquish her power now.''
   In 1984, Ms. Milley was named chancellor, the first non-composer
to hold the post. Soon after her appointment, her management style
came in for criticism as being abrasive and crisis-oriented.
Critics also said she wouldn't delegate authority.
</TEXT>
