<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-89 1921EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Laurel     04-19 0476</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Laurel,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Philippine Vice President Says He's `Jobless'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Salvador Laurel, the Philippine vice president
at odds with President Corazon Aquino, described himself on
Wednesday as being in ``a state of suspended animation'' as he
prepares a bid for his nation's top office.
   Laurel, who spoke with reporters at the National Press Club, is
visiting Washington to meet with congressional leaders and
highlight his views in advance of next month's national convention
of the opposition Nacionalista Party.
   He has said he expects to be one of several candidates who are
going to ``throw their hat in the ring'' for the 1992 presidential
elections. Although Mrs. Aquino has said she will not seek
re-election, it is possible that she may be drafted to run again.
   Relations are so poor between Mrs. Aquino and her vice president
that they do not speak.
   Although Laurel said his visit was not geared around criticism
at Mrs. Aquino, the majority of his statements found fault with her
government's battle against the nation's 20-year-old communist
insurgency, as well as the approach to economic and political
development.
   In contrast to the U.S. system of government, the Philippine
vice president has no duties under the constitution unless
appointed to a position by the president. After a political falling
out in 1987, Laurel resigned his post as foreign minister and
lately has been organizing an opposition party.
   ``I'm in a state of suspended animation,'' he said.
   Still, he quipped, ``as a jobless vice president, I'm able to
travel more than others'' and visit with citizens.
   As for the insurgency, Laurel said rebel numbers have ballooned
from 14,000 to 33,000 in the past three years.
   ``If we don't put up a responsible, democratic opposition, the
alternative we face is a violent opposition,'' he said.
   A State Department official familiar with the situation in the
Philippines said, however, that the insurgency was not that large
and that it ``hasn't made any particular progress'' over the past
several years. The official commented on condition he not be named.
   The vice president also said he differed with Mrs. Aquino on the
issue of the negotiation of the future of U.S. bases in the
Philippines and he criticized a lack of movement on the issue.
   He argued that the Philippine government should enter into
negotiations with the United States as soon as possible, since the
pact expires in 1991.
   Laruel did say Mrs. Aquino deserved credit for helping the
nation through a rocky three years since former dictator Ferdinand
Marcos left the country. A civilian-military uprising in February
1986 ended Marcos' rule and swept Mrs. Aquino and Laurel into power.
   But Laurel argued that ``the transition from dictatorship to
democracy'' won't be complete without the formation of a
``responsible, legitimate, organized opposition,'' which he said
his party intends to be.
</TEXT>
