<FIRST>r w AM-OverweightTrucks     04-19 0207</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Overweight Trucks,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Truckers Group Says Many International Containers Overweight</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Overloaded container trucks carrying European
beer, paper products and ceramic tiles are violating U.S. highway
regulations and endangering trucking safety, a truckers group told
Congress Wednesday.
   Thomas J. Donohue, head of the American Trucking Associations,
said the heavy containers packed in Europe increase stopping
distances, decrease vehicle control and put additional stress on
American trucks.
   Donohue said beer imports from Holland top the list of
potentially overweight containers, followed by paper products and
ceramic tile imported from various countries.
   ``By allowing imports such as beer to move at higher weights
than those allowed domestic products, the U.S. is, in effect,
providing an economic subsidy to foreign competitors,'' Donohue
told the Senate Commerce, Science and Transportation Committee.
   He said the Federal Highway Administration lacks authority to
regulate the containers because they are only illegal when they are
carried on the highways, where enforcement agents fine truckers for
the overweight cargoes.
   Donohue said a recent study by the highway administration
indicates that a third of all import and export containers moving
through U.S. ports are in possible violation of federal highway
weight limits. The top violator among shipments for export is waste
paper, he said.
</TEXT>
