<FIRST>u w AM-Bush-Sightseeing     04-19 0492</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Sightseeing,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush-Jordan, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush the tourguide was at it again
Wednesday, this time taking his guest for a spin on the Potomac
River in a yacht _ snatched from drug dealers and fit for a king.
   Continuing a practice of taking Middle Eastern leaders on
sightseeing trips around Washington, Bush hosted Jordan's King
Hussein by making use of a yacht, now owned by the U.S. Navy. Bush
has shown a penchant of late for making sure his foreign guests get
a taste of the tourist sights.
   The president took Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak to the
season opener baseball game in Baltimore two weeks ago. Bush then
showed Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir the Air and Space
Museum, one of the most popular tourist attractions in the capital.
   Hussein's tour began with a historical tone.
   Before their cruise, the king and Bush flew by helicopter to
nearby Mt. Vernon, the sprawling Virginia riverside estate of
George Washington. There, with an entourage of about 30 people,
they toured the home while tourists waited outside on the spacious
grounds.
   Then Bush and Hussein, trailed by a column of aides whose dark
suits contrasted with the flowering trees and springtime greenery,
descended a brick walkway to the Potomac River where they received
a lively sendoff from the Fife and Drum Corps of the Old Guard, 3rd
U.S. Infantry. The fife and drum band was dressed in American
Revolution costumes, with three-corner hats and red jackets.
   As how he liked his Mt.Vernon tour, Hussein smiled broadly and
said, ``I enjoyed it very, very much.''
   The two leaders boarded a 61-foot yacht named the Cinclantflt
Barge for the 10-mile ride back to Washington. Confiscated from
drug dealers in Florida, the craft, equipped with a bar and other
luxuries, is used for special functions of the chief of naval
operations, according to Coast Guard crew members who accompanied
the Bush tour.
   Bush and Hussein remained inside the yact, seated around a
conference table bedecked with a bowlof red roses and pink
carnations. Among those accompanying Bush were Secretary of State
James A. Baker III, National Security Adviser Brent Scowcroft and
Chief of Staff John Sununu.
   If Hussein glanced out the porthole, he could have seen the
luxurious homes along the riverbanks, the Revolutionary War-era
Fort Washington and the historic harbor of Alexandria, Va.
   The sceneary Wednesday also included a burning automobile on the
Wilson Bridge, just about wheere the Cinclanflt passed.
   A handful of police boats, including a District of Columbia
fireboat called the John Glenn, shooed away fishing and
recreational boats and kept two large tour boats at dock until the
presidents passed.
   After more than an hour of 12-knot travel, the Bush yacht
anchored at Bolling Air Force Base, just south of the capital, and
Hussein headed off for lunch with Vice President Dan Quayle and
Bush returned to meetings at the White House.
</TEXT>
