<FIRST>r a AM-FastDay     04-19 0409</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fast Day,0419</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Hampshire Observes Unique `Fast Day'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ADOLPHE V. BERNOTAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some New Hampshire residents will have a
long weekend thanks to a state holiday born in 1681 out of fear
that its first governor was going to die. Monday is Fast Day.
   Until four years ago, the fourth Monday in April was observed
widely as a spring Thanksgiving, with all state offices closed. But
the state's contract with its workers now has made Fast Day a
``floating holiday,'' an optional day off that allows state offices
to stay open.
   Although state offices will be open, some city and town offices
will close, schools and banks will close, federal offices will be
open and stores will have sales.
   Fast Day began with John Cutt, about whom little is known other
than he was ``President of the Royal Province of New Hampshire by
grace of Charles II,'' and that he sometimes spelled his name Cutts.
   Cutt was the richest merchant in Portsmouth, the colonial
capital. On May 6, 1680, when he was 60, he had a foreboding of his
death and wrote his will. By next year, the Welsh immigrant was so
ill that the colonial General Assembly declared a day of ``fasting,
humiliation and prayer'' for his recovery.
   It was a peculiarly New England custom to declare days of
fasting and prayer whenever the colonists felt threatened by
catastrophe.
   The first known fast day was observed by Massachusetts after the
drought of 1622. In 1894, Massachusetts substituted Fast Day with
Patriots Day to observe the start of the Revolutionary War.
Massachusetts and Maine observe Patriots Day on the third Monday in
April.
   New Hampshire's theological cure for Cutt failed. He died on
April 1, 1681.
   New Hampshire used to observe as many as three Fast Days a year.
By 1899, the Legislature decided on one and in 1949, with a view
toward a three-day weekend, the Legislature settled on the fourth
Monday in April.
   The nature of the observance has changed. Church attendance used
to be mandatory.
   The 10-shilling fine against those taking part in ``labour,
business or work of their ordinary calling'' was lifted long ago.
Recreation no longer is forbidden.
   Now the holiday comes as New Hampshire's long winter gives way
to spring, when snow tires and storm windows are packed away in
garages, when schools begin a week of vacation, and when golf
courses become snow-free.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890419-0177 </DOCNO>
