<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Passover     04-19 0419</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Passover,0431</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iraelis Commemorate Exodus From Egypt; Police On Alert</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto TLV1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israelis gathered for festive meals Wednesday
to begin Passover, the holiday commemorating the liberation of the
ancient Israelites from slavery. Security forces were on high alert
in case of guerrilla attacks.
   Thousands of people went to resorts on the Red Sea,
Mediterranean and Sea of Galilee. In Tel Aviv, secular Israelis
jammed beaches and outdoor restaurants.
   Army and police alerts were ordered because the 16-month-old
Palestinian uprising in the occupied territories increased fear of
guerrilla attacks during the holiday.
   The army stepped up its forces to prevent infiltrations across
Israel's borders. Since January, 31 guerrillas have been killed in
a dozen attacks along the border with Lebanon.
   Police were out in force in Jerusalem's walled Old City to
prevent disruptions of religious services, a national police
spokesman said.
   In downtown Jerusalem, police discovered a small explosive
device in a paint bucket left on the sidewalk near a cafe, but
experts defused it, police spokesman Uzi Sandori reported.
   Passover, which commemorates the flight of the Israelites from
Egypt, began at sundown Wednesday with a traditional meal known as
the seder. It includes such symbolic foods as bitter herbs to
remind Jews of the harshness of their enslavement, and an
unleavened bread called matzoh.
   During the week-long holiday many Jews abstain from bread, beer
and other products made with yeast to remember the Israelites, who
left Egypt so quickly they had no time to leaven their bread.
   The holiday derives its name from the book of Exodus, which
recounts that God ``passed over'' the homes of Israelites when
meting out the worst of 10 plagues, and killed the first-born of
every Egyptian. The plagues forced the pharaoh to let the Jews
leave Egypt.
   In Tel Aviv, U.S. Ambassador William A. Brown participated in a
symbolic outdoor seder organized by Soviet Jewish activists to
thank the United States for supporting Soviet Jews who have been
refused permission to emigrate.
   Organizers set up a table on the sidewalk across the street from
the embassy, serving wine and traditional Passover dishes.
   The army served Passover meals at military bases, but soldiers
serving in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip were given grape
juice instead of the traditional four cups of red wine, an army
spokesman said.
   In a goodwill gesture for the holiday, more than 700 prisoners
serving time for criminal offenses were given forloughs of two to
four days, said Shuli Meiri, a prison services spokeswoman.
</TEXT>
