<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-89 2058EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-ChildSupport     04-19 0210</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Child Support,210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rules Proposed to Speed States in Child-Support Enforcement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government proposed regulations Wednesday
designed to force states to pursue child support more vigorously by
requiring them to supply information for collection orders promptly.
   ``In the past, some states have not given sufficient attention''
to such efforts, said Health and Human Srvices Secretary Louis
Sullivan. ``Millions of children have suffered because of this lack
of attention.''
   Delay in action by the states, he said, has prevented children
from receiving financial support they are due.
   The regulations, which implement the Family Support Act passed
last year by Congress in a major welfare overhaul, sets time limits
for states to respond to requests for assistance in establishing
and enforcing child support orders.
   Limits would be established for opening and maintaining case
records, locating absent parents, establishing paternity, enforcing
support obligations and receiving and distributing support
payments. The regulations also provide criteria for states to use
in determining whether to close a child support case.
   States would be required to comply with those time limits by
Oct. 1, 1990.
   The regulations were published in Wednesday's Federal Register.
The Department of Health and Human Services set a 60-day comment
period, after which the department will issue final rules.
</TEXT>
