<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     04-19 0421</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0435</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rain In The South, Northwest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Showers and thunderstorms were scattered over the Gulf Coast
states Wednesday and rain fell in the Northwest, but most of the
rest of the nation had mild, sunny weather.
   A cold front extended from North Carolina to the middle of
Texas, separating cool, dry air to the north from warm and humid
air to the south.
   Along the front, showers and thunderstorms were scattered over
the South and were most widespread in southern Texas.
   Morning thunderstorms were heaviest on the west side of San
Antonio, Texas, where hail up to an inch in diameter was reported
and some roads were closed by high water, the National Weather
Service said.
   Heavier rainfall during the six hours up to 1 p.m. CDT included
2.57 inches at Kelly Air Force Base at San Antonio, Texas.
   Wind gusted to 46 mph during a thunderstorm at Beeville, Texas,
the weather service said.
   Showers and a few thunderstorms also occurred over northeastern
Mississippi, northwestern Alabama and along the Mississippi Gulf
Coast.
   Scattered showers and thunderstorms developed during the
afternoon over the Florida Peninsula.
   In the Northwest, scattered afternoon showers developed from
western Montana to eastern Washington state.
   Elsewhere, the sky was clear from the Great Lakes across the
central Plains to the Southwest.
   Most of the western half of the nation had afternoon
temperatures in the 60s and 70s, up into the 90s in the desert
Southwest.
   Behind the cold front, temperatures were in the 40s and 50s from
the upper Mississippi Valley across the Ohio Valley and Great Lakes
to New England, and scattered frost was forecast overnight in
northern Kentucky.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 41
degrees at Sault Ste. Marie, Mich., to 99 at Gila Bend, Ariz.
Wednesday's low in the 48 contiguous states was 19 degrees at
Gunnison, Colo.
   For Thursday, scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecast
along the Carolina coast, across southern Georgia and over much of
Florida, and over the upper Mississippi Valley. Rain was forecast
across the Pacific Northwest.
   Highs in the 50s and 60s were predicted over the Great Lakes
region and New England, with some 40s in extreme northern sections;
in the 60s in the Appalachians and along the mid Atlantic Coast,
and along much of the Pacific Coast; in the 90s in southwestern
Texas and sections of New Mexico; around 100 in the desert
Southwest; and in the 70s and 80s across most of the rest of the
nation.
</TEXT>
