<FIRST>r i AM-Greece     04-19 0407</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Greece,0417</SECOND>
<HEAD>State To Pay For Premier's Libel Suit Against Time Magazine</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHILIP DOPOULOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state will pay for Premier Andreas
Papandreou's libel suit against Time magazine for publishing
accusations by a Greek fugitive banker that Papandreou received
millions of dollars in payoffs, a government spokesman said
Wednesday.
   Spokesman Sotiris Kostopoulos said at his daily news briefing
that Papandreou sued the American newsmagazine ``as premier of
Greece ... so all expenses incurred by this suit will be paid by
the Greek state, which will be reimbursed from the damages received
from the positive outcome of the trial.''
   Kostopoulos confirmed that New York attorney Leonard Boudin
already has been paid $100,000 through the Greek Embassy in
Washington to handle the suit. He did not disclose how much money
Papandreou seeks in damages.
   Boudin said in New York Monday that the suit was brought against
Time in London because in Britain he need show only that the story
written about Papandreou was libelous and damaged his reputation,
without regard to whether he is a public figure.
   Time ran an interview with George Koskotas, former chairman of
the Bank of Crete, in its March 13 issue. Koskotas alleged that
Papandreou and senior members of his governing party, the
Panhellenic Socialist Movement, or PASOK, received millions of
dollars in payoffs in return for political favors.
   Time officials said attempts were made to obtain Papandreou's
and the government's side of the story before it was published, but
they were rebuffed.
   Koskotas arrived in America days after he fled Greece in
November. He was arrested and jailed in Salem, Mass., where he has
granted interviews to the media. He awaits hearing on a Greek
petition for his extradition.
   The $200 million embezzlement scandal at the Bank of Crete has
been front page news in Greece since it broke last October.
   Eight ministers resigned and eight PASOK-appointed officials
from state enterprises were accused of accepting ``stolen money''
from the Bank of Crete and were imprisoned.
   Koskotas' bodyguards told investigators they personally
delivered cartons stuffed with tens of thousands of dollars to a
close friend of the premier's.
   At an earlier news briefing this month, spokesman Kostopoulos
branded Koskotas a ``swindler'' who had connections with
high-ranking American officials and alleged that they were behind
the scandal.
   He echoed Papandreou's repeated charges that foreign
decision-making centers initiated the campaign to undermine Greece
and smear the premier's name.
</TEXT>
