<HEAD>Salcido Told Mother On Day Of Slayings That He Expected To Die</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Winery Slayings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   On the day Ramon Salcido allegedly began a
deadly rampage through the California wine country, he called his
mother in Mexico and sobbed: ``Mama, this is the last time you will
hear my voice.''
   Valentina Bojorquez Armendariz could not recall exactly what her
oldest son said Friday, but remembered him saying ``I have problems
and I'm going to kill myself,'' or ``I have problems and they're
going to kill me.''
   Ms. Bojorquez, 49, was interviewed at home in Los Mochis,
Mexico, by the Los Angeles Times before Salcido's arrest Wednesday
by Mexican federal agents outside Guasave, a village in Sinaloa
state just north of his hometown.
   Salcido has been sought by California authorities since Friday's
discovery of the bodies of his wife, mother-in-law, two young
sisters-in-law and a co-worker at the Sonoma County winery where he
was employed.
   Three of his little daughters were found with their throats
slashed the next day. Two were dead but one survived and has begun
to recover.
   Ms. Bojorquez said her son hung up and she had not heard from
him again, but she learned from news accounts that he was wanted
for the slayings.
   She said before his arrest that she believed it would be best
for him to give up.
   ``If he's not guilty, he should have nothing to fear. ... He
believed in his family,'' she said. ``He loved them and was very
proud of them. I don't believe that Ramon could have done this.''
