<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Defense     04-19 0446</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Defense,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>No Decision On Missiles</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush told a group of congressional
leaders Wednesday that he hasn't decision on future development of
the MX nuclear missile, the legislators said.
   ``He's indicated he's working on the MX issue and he's anxious
to receive the input from a wide variety of individuals on Capitol
Hill,'' said Sen. John Warner, R-Va. ``He did not in any way strike
a note of finality.''
   Warner and other legislators said they didn't know whether Bush
would support building a mobile version of the MX, would back the
smaller Midgetman missile, or some combination of the two.
   Bush discussed the issue with House and Senate members of both
parties. He convened the group, along with his top foreign policy
advisers, in what he intends to use as an occasional chance to
consult with them on general foreign policy, his staff said.
   The missile question is part of an effort to build new weapons
for the land-based leg of the U.S. nuclear arsenal. Bush's options
are to base new 10-warhead MX missiles on rail cars, a system
favored by Air Force generals, or develop a new single-warhead
missile known as the Midgetman, to be housed on trucks.
   The Midgetman is far more costly, with a price tag of nearly $24
billion for 500 single-warhead missiles, compared to $5.4 billion
for the same capability on the multi-warhead MX, according to Air
Force estimates.
   The United States currently has 50 MX missiles based in silos in
Wyoming and Nebraska, in addition to the multi-warhead Minuteman
missiles.
   The Soviets have deployed two mobile systems, the SS-25 with one
warhead and the SS-24, with 10 warheads.
   Rep. Les Aspin, D-Wis., chairman of the House Armed Services
Committee, said ``Those of us who think it's important to have a
Midgetman in the package got to make our case. If the president's
made his mind up, he didn't reveal it.''
   Aspin said he argued that the issue is ``critically important''
for achieving a strategic arms reduction treaty with the Soviets.
   The Bush administration is engaged in an overall review of
national security and foreign policy.
   Members of Congress who met with Bush didn't fault the White
House for that long process.
   `This is a new administration. It's a new Congress. I don't know
who came up with the idea that President Bush could just simply
move in and everything would be right on track and there would be
no review no slowdown,'' said Rep. Dante Fascell, D-Fla., chairman
of the House Foreign Affairs Committee. ``They're not taking
anything at face value or past value. I find that very comforting.''
</TEXT>
