<FIRST>r w AM-Kemp-Vouchers     04-19 0494</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Kemp-Vouchers,1st ld-writethru, a0744,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 4th graf to add committee vote; adds graf at end to include
Mikulski quote</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENISE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Housing Secretary Jack Kemp on Wednesday eased
away from a commitment by the Bush administration to replace
expiring housing subsidy certificates with vouchers.
   While not announcing a policy reversal, Kemp told a House
subcommittee that the Department of Housing and Urban Development
was looking ``for some way to take the best characteristics of the
Section 8 certificate and the voucher and marry them.''
   ``I don't want to be the secretary of vouchers. I really,
strongly believe we need housing and economic development and
vouchers are a tool to give people a choice,'' said Kemp.
   Kemp's comments came in an apppearance before the House
Appropriations Subcommittee on HUD and independent agencies where
he presented the agency's 1990 budget request a day after the full
committee voted to add $153 million under the McKinney Homeless
Assistance Act to the agency's 1989 budget. department's 1990
budget request.
   Replacement of certificates with vouchers originated with former
President Reagan's 1990 budget proposal and was retained in the
revisions Bush submitted to Congress in February.
   About 1 million low-income households receive rental assistance
subsidies through the two programs.
   Subsidies in the HUD section 8 certificate are based on the
difference between 30 percent of a family's adjusted monthly income
and actual rent, which cannot exceed the fair market rent for the
area in which the family lives.
   Beginning in 1989, subsidies for 780,000 certificates will
expire over a 12-year period.
   A recent study by the General Accounting Office, the
investigative arm of Congress, concluded that ``with HUD's 1989
budget request, about 9,500 or 6 percent fewer families can be
assisted with vouchers than with certificates.''
   The report also said it would cost an additional $208 million to
assist the same number of families with vouchers.
   ``They are ... more expensive than the certificate, but the
purpose was not to compete against the certificate. The purpose was
to give choice, ... give people a chance to upgrade,'' Kemp told
the panel.
   But he said he was open to looking at a mix of both as a part of
HUD's housing subsidy program.
   ``I'd also like to have somebody think of how we can take a
voucher or a certificate and have an element in there that would
give people some equity, some chance of maybe using it as a
potential for making a down payment someday,'' Kemp added.
   ``I commend Secretary Kemp for taking a fresh look at this
issue. The recent GAO report showed that the housing voucher
program hasn't lived up to expectations. I stand ready to work with
Secretary Kemp to develop a program that will provide
moderate-income pepole with the housing they need and at a price we
can afford,'' said Sen. Barbara Mikulski, D-Md., chairman of
Senate's HUD Appropriations subcommittee that had requested the GAO
study.
</TEXT>
