<FIRST>u a AM-CruseSentencing 1stLd-Writethru a0667 04-19 0416</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cruse Sentencing, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0667,0426</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Recommends Death Penalty For Shooting Spree Killer</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RETRANSMITTING a0774 to CORRECT writethru sequence; this version
updates throughout with judge accepting death penalty recommendation, comment
from prosecutors and jurors; editing to tighten; no pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BARTOW, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A retired librarian convicted of shooting
six people to death and trying to kill 24 others in a 1987 shopping
center rampage deserves the death penalty, a jury recommended
Wednesday.
   William Cruse, 61, sat hunched over the defense table and showed
no emotion as the recommendation was read to Circuit Judge John
Antoon after 1{ hours of deliberations.
   Antoon, who is not bound by the recommendation but said he would
give it great weight, set sentencing for July 28.
   The jury, which could have recommended a life prison sentence
instead of death, convicted Cruse on April 5 of 32 counts of
murder, attempted murder and kidnapping.
   The rampage occurred on April 23, 1987 at two shopping centers
in Palm Bay 30 miles south of Cape Canaveral on Florida's east
coast. The dead included two policemen.
   ``Cruse declared war on the community of Palm Bay,'' State
Attorney Norm Wolfinger said after Wednesday's decision. ``The jury
verdicts were very appropriate.''
   Jury foreman Wayne Hogan said a videotape of Cruse's police
interrogation strongly influenced the 12-member panel's decision.
Juror Edward Cook said, ``We all felt the same. He knew what he was
doing.''
   Defense attorneys refused to comment. They had contended Cruse
was insane at the time of the slayings.
   In closing arguments earlier Wednesday, State Attorney Norm
Wolfinger ridiculed the insanity defense.
   ``Evidence has shown that this defendant has forfeited his right
to live on Earth,'' the prosecutor said. ``He is a cold,
calculating killer. He deserves to die.''
   Wolfinger held up a shotgun and a semiautomatic assault rifle
used in the rampage. He pumped the shotgun several times and popped
an ammunition clip into the rifle repeatedly.
   ``He was going to kill as many people ... as he could,'' he said.
   Despite evidence of mental illness, Cruse showed he was in total
control of his faculties when he methodially tracked down his
victims and shot at them repeatedly, some as they lay wounded and
moaning on the ground, Wolfinger said.
   Assistant Public Defender Paul Arlt argued that the rampage
would never have happened if Cruse had not been suffering from
mental or emotional disturbance.
   ``Mr. Cruse that day was a bubbling cauldron'' that finally
exploded, Arlt said in his closing argument.
</TEXT>
