<FIRST>u a AM-KMartExplosion     04-19 0540</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-K Mart Explosion,0558</SECOND>
<HEAD>Five-Year-Old Bomb Victim Receives Money, Gifts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BETH HARRIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Well-wishers flooded a hospital with stuffed
animals and other gifts Wednesday for a 5-year-old girl who lost
her hand when a pipe bomb concealed in a toothpaste dispenser
exploded at a K mart.
   Erin Bower lost her left hand and may recover only partial sight
in her left eye, Methodist Hospital physicians said.
   Erin, who was shopping with her parents at the K mart Monday
night, was holding the pump-type toothpaste dispenser when it blew
up.
   Her condition was upgraded Wednesday from serious to fair, and
she was moved from the pediatric intensive care unit to a
children's room, hospital spokesman David Richards said.
   ``That's really good news,'' Richards said. ``She's taken some
7-Up and apple juice and her mood is quiet.''
   ``She's in a lot of pain, so I'm not sure how much hassunk in at
this point,'' said hospital social worker Lynn Young. ``A lot of
the questions (about the explosion) haven't come yet.''
   The hospital has received a flood of balloons, plants and
stuffed animals and hundreds of calls expressing sympathy for Erin
and her parents, who have another daughter.
   ``The first thing they say is, `This was so horrible, I just
wanted to let the parents know I'm praying for them,''' said Mrs.
Young. The bombing makes people feel ``so vulnerable, like this
could happen to anybody,'' she said. ``A nice family goes to K mart
and their life changes forever.''
   A trust fund for paying Erin's medical expenses was set up at
the First National Bank branch where her 31-year-old mother,
Maureen, is manager.
   ``People are dropping off checks and cash,'' said bank Assistant
Manager Judy Bandy. ``Everyone is concerned for the well-being of
Erin.''
   Mrs. Bowers was slightly injured by shrapnel from the bomb. No
one else was hurt.
   Investigators have received more than 200 phone calls from
people who think they can identify two men wanted for questioning
who are depicted in composite sketches circulated by the Marion
County sheriff's department.
   The men, both believed to be about 20 years old, drew police
attention because they were seen nonchalantly leaving the store
immediately after the explosion as other people reacted to the
blast.
   Authorities have been contacted by former Indianapolis residents
from as far away as Alaska, Canada and Florida, said detective Sgt.
Mike Kouns of the sheriff's department.
   ``I've got more information than I know what to do with,'' Kouns
said.
   Police and two agents from the federal Bureau of Alcohol,
Tobacco and Firearms spent Wednesday cross-checking names reported
by callers.
   Kouns said the bombing could have stemmed from a vendetta
against a K mart employee or the store itself, or may have been a
random attack.
   K mart offered up to $5,000 for information leading to the
arrest and conviction of those responsible, but sheriff's
department spokesman Scott Minier said store officials would be
urged to raise the reward to at least $10,000 ``because of the
senselessness of the crime.''
   Several Indianapolis radio stations urged listeners to
contribute to reward funds. K mart spokeswoman Leslie Kota at the
chain's Troy, Mich., headquarters, said company officials had not
discussed raising the reward.
</TEXT>
