<FIRST>u i AM-Britain-SexTales     04-19 0599</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Sex Tales,0614</SECOND>
<HEAD>Paper Prints Picture Of U.S. House Speaker And Woman in Scandal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A British tabloid, serializing the sex and scandal
memoirs of a former call girl who later worked as a government
researcher, printed a picture of her with U.S. House Speaker Jim
Wright in Thursday's editions.
   Early editions of the Daily Mail said the picture of Pamella
Bordes and the Texas Democrat, now under investigation for alleged
unethical conduct, was taken during a 1983 meeting in Wright's
office on Capitol Hill.
   The London tabloid, which bought the rights to Ms. Bordes'
story, said at that time she was working for the Indian mystic and
businessman Chandra Swami. The meeting was arranged by the Swami,
who had business connections in Washington, the paper reported.
   ``Among the things discussed, according to those close to the
Swami, was the possibility of obtaining a `green card' permit for
Pamella officially to become an American resident,'' the newspaper
said.
   ``Unknown to Jim Wright, this was at a time when she was, in her
own words, working as `sex bait' for the Swami's international
business deals. At the meeting, the Swami presented Mr. Wright with
some ceremonial gifts and pleaded with him to help Pamella.
   ``His (Wright's) staff sent a copy of this picture to Pamella
signed with his best wishes.''
   The newspaper said a spokesman for Wright said the office
remembered the meeting with Swami's group but ``did not recall
doing anything to help her obtain a green card.''
   Wright has denied charges by the House Ethics Committee that he
violated House rules in 69 instances involving an unusual book
publishing deal and his benefits from a business partnership.
   The first installment of Ms. Bordes' memoirs printed in
Wednesday's Daily Mail contained lurid tales of sex with financier
Adnan Khashoggi, with a Saudi prince and with a top aide to Libya's
Col. Moammar Gadhafi.
   The Daily Mail quoted her as saying she was introduced to life
as a jet-set call girl by Khashoggi, the Saudi billionaire arms
dealer, whom she met in Paris in 1983.
   The Mail said it was sending all its material on Miss Bordes and
Khashoggi to the FBI.
   Khashoggi was arrested Tuesday in Switzerland on a U.S.
extradition request connected with allegations he helped hide
assets belonging to deposed President Ferdinand Marcos of the
Philippines and his wife, Imelda.
   In its story, the Daily Mail quoted her as saying her bedmates
included Prince Mohammed of Saudi Arabia, with whom Khashoggi was
brokering an arms deal. The newspaper did not identify the prince
further except to say he was a senior member of the ruling family.
   The newspaper reported that she was flown to Tripoli, Libya in
1984 in the private jet of Ahmed Gadaff Al Diam, whom the Mail
identified as a cousin of the Libyan leader, second-in-command of
Libyan intelligence, and Libya's top arms buyer in Europe. She was
quoted as saying she had sex with Al Diam in Tripoli.
   Miss Bordes, 26, who was Miss India in 1982, was quoted as
saying she got money from Al Diam and stayed in touch with him
until shortly before she got a job last year as a researcher in the
British Parliament.
   It was that job that led to the British press's discovery of her
background and raised questions about whether national security was
compromised by allowing free movement in the House of Commons to a
woman with high-level Libyan connections.
   Miss Bordes fled to the island of Bali, was tracked down by
British reporters and offered her story to the highest bidder.
</TEXT>
