<FIRST>r a AM-UMassProtest     04-19 0225</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UMass Protest,0229</SECOND>
<HEAD>7 Massachusetts tudents Arrested In Protest Of Defense Department
Research</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMHERST, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seven students were arrested Wednesday
after refusing to budge from a University of Massachusetts
laboratory where they were protesting against Defense
Department-funded research.
   Campus Director of Public Safety Arthur Hilson said the three
women and four men were removed, and in some cases dragged, from
the Marcus Hall laboratory, when they remained in the building
after closing hours. He did not release their names, but said they
were being booked on trespassing charges.
   The occupation, which started at 1 p.m., stemmed from a campus
rally earlier in the day against such projects as the university's
quest for an anthrax vaccine.
   The university maintains the research focuses on a non-virulent
strain and is for peaceful purposes, but students and members of
the local chapter of the American Friends Service Committee want
the research moved off campus.
   ``It's kind of a leap to say basic research on the university
campus is somehow directly supporting a war in El Salvador,'' said
university spokeswoman Jeanne Hopkins. ``Our research here is all
basic. It's all non-classified.''
   Hilson said the students were repeatedly warned that they were
violating the student code of conduct by staying in the building
after hours. He said he consulted with school Chancellor Joseph
Duffey before ordering the arrests.
