<FIRST>u i AM-Panama-US     04-19 0282</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Panama-US,0290</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Citizens Must Now Have Special Visas To Travel To Panama</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has told airlines and
travel agencies that beginning Friday all U.S. citizens must have
visas approved by the government to visit Panama.
   The Panamanian Institute of Tourism said in a statement that
each visa must be stamped by a Panamanian consul that recognizes
the government of acting president Manuel Solis Palma.
   The majority of Panamanian consulates do not recognize the Solis
Palma government, continuing to recognize the government of
President Eric Arturo Delvalle, who was ousted in February 1988.
   Previously, U.S. citizens traveling to Panama needed a tourist
card, available at any Panamanian consulate.
   The institute, in a statement distributed to the tourist
industry, said U.S. citizens wishing to visit Panama on business
dealing with Panama Canal accords between the Panamanian and U.S.
governments must still have official permission from the Panamanian
government to enter and leave the country.
   The official permission must be sought by U.S. officials and
will remain valid as long as a U.S. citizen works with the Panaama
Canal Commission, the statement said.
   The U.S. and Panamanian governments have been at odds for more
than a year, ever since Panama's de facto leader, Gen. Manuel
Antonio Noriega, orchestrated the ouster of then-president Delvalle.
   Delvalle was ousted after he tried to fire Noriega, the Defense
Forces chief, following Noriega's indictment by a federal grand
jury in Florida on drug trafficking charges. Solis Palma was later
appointed acting president.
   The United States has imposed economic sanctions on Panama in an
attempt to force Noriega out and continues to recognize Delvalle
and reject Solis Palma as the country's legal president.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
