<FIRST>u a AM-BattleshipScene 2ndLd-Writethru a0795 04-19 0471</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Battleship Scene, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0795,0481</SECOND>
<HEAD>Anxious Families Gather To Wait For News</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 3rd graf, ``The longer ..., to include
Navy policy on notification, release of identities to news media.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Battleship Explosion, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By D.W. PAGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORFOLK, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Families of crew members aboard the USS Iowa
gathered Wednesday at a Norfolk Naval Station gym to await word
about loved ones who were on the ship when a gun turret packed with
gunpowder exploded in flames.
   ``The major problem is lack of information,'' said Navy Chaplain
Barry Brimhall, who was with the families. ``They are very, very
frustrated. For those who had husbands or sons in the area of the
explosion, they are wondering, `Was it my husband, my son?'''
   ``The longer we hear nothing, the better it is,'' said Sandy
Tate of Charleston, W.Va., a relative of crewman Jonathan Tate.
   Navy policy requires that families of dead or injured sailors be
notified before any list of victims is released to the news media,
and not all families had been notified by mid-evening Wednesday,
officials said.
   Brimhall was one of many Navy chaplains, social workers, and Red
Cross personnel called in to deal with the families' grief.
   ``The first thing we did was establish a place for them to
gather,'' said Master Chief Billy Kinder, an Atlantic Fleet
spokesman. ``We provide a place for them to be. The chaplains,
social workers, Red Cross and others are there to help them in any
way possible.''
   ``Our primary purpose,'' Brimhall said, ``is to help them air
their feelings, talk about their fears to reassure them, but be
honest. Some are going to loose a loved one. It is a ministry of
presence.''
   The families were helping each other, Brimhall said.
   ``There is a lot of support within the group. I saw
relationships develop right before my eyes as women put their arms
around those who were having touble,'' he said.
   He described the mood in the gym as varied.
   ``There are those who are really struggling and those who are
really stoic,'' he said.
   Ann Quagliotti of Brownton, W.Va., said she and her husband
hadn't been able to reach Navy officials to find out about her son,
Mark Quagliotti, a dentist on the Iowa.
   ``I have no idea where our son could be,'' Ms. Quagliotti said.
``Anything is possible.''
   The Navy's contingency plan for such tragedies was worked out
long before the accident, Kinder said.
   ``We take this very seriously. Family response crisis is a very
major issue with us,'' he said.
   Kinder said the families are given updates at least every half
hour, and more often as developments warrant.
   ``Right now, for some of these families, they would rather have
bad news than no news at all,'' Brimhall said.
</TEXT>
