<FIRST>u i AM-Bolivia-US-Cocaine     04-19 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bolivia-US-Cocaine,0301</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police, U.S. Drug Agents Seize 1,375 Pounds of Cocaine</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER McFARREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LA PAZ, Bolivia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police and U.S. Drug Enforcement
Administration agents raided a remote ranch and seized 1,375 pounds
of refined cocaine, the largest ever seized in Bolivia, U.S.
Ambassador Robert Gelbard said Wednesday.
   The cocaine was found Monday at a ranch 330 miles to the
northeast of La Paz, near the town of San Ramon, said U.S. DEA
agents involved in the seizure. Authorities said one person was
apprehended during the raid, which was first disclosed Wednesday.
   ``This is far and away the largest single amount ever caught in
Bolivia,'' Gelbard said in an interview. He said the amount _ more
than double the cocaine seized in Bolivia all last year _ indicated
a capacity of producing refined cocaine much greater than
previously estimated by U.S. authorities.
   Bolivian police authorities believe the cocaine belonged to
Carmelo Rodriguez, considered to be one of Bolivia's biggest
cocaine traffickers.
   A relative of Rodriguez owned the ranch, officials said. The DEA
said a cocaine processing lab was found and destroyed at the same
ranch in August. They said it apparently was awaiting shipment to
Colombia.
   The cocaine was seized during an operation involving 20 Bolivia
narcotics police and DEA agents who flew to the jungle ranch on
four Huey helicopters donated by the U.S. government.
   Authorities said a ranch employee was being held for questioning
at a police base in Trinidad, about 250 miles northeast of La Paz.
They said the cocaine was being held by authorities under the
supervision of the attorney general's office, which is seeking a
court order to burn it.
   During all of 1988, authorities seized 546 pounds of refined
cocaine in Bolivia, U.S. officials said.
</TEXT>
