<FIRST>u a AM-DeConcini-Karlsen     04-19 0409</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-DeConcini-Karlsen,0425</SECOND>
<HEAD>DeConcini's Longtime Campaign Treasurer Under Investigation For Theft</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Dennis DeConcini's longtime campaign
treasurer has admitted taking some $500,000 from re-election bank
accounts, the senator's spokesman said Wednesday.
   U.S. Attorney Stephen M. McNamee wouldn't say whether charges
would be filed against accountant Thomas Karlsen of Mesa, who
joined the Arizona Democrat's campaign staff in 1974.
   McNamee took depositions Wednesday from other workers in the
Arizona Democrat's office here Wednesday. ``We just had a meeting
where they presented their evidence,'' McNamee said.
   In a telephone interview from Washington, Bob Maynes,
DeConcini's press secretary, said Karlsen promised to pay back the
money which he admitted to taking.
   ``But I think that to repay implies an ability that I do not
know is there,'' Maynes said. ``He said he would do everything he
could to make restitution, and he does have some financial
resources.''
   He said DeConcini was saddened by what he viewed as betrayal by
an insider.
   Karlsen has an unlisted phone number and could not be reached
for comment. Maynes said the Tempe resident was still in the
Phoenix area, but had ``left town'' April 10, leaving behind a note
that he didn't plan to return.
   ``He changed his mind and came back to the Phoenix area Sunday,
and he called Monday and admitted that he had done this,'' Maynes
said.
   He said it wasn't known how much money was missing. ``We're in
the process of trying to reconstruct the events,'' Maynes said.
   The funds apparently were withdrawn from certificate-of-deposit
accounts after they had been recorded, Maynes said.
   The first thefts took place about 1981, he said. Since then,
Karlsen has been divorced twice and had a series of business
reversals through his Karlsen &amp; Karlsen firm, Maynes added.
   Karlsen has been treasurer for several other Democrats,
including Richard Kimball, who ran unsuccessfully for a U.S. Senate
seat, and Gov. Rose Mofford.
   Mofford campaign finance committee Chairwoman Lorraine Frank
said Karlsen resigned last week. She said no money was missing from
the governor's coffers.
   State Board of Accountancy records show Karlsen was certified as
a public accountant in 1972. Two years later, he met DeConcini and
became treasurer in time to help in DeConcini's successful 1976
campaign.
   A survey by the Common Cause organization showed DeConcini had a
$502,000 campaign surplus as of Dec. 31. The survey also said
DeConcini, whose 1988 campaign raised $3.3 million, had the
sixth-largest surplus among incumbent Senate candidates.
</TEXT>
