<SECOND>AM-North Jurors,0327</SECOND>
<HEAD>North Trial Jurors Lied On Questionnaire, Network Reports</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-North Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two jurors and an alternate juror in the
Iran-Contra trial of Oliver North did not tell the truth when they
said they had never been involved in court proceedings, ABC-TV news
reported Wednesday.
   The three could be disqualified, the network reported on ``World
News Tonight'' on the eve of jury deliberations in the trial of the
former White House aide.
   The jury is expected to begin deliberating Thursday after a
rebuttal argument by prosecutor John Keker and final instructions
from U.S. District Judge Gerhard A. Gesell.
   ABC said the jurors apparently did not give full answers in a
questionnaire in which they were asked whether they or any member
of their families had ever been involved in civil or criminal court
proceedings.
   One juror answered ``no'' even though he was sued for $100,000
in 1981 as a result of an auto accident, and another juror said
``no'' even though she was sued in 1982 for $50,000 following a car
crash, ABC said.
   Both lawsuits were settled but constitute court proceedings
anyway, according to ABC.
   If Gesell decided to disqualify either or both jurors, the first
alternate would be named to take their place.
   That juror also answered ``no'' to the question but, ABC said a
computer check at Superior Court showed that the alternate was
arrested twice on drug charges and was put on probation for a year.
   Gesell was told of the findings but declined to comment, the
network said.
   North, a former Marine lieutenant colonel, was a major figure in
the Iran-Contra scandal. He is charged with 12 criminal counts. The
charges include lying to Congress and the attorney general,
illegally converting traveler's checks to his own use and
conspiring to defraud the Treasury through a tax scam to support
the Contra rebels fighting the Nicaraguan government.
</TEXT>
