<FIRST>r a AM-PotomacView     04-19 0398</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Potomac View,0410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Homeowner Sentenced To 15 Days For Cutting Trees To Improve View</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEX DOMINGUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge sentenced a Potomac man to 15
days in jail and fined him $20,000 Tuesday for cutting down 138
trees on a national park near his home to get a view of the Potomac
River.
   ``It is true that the area can be restored, but only with great
expense of time and resources, so a message must be sent to
others,'' U.S. District Judge J. Joseph Howard said while
sentencing Isaac Fogel. ``That message, gentlemen, is that one may
forfeit his or her liberty.''
   Fogel, 45, had the trees removed, then advertised his home has
having a river view, the government said in its indictment.
   ``I was willing to settle this thing when I first talked to the
parks department if they hadn't insisted on branding me a
criminal,'' Fogel said before sentencing.
   He was convicted earlier this year of destruction of government
timber, a misdemeanor, and disposing of government property, a
felony.
   He faced a maximum sentence of 11 years in prison and $350,000
in fines. Prosecutors recommended a $64,000 fine and a 60-day
sentence.
   ``I think the court gave the sentence we recommended serious
consideration and we are pleased with the sentence,'' Assistant
U.S. Attorney David King said.
   The 138 trees in the Chesapeake and Ohio Canal National
Historical Park were valued at more than $30,000. King asked the
judge to fine Fogel twice the replacement value of the trees as
punishment.
   Fogel, president of a water bed manufacturing company in Jessup,
and his wife, Jo, bought the house in 1982, the indictment said.
   In March 1985, despite discussions with National Park Service
officials about what timber could be cut, Fogel hired a tree
service company to cut down the trees, the goverment contended.
   Fogel and his wife later listed the house and four acres for
sale, advertising it as having a river view, the indictment said.
The house, which has not been sold, was assessed for tax purposes
in 1986 at $381,510.
   Howard sentenced Fogel to concurrent three-year and six-month
sentences, suspending all but 15 days of the three-year sentence
and the entire six-month sentence. Fogel was also ordered to serve
two years' probation upon his release and perform 300 hours of
community service.
   Fogel is considering an appeal.
</TEXT>
