<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-89 0338EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Citicorp-SoAfrica     04-19 0341</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Citicorp-SoAfrica,0356</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shareholders Reject Lending Resolution</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Citicorp shareholders have overwhelmingly
rejected requests from church groups led by the Rev. Jesse Jackson
and representatives of South African Archbishop Desmond Tutu to
sever all remaining ties with racially segregated South Africa.
   Citicorp, the nation's largest banking company, stopped doing
business in that country two years ago when it sold its Citibank
N.A. Ltd. subsidiary to First National Bank of Southern Africa
Ltd., South Africa's largest bank, for about $65 million.
   But Citicorp, like some other U.S. banks, still has about $666
million in private outstanding loans to South African borrowers. It
recently agreed to extend by 10 years payments on the bulk of that
debt, and accept partial principal payment as part of an agreement
with other international banks.
   South Africa had placed a temporary moratorium on principal
payments of bank debt in September 1985.
   The church groups had asked that Citicorp, which remains the
largest U.S. commercial bank creditor of that country, to refuse to
reschedule South African debt and make any new loans as long as the
present political system remains intact.
   ``By extending this debt we're expressing a tolerance of South
Africa,'' Jackson said Tuesday at Citicorp's annual shareholders
meeting. ``We must make a moral judgment.''
   Citicorp Chairman John Reed said that while his company opposes
South Africa's apartheid system ``debt forgiveness is a word you'll
never hear from this bank.''
   ``Our objective is simple and straightforward: We would like to
be paid back. It's not a question of morals ... it's a question of
business judgment,'' he explained.
   Citicorp shareholders also agreed, with 91.6 percent of them
voting against a proposal to abandon debt rescheduling agreements
with South Africa, vs. 8.4 percent approving it. The remaining
abstained.
   The shareholders also rejected a request by the church groups
for Citicorp to end corresponent banking with South Africa, in
which it performs services for firms not having access to direct
facilities. The vote was 89.2 percent opposed, 10.8 percent in
agreement and the rest abstaining.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
