<DOCNO> AP890419-0226 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-89 0339EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-EconomicsRap Bjt   04-19 0596</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Economics Rap, Bjt,0629</SECOND>
<HEAD>Teacher Gets Kids Rappin' Economics With `RUN G.N.P.'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ross Kapstein has been teaching long enough to
know that kids aren't exactly wild about learning economics. So he
came up with a novel way of presenting the often-dry curriculum:
through the lyrics of rap music.
   Kapstein, who has dabbled in the music business as a performer
and manager during his 18 years as a public school teacher, wrote
and recorded ``RUN G.N.P.,'' a rappin' tribute to the joys of
economics.
   He also had some of his students at Martin Luther King Jr.
Middle School participate in making a video version of the song.
Kapstein uses both as motivational tools to make economics seem
less imposing to the 6th-, 7th- and 8th-grade students in his
social studies and history classes.
   Rather than the academic words of a textbook, Kapstein believes
teachers could better introduce young students to economic concepts
with such lines as:
   ``Try to maximize profits
   Minimize costs
   That's what I'm tryin' to do
   Increase productivity
   Improve the quality
   So I can bring the best product to you.''
   Or how about this explanation of supply and demand:
   ``Now, when resources get scarce
   or demand increases
   the price of goods rise
   it rarely decreases.
   People's tastes change
   and so do I
   If I want to stay in business
   I'd better comply.''
   And, you can dance to it.
   ``I thought it was a good idea in this day and age, when kids
can rap and memorize pages and pages of (entertainment)
information, why not do something educational to go along with
it,'' Kapstein said in a recent interview.
   ``Economics is sometimes boring and difficult,'' he said. ``I
saw this would be a really nice idea. Hell, I write music, songs _
I said let me put something together.''
   Kapstein, 40, recorded the song, whose title was inspired by rap
stars RUN D.M.C., with a small group of professional musicians. He
hopes to release it as a single for use by other teachers.
   The video, set in a city park, has the ragged feel of a home
movie, but Kapstein said he'd like to make a more polished version
if he can obtain money to cover production costs.
   Economics is just a small part of the middle school curriculum.
But Kapstein believes that if his musical efforts are successful,
students will be more inclined toward the subject when they reach
high school.
   ``Kids in high school really put it off ... it's something that
really has a low priority,'' Kapstein said. ``We try to dispel the
myths, so it's not a terrible monster.
   ``It can ba a lot of fun, economics can be made easy,'' he
added. ``When they get into economics is high school, they're gonna
say, `Yeah.'''
   Kapstein said the seeds of his idea were planted a couple of
years ago when he enrolled in a program at Georgia State
University's Center for Business &amp; Economic Education that stressed
creative and unusual approaches to teaching.
   Mixing music and economics was a natural for him, Kapstein said.
   ``I've always been into motivating the kids through music,''
said Kapstein, who in the 1970s managed the career of the late
blues singer Willie Guy Rainey.
   ``I used to bring in Willie Guy during Black History Month, and
he was the most effective,'' he said.
   Kapstein said he has other ideas, but for now he's waiting to
see if ``RUN G.N.P.'' catches on.
   ``If things take off, I'll be turning out songs like crazy,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
