<FIRST>r f PM-AgingTurboprops     04-19 0403</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Aging Turboprops,0413</SECOND>
<HEAD>Firm Says Turboprop Fleet Younger Than Jetliner Fleet</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Aircraft Order, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The average age of planes in the fleet of
turboprop aircraft used by airlines in North America is 3.1 years
younger than the average for the jetliner fleet, says an aviation
consulting firm.
   The average age of turboprop aircraft used by airlines in the
United States and Canada is 9.3 years, while the average age of jet
aircraft is 12.4 years, according to a study released Tuesday by
Avmark, Inc., which appraises aircraft throughout the world.
   The report prepared for the Regional Airline Association's
International Conference on Aging Commuter Aircraft in Kansas City,
Mo., next week says the average age for the worldwide fleet of
turboprops is 11 years old, compared with more than 13 years for
passenger jets.
   The study, which groups aircraft by regions of the world, says
the North American turboprop fleet is the youngest, while the
Middle East has the oldest aircraft with an average age of 15.4
years. Turboprops in Asia and Australia average 13.5 years, in
Latin America 13 years, in Africa 12.4 years and in Europe 12.1
years, according to the report.
   ``The average age of the commuter-regional turboprop fleet is
expected to experience a decline as the operators continue to
expand their operations through acquisition of a substantial number
of new aircraft in the next decade,'' the report says.
   It says 68.1 percent of the turboprops in North America were
built within the last nine years, while 7.6 percent were built 20
or more years ago. The oldest turboprops are those that carry 40 to
50 passengers, while the youngest are in the 20-39 passenger
category.
   The youngest fleets, according to Avmark, belong to the Midway
Express system, 3.4 years, and Piedmont Commuter, 3.8 years, while
the oldest are operated by Air Canada Connector, 13.2 years, and
Aloha Island, 12.7 years.
   Other fleets in the report and the average age of their
turboprop planes are Delta Connection, 5.6; American Eagle, 5.7;
Northwest Airlink, 6.5; United Express, 6.6; Eastern Express, 7.1;
TWExpress, 7.9; Allegheny Commuter, 8.1; Alaska Commuter, 9.0; Pan
Am Express, 10; Continental Express, 10.8, and Canadian Partner, 11.
   The report covers airplanes in use as of July 1988 and covers
those seating 13 passegners or more that were originally designed
for passenger use although a few are now being used to haul cargo,
Avmark said.
</TEXT>
