<FIRST>r f PM-AircraftSales     04-19 0258</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Aircraft Sales,0270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Small Aircraft Sales Up, Billings Down</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Jet Order, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of new single-engine aircraft sold
by U.S. manufacturers increased 28.5 percent in the first quarter,
but sales of all other types of smaller aircraft decreased from the
same period last year, an industry group reported.
   In 1988, the small-aircraft industry reported its first increase
in a decade of both the number and value of planes delivered. The
figures cover sales of civilian planes that carry fewer than 20
passengers and generally are not used by scheduled airlines.
   The first-quarter report released Tuesday by the General
Aviation Manufacturers Association, based on delivery of aircraft,
showed 212 single-engine planes sold, compared with 165 in the
year-ago quarter.
   Sales of jet planes dropped from 34 to 23, while turboprop sales
were down from 52 to 51 and twin-engine aircraft from 23 to 18.
   Sales reached $302.97 million for the first quarter, compared
with $377.46 for the first quarter of 1988, and the value of
aircraft sold abroad dropped to $97.5 million from last year's
$158.52 million for the quarter, the association reported.
   ``The increase in total aircraft deliveries is an encouraging
sign,'' said Edward M. Stimpson, the association's president. But,
he said, the industry has been ``devastated by unfair product
liability laws.'' The association supports bills introduced in
Congress that would limit the liability of manufacturers.
   Stimpson said increased funding to modernize airports is also
needed for the industry to grow.
   The association represents 36 manufacturers of aircraft, engines
and related equipment.
</TEXT>
