<FIRST>r f PM-Whittle-Books Bjt   04-19 0650</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Whittle-Books, Bjt,0671</SECOND>
<HEAD>Whittle Communications Plans To Publish Ad-Sponsored Books</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Whittle Communications LP wants to put short
hardcover books by respected authors in the briefcases of America's
corporate and civic leaders, and is selling advertising space in
the books to pay the bill.
   The proposal disclosed Tuesday stirred curiosity in the
publishing community, which has generally limited advertising in
hardcover books to pitches for either the author's or the
publisher's other works.
   ``Whether it is a ridiculous idea that will fall on its face or
be the wave of the future, I can't tell yet,'' said Joni Evans, the
publisher of Random House.
   Nansey Neiman, publisher of Warner Books, said she hasn't
decided whether advertising in books would be good for business.
But, she added, ``As a reader, I'm not sure I want to read a book
and find an ad for baby powder, or worse.''
   The Knoxville, Tenn.-based Whittle said Tuesday it has signed
David Halberstam, John Kenneth Galbraith and seven other well-known
authors for the first of what it says will be several sponsored
book series.
   It would be the first book publishing venture by the
fast-growing media concern, which has specialized in creating
magazines, posters and television programs that sponsors may use to
reach tightly-defined audiences such as new mothers, pet owners or
teens at school.
   Whittle, which is 50 percent-owned by the media giant Time Inc.,
said it plans to publish the first book in what is tentatively
called ``The Larger Agenda'' series later this year. It plans five
books a year.
   The other authors signed by Whittle are George Gilder, Edward J.
Epstein, James Atlas, Robert Waterman, Richard Holbrooke, Daniel
Seligman and William Greider. They are reportedly being paid an
average of $60,000 each.
   Among the topics, Epstein will write about Michael Milken, the
indicted junk bond pioneer; Holbrooke will explain why business
people should care about foreign policy; and Greider will write
about the financial system.
   The books will run about 100 pages, with 20 pages of advertising
scattered among 80 pages of editorial text, and will be sent for
free to about 150,000 people Whittle considers opinion leaders.
   Christopher Whittle, chairman of Whittle Communications, said
the project resulted from research that showed many readers failed
to read or finish books because the books were too long and they
had too little time.
   He said writers, meanwhile, wanted an outlet longer than
magazines provide but shorter than full-length books.
   Advertising support provided the financial bridge needed to
support the shorter books, he said.
   Greider, reached in Washington, D.C., said liked getting a
``chance to reach what should be a pretty blue-chip audience'' and
had no problem with the type of advertising he expects would be
included in the series.
   ``If the book was studded with truss ads and hair-restoring ads
and breast implant ads, I could see how you might have some
problems with it,'' he said.
   Whittle plans to sell copies at bookstores nationwide six months
after the free distribution and will sell them more cheaply than
books without ads.
   Whittle officials declined to identify advertisers, but a source
familiar with the plans, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
Federal Express Co. of Memphis, Tenn., will be the sole advertiser
in the first series.
   Federal Express spokesman Jim Coleman said that for competitive
reasons, the company does not comment on its advertising plans.
   Carolyn Reidy, president and publisher of Avon Books, said
paperbacks once routinely carried ads two decades ago but the
practice was phased out because of postal regulations and protests
from authors. ``I don't think there will be a rush to do it
again,'' she said.
   Whittle said he hoped to be publishing up to 40 books a year
generating $50 million in annual revenue for his company in five
years. The company had $150 million in revenue last year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890419-0233 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-89 0344EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Ramada Bjt   04-19 0643</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ramada, Bjt,0670</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ramada Agrees To Sell Hotel Group, Change Name</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MEL REISNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ramada Inc. says it will sell its hotel division
to a Hong Kong firm and give up its 30-year-old trademark of
roadside hospitality as it concentrates on its gambling operations
in a bid to restore profitability.
   Ramada announced an agreement Tuesday to sell its 825-unit hotel
group and the Ramada name to New World Development Co. for $540
million.
   No name has been chosen for the restructured Ramada, said Ramada
spokesman Joe Cole.
   The restructuring was announced last October after Ramada
rejected a takeover bid by the Pritzker family of Chicago, owners
of the Hyatt hotel chain.
   Cole said Phoenix-based Ramada will keep its four casinos _ one
in Atlantic City, N.J., and three in Nevada _ and concentrate on
turning a profit. The company has no immediate expansion plans, he
said.
   Ramada lost $5.1 million last year.
   The hotel group operates under the Ramada Inns, Ramada Hotels,
Rodeway Inns and Renaissance Hotels names.
   Prime Motor Inns of Fairfield, N.J., will pay an undisclosed sum
to New World to operate as franchisor of roughly 600 of the
moderately priced hotels and motels in the United States under the
Ramada and Rodeway names.
   New World, a major real estate company, would be left with about
125 hotels overseas and 15 Renaissance Hotels domestically, Ramada
said.
   Gaming commissions in Nevada and New Jersey, the U.S. Securities
and Exchange Commission and the approximately 31,000 Ramada
stockholders must approve the transaction, Cole said.
   Ramada shareholders will get $7 a share in cash and a
one-quarter share in the new gaming company.
   Cole also announced a preliminary estimate of first-quarter
results showing revenues of $124 million and an operating loss of
$19 million. Ramada had sales of $101.9 million and a $364,000
operating loss in the year-earlier quarter.
   Ramada stock closed at $11.37{, down 75 cents.
   The transaction is a major step in Ramada's restructuring plan,
begun last October, Chairman Richard Snell said.
   ``New World and Prime are making a major commitment to achieve
success for the 800-plus hotels in the Ramada and Rodeway
systems,'' Snell said in a statement. ``The present Ramada Inc.
shareholders will benefit from their investment with cash and a
continuing interest in the new gaming company.''
   Ramada announced March 24 that it had agreed to sell the 152
restaurants in its Marie Callender Pie Shops restaurant unit to a
group of private investors. That sale for undisclosed terms will be
completed by the end of the month, Cole said.
   Cole said the restructuring would be completed within two to
three months.
   Ramada operates the TropWorld Casino and Entertainment Resort in
Atlantic City, recently refurbished for $200 million and reopened
as the largest casino there.
   The $60 million Ramada Express Hotel Casino opened last June in
Laughlin, Nev. The two other holdings are the Tropicana Resort and
Casino in Las Vegas and Eddie's Fabulous 50's Casino in Reno.
   The new company will employ about 10,000 people, Cole said.
Ramada currently employs about 20,000 _ half in its gaming
operations, 5,600 in the hotel group, and about 3,400 in the
restaurant business.
   Studies last year persuaded Ramada's board of directors that
gaming was the way to profitability.
   Ramada last year received $477 million in revenue from casino
operations and $244 million from hotels and motels. Ramada had
income from continuing operations from casinos of $40 million and
operating income from hotels and motels of $15 million.
   Ramada was started by investors who opened a motel in Flagstaff
in 1954.
   The group's first motels went by the Flamingo or Hiway House
names. When the first franchise was awarded in 1959, the name was
changed to Ramada, a Spanish word meaning ``shady resting place''
and applied to an open, gazebo-like structure offering shade in
treeless areas.
</TEXT>
