<DOCNO> AP890419-0234 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-89 0352EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Eastern-FrequentFlier Bjt   04-19 0677</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern-Frequent Flier, Bjt,0697</SECOND>
<HEAD>Frequent Flier Who Intervened In Eastern Case Wants Airline Back</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN S. CARLSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Even if the strike against Eastern Airlines is
never resolved, Moreton Rolleston Jr. figures his pilot son and
flight attendant daughter-in-law eventually will find work. But
he's worried about the effect on competition at Atlanta's airport.
   The 71-year-old Atlanta lawyer said Tuesday he intervened in
Eastern's bankruptcy case because he wants to make sure the idled
airline returns to operation.
   ``This is real important to Atlanta,'' Rolleston said in an
interview. ``Eastern had been running 100,000 people to Atlanta
every day, 290 flights a day. Forty percent of the traffic in
Atlanta was Eastern.''
   U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Burton R. Lifland in New York scheduled a
hearing for next week on Rolleston's motion to have the court to
appoint a trustee to run Eastern until parent Texas Air Corp. can
sell it.
   Rolleston was allowed to intervene in the case because he is a
member of Eastern's frequent flier program, which is run jointly
with sister carrier Continental Airlines. Since he has mileage
credits in the program, which rewards frequent fliers with free
trips, the court considered him an Eastern creditor.
   Eastern spokeswoman Karen Ceremsak said Texas Air's current
position is that Eastern is no longer for sale and instead will be
trimmed to a smaller size and remain in operation as part of its
bankruptcy reorganization.
   She said Rolleston ``is the father of a striking Eastern pilot
and the father-in-law of a striking Eastern flight attendant, so
his interests are more than those of a frequent traveler.''
   ``I'm not a stockholder. I have no financial connection with
Eastern. I have not sought out anybody to buy it. I have no strings
attached, although I do have a personal interest,'' he said.
   ``My son is a captain with Eastern; he's been with Eastern for
22 years, and my daughter-in-law is a flight attendant,'' Rolleston
said. ``I'm not going to give you his name because my family is not
part of this. What I did, I did as a lawyer and I did it before any
of them knew about it.''
   Since Eastern went on strike, he said, ``you can't get out of
Atlanta unless you're on Delta'' Air Lines, which is based in
Atlanta.
   And Delta's flights are so crowded since the Eastern strike,
it's cramping his traveling style. Used to having a choice of
flight times, Rolleston complained that, to go to a bankruptcy
court hearing on Eastern on Monday, ``I could only get one flight
out to New York Sunday.''
   Eastern workers have been on strike since March 4, contending
Texas Air Chairman Frank Lorenzo has damaged the airline and
plotted to destroy their unions by transferring valuable assets to
Continental.
   Lorenzo put Eastern into bankruptcy court refuge March 9 and has
been seeking a buyer. Ex-baseball Commissioner Peter Ueberroth
nearly completed a $464 million deal to buy Eastern. But the sale
fell through over a dispute between the unions and Lorenzo over who
would run the airlines until Ueberroth's investor group could
assume control.
   ``Regardless of whether you agree with them or not _ and I'm not
going to take a position on that _ the employees are not going to
go back to work as long as Lorenzo controls Eastern,'' Rolleston
said. ``If you had a trustee, the employees would go back to work.''
   Rolleston said his son isn't angry that his father jumped into
the fray.
   ``He went to New York with me (for a hearing earlier this week),
but he's not in the lawsuit, and he doesn't want to get involved in
the legal end of it,'' Rolleston said.
   Rolleston said his family's involvement in the company isn't the
reason he's trying to get Eastern back into operation anyway.
   ``This is real important to this city,'' he said. ``The fact
that it'll help my son and daughter-in-law is fine, but they'll be
back flying one of these days anyway. I want Eastern Airlines
flying here in Atlanta.''
</TEXT>
