<DOCNO> AP890419-0235 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-89 0358EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Northwest Bjt   04-19 0664</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Northwest, Bjt,0684</SECOND>
<HEAD>Davis Financing Plan Earns Respect From Analysts</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Eastern-Frequent Flier, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Analysts say billionaire oilman Marvin Davis
has obtained financing that will support a bid of more than $100 a
share for NWA Inc., a belief reflected by the sharp climb in the
stock price of the parent of Northwest Airlines.
   NWA's stock closed Tuesday at $97.38, up $7.13. It was the most
active issue on the New York Stock Exchange, with 3.5 million
shares trading hands.
   ``This should flush out any competing bids and probably a higher
bid from Davis,'' said Louis Marckesano, an analyst for Janney
Montgomery Scott Inc. of Philadelphia.
   Davis has said he would consider increasing his bid of $2.7
billion, or $90 a share, but did not offer a higher price Tuesday.
NWA's board has rejected his current bid as inadequate and on
Monday directed management to explore a wide range of possible
deals to maximize shareholder value.
   Marckesano said the board's announcement may have played the
biggest role in making the stock jump. But part of the momentum
came from the realization that Davis' $3.3 billion financial
package could support a bid of up to $110 a share, said Kurt Rivard
of Minneapolis-based Dain Bosworth Inc.
   ``It's a very strong financing package,'' said Sandy Schuele,
who operates a small hedge fund in Plainfield, N.H. ``If there is
anyone else in the wings, they would have to surface now. If they
don't surface, there is no one else in the wings.''
   The package would include $300 million of Davis' own money, a
$600 million bond offering and a $500 million loan from Citibank.
The balance would be a loan arranged by Citicorp North America Inc.
from a syndicate of major banks, Davis said.
   In addition, Citibank would provide a $250 million backup
revolving line of credit to be available to supplement NWA's
working capital, Davis said.
   ``Citibank wouldn't undertake this unless they felt their client
had a serious purpose,'' Schuele said.
   In state government circles, where officials have expressed fear
that Davis would break up the Eagan-based airline to pay takeover
debt, there was some criticism of the financial package.
   Minnesota Commerce Commissioner Michael Hatch said the package
would require annual debt payments of up to $450 million, depending
on the interest rates.
   ``The company had a profit last year of $135 million,'' Hatch
said. ``Where does he get the other $300 million? What he presented
today doesn't give that answer and very frankly that's the
question.''
   Hatch has supported efforts in the Minnesota Legislature to pass
laws that would discourage a takeover of Northwest, which employs
more than 15,000 people in the state. Gov. Rudy Perpich said
actions are still being pursued on the state and federal levels to
thwart a takeover even though he believes Davis is determined to
buy Northwest.
   Davis repeated Tuesday that he would not have to sell
``strategic'' assets or cut employment to finance the takeover.
   Mark Daugherty, an analyst with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. of New
York, said Davis would have second thoughts about not selling
strategic assets if a recession develops. He said the debt load of
Davis' plan would be ``burdensome'' on the airline.
   NWA has said it will provide non-public information to Davis and
other ``qualified third parties'' interested in buying the company.
Management has received approval to negotiate with Davis, but
neither the company nor a Davis spokesman in New York would say
whether the two sides had made contact.
   NWA's board also said it would explore restructuring moves
including the acquisition of another company, a partial or complete
liquidation of the airline, a repurchase of shares, a special
dividend to shareholders, or a sale of equity to third parties.
   William Genoese, who heads the airline division of the
International Brotherhood of Teamsters, on Friday said Northwest
might be considering buying financially troubled Pan American World
Airways. The company would not comment on the rumor.
</TEXT>
