<FIRST>r f PM-PrimeComputer     04-19 0318</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Prime Computer,0328</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Continues Injunction Against Prime Takeover</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has refused to lift an injunction
against MAI Basic Four Inc.'s $970 million hostile bid for Prime
Computer Inc.
   U.S. District Court Judge A. David Mazzone said Tuesday he would
not remove the injunction until MAI, a Tustin, Calif., computer
firm, provides Prime stockholders with audited year-end financial
statements from MAI's investment bank, Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.
   The ruling will further delay MAI's $20-per-share tender offer
for Prime, a Natick-based computer maker with revenue of $1.59
billion last year. The tender offer has been enjoined since Dec. 9
when Mazzone ruled that Drexel's involvement in the takeover battle
was so extensive that the bank should be considered a co-bidder and
had to disclose financial information.
   ``We are very gratified that Judge Mazzone has ordered MAI and
Drexel to make the disclosures we have been seeking for five
months,'' said Prime spokesman Joseph Gavaghan.
   MAI also is waging a proxy battle for control of Prime's board
of directors at the company's June 14 annual meeting. Prime
Chairman David J. Dunn said the current board is committed to
selling the company but considers MAI's offer too low.
   MAI filed financial disclosure documents with the Securities and
Exchange Commission April 6 in an effort to satisfy Mazzone and
remove the injunction.
   In his ruling Tuesday, the judge said most of those documents,
including a list of Drexel's trades in Prime stock, were adequate.
But he said Drexel's statement of financial condition, which was
for the first nine months of 1988, was not current enough.
   Mazzone said he would not lift the injunction until 10 days
after MAI certifies that it has mailed Drexel's year-end statement
to Prime stockholders.
   At the same time, the judge denied a motion from Prime to place
another injunction on the offer because of alleged violations of
Federal Reserve margin requirements.
</TEXT>
