<DOCNO> AP890419-0239 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-89 0931EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-EEC-Plessey     04-19 0327</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EEC-Plessey,0339</SECOND>
<HEAD>EEC Plans To Clear Plessey Takeover Bid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The EEC Commission plans to clear the
$3 billion takeover bid for Britain's defense-electronics company,
Plessey, by Siemens of West Germany and General Electric Co. of
Britain, it was announced Wednesday.
   If the provisional decision by the European Economic Community
is confirmed, it could clear the way for the creation of a new
electronics giant in Europe.
   In a statement, the EEC's competition commissioner Sir Leon
Brittan said the commission ``had come to the conclusion that the
proposed arrangements do not raise objections under the EEC's
competition rules.''
   Brittan stressed, however, that all parties concerned and the
public would be invited to comment before a final decision was made.
   He said that Plessey would have six weeks to respond to the
commission. Then, according to what the company says in its
response, the commission would either confirm its decision or look
at the case again.
   The EEC's opinion was issued prior to the publication in Britain
of a review of the bid by the British Monopolies and Mergers
Commission.
   Brittan said his proposed clearance of the bid excluded
Plessey's defense interests because EEC rules allow member states
to take unilateral measures necessary to protect these interests.
   He said that General Electric Co. (GEC) and Siemens had pledged
to maintain Plessey's semi-conductor activities as a distinct
company under Plessey management and to support related research
and development.
   The commission said that GEC and Siemens agreed not to make any
``substantial modifications'' in those activities without obtaining
the approval of the EEC.
   EEC antitrust officials launched the probe into the bid for
Plessey after the company asked the commission last December to
block the bid under the EEC's competition rules. These rules outlaw
any industrial agreement likely to distort free competition.
   GEC and Plessey are Britain's two largest defense-electronics
contractors. Siemens, with NV Philips of the Netherlands, is one of
Europe's two top electronics groups.
</TEXT>
