<FIRST>u f PM-Drexel 1stLd-Writethru   04-19 0739</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drexel, 1st Ld-Writethru,0763</SECOND>
<HEAD>Drexel To Sell Retail Brokerage Unit As Part Of Major Restructuring</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS lead, 19th graf to CORRECT number of workers; PICKS UP
`Individuals prefer...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stung by bad publicity from the government's
massive securities fraud probes and slumping business since the
1987 stock market crash, Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. is shedding
its 2,300-employee retail brokerage unit as part of a major
restructuring.
   The nation's fifth-largest investment firm said Tuesday it will
try to sell the brokerage unit, which accounts for about 10 percent
of Drexel's business, to another brokerage house.
   Drexel said it also is abandoning its business in municipal
securities, over-the-counter stocks, and research and transactions
in non-U.S. securities. The restructuring will cut Drexel's work
force by about a third.
   The move comes five days after Drexel agreed to tight federal
oversight for three years in settling civil fraud charges with the
Securities and Exchange Commission.
   Drexel Chief Executive Frederick H. Joseph announced the
restructuring over the firm's public address system, calling the
verdict by its board of directors last weekend ``the only
economically viable solution.''
   He said the move was made to so Drexel could deal with the
``current realities'' at the firm, implying the government's nearly
three-year investigation of alleged securities abuses, many
involving the Milken's dealings with jailed inside trader Ivan
Boesky.
   ``The decision was made in view of the anticipated inability to
grow the retail business to an economically viable size in light of
ongoing adverse publicity ...,'' Drexel said in a statement.
   The SEC pact clears the way for settlement of criminal fraud
charges with the Manhattan U.S. attorney's office. Drexel has
agreed to plead guilty to six felonies and pay a record $650
million to avoid a massive racketeering indictment.
   A rash of civil lawsuits over Drexel's activities, possibly
numbering in the thousands, now are expected to be filed in
individual states. In addition, congressional officials have
indicated they plan further investigations into Drexel.
   The continued investigations, along with the possible
high-visibility trial of former Drexel junk-bond financier Michael
Milken, means the firm will remain in a negative spotlight for some
time.
   ``It's a kind of situation that's very sensitive as far as
retail clients are concerned,'' said PaineWebber Inc. analyst
Brenda Davis McCoy.
   In its statement, Drexel cited ``the depressed state of the
securities industry, the anticipated lack of participation by
individual investors'' and increased competition from commercial
banks in retail brokerage.
   Drexel, which does not release earnings or other detailed
financial data, said it has total capital of about $2 billion and
net equity capital of about half that.
   Drexel spokesman Steven Anreder declined to give details on the
extent of the retail business decline, but said: ``It was just
getting difficult. Indeed, the numbers were going in the other
direction.''
   After a board meeting Tuesday, Drexel said it notified about 10
other Wall Street firms about peddling the division. It said it
hopes to have bids by Saturday and a sale completed by early next
week.
   Drexel's statement said the firm would concentrate on high-yield
junk bonds, government securities, corporate finance, institutional
fixed income activities, mortgage-backed securities, arbitrage and
commodities.
   Business on Wall Street has been sluggish because of high
interest rates, continued investor distrust following the October
1987 market crash, and a severe decline in mergers and
acquisitions. Several firms announced weak first-quarter profits in
the last week.
   Drexel itself has shrunk from a high of about 10,000 employees
worldwide to 9,100 today. The 10 percent payroll decline is about
average for Wall Street firms, most of which laid off hundreds of
employees after the crash.
   The retail brokerage unit has lost about 200 brokers from a high
of 1,300. It now has about 1,100 brokers and another 1,200
employees. Drexel declined to say how many people would be laid off
in the restructuring.
   ``Individuals prefer money market instruments, savings accounts
to speculation or even investments,'' said James Hanbury of
Wertheim Schroder Inc. ``It's cyclical. We're in a down cycle.''
   Joseph named Merrill Lynch &amp; Co., Prudential-Bache Securities
Inc., Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc., Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. and
PaineWebber as possible buyers. Shearson spokesman Steve Fagan said
his firm is not interested in the unit.
   Because of the planned personnel reduction, Drexel also said it
had informed the city of New York that it was scrapping plans to
build new Manhattan offices.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
