<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices were mixed today as traders cashed
in on some of the recent gains that have carried the market to its
highest levels since the crash of 1987.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 2.20 to 2,381.60 in
the first half hour of trading.
   But losers outnumbered gainers by more than 3 to 2 in nationwide
trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 380 up, 580
down and 559 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 29.62 million shares as of 10
a.m. on Wall Street.
   Analysts said stocks have drawn support in recent days from
spreading hopes that inflationary pressures might be easing and
interest rates were turning downward.
   Inflation figures for March, unlike those for the two previous
months, contained no unpleasant surprises that seemed likely to
prompt the Federal Reserve to tighten credit further.
   However, brokers say, signs of a slowing economy also raise some
new worries for investors.
   For one thing, some observers suggest, they could lead to
reduced expectations about corporate earnings and heightened
concern about the possibility of a recession.
   American Telephone &amp; Telegraphrose \ to 33]. The company posted
a 20.6 percent increase in its first quarter earnings, and said it
had a good chance to keep up that pace.
   Microsoft, the most active issue in the over-the-counter market,
rose 1} to 55. The company reported earnings for the fiscal quarter
ended March 31 of 73 cents a share, up from 67 cents in the
comparable period a year earlier.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
slipped .02 to 171.11. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index was down .13 at 339.07.
   On Tuesday the Dow Jones industrial average climbed 41.61 to
2,379.40.
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by more than 2 to 1 on
the NYSE.
   Big Board volume totaled 208.65 million shares, against 128.54
million in the previous session.
