<HEAD>Soybeans Gain On Brazilian Dock Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean prices for near-term delivery rose
strongly this morning on the Chicago Board of Trade on perceptions
that a 9-day-old Brazilian dockworkers strike is disrupting exports
of Brazilian soybeans.
   Grain futures were modestly higher in early trading, but gains
in most markets were being held in check by prospects for rain in
the Midwest later this week.
   No substantial progress was reported at a formal mediation
session Tuesday in efforts to end the nationwide dockworkers strike
in Brazil, the world's second-largest soybean producer after the
United States.
   Weather forecasts continue to exert a strong influence on the
markets, where memories of last summer's drought linger. Many
private forecasters are still predicting dry weather in the Corn
Belt all the way into next week but some see an increasing
likelihood of showers in the region later this week.
   In early trading, wheat was 1 cent to 6 cents higher with the
contract for delivery in May at $4.13 a bushel; corn was unchanged
to 1 cent higher with May at $2.76{ a bushel; oats were 2\ cents to
2} cents higher with May at $2.01 a bushel; soybeans were 1 cent
lower to 7{ cents higher with May at $7.56 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were modestly lower in early trading
on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
