<FIRST>r f PM-Earns-TexasEastern     04-19 0375</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Earns-Texas Eastern,0387</SECOND>
<HEAD>Texas Eastern Post First Quarter Earnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texas Eastern Corp., a natural gas and petroleum
products pipeline company that has been pursued by two companies,
said today earnings for the first quarter of 1989 improved by 97
percent partly because of an $11.6 million settlement in a pipeline
project.
   For the first three months of this year, the Houston-based
company posted earnings of $57.5 million, or $1.02 per share, on
operating revenue of $1 billion, compared to $29.2 million, or 55
cents per share, on revenue of $898 million for the same period in
1988.
   Included in the profits were $11.6 million in non-recurring
gains primarily due to settlement of anti-trust litigation
associated with the ETSI coal slurry pipeline project, in which
Texas Eastern was a partner.
   Excluding $29.2 milion in non-recurring net charges relating to
events which led to the pending merger of Texas Eastern and
Houston-based Panhandle Eastern Corp., the company had net earnings
of $86.7 million for the three month period ending March 31.
   ``We are pleased with the company's first period performance. It
reflects the results of the extensive restructuring program
undertaken during the past two years; the company has posted four
consecutive quarter-to-quarter improvements in net earnings,'' said
Dennis R. Hendrix, president of Texas Eastern.
   ``The asset disposition program and efficiencies achieved
through decentralization and staff reductions have returned the
company's earnings to levels attained during the early 1980s when
the company benefitted from much higher crude oil prices,'' he said.
   The battle for Texas Eastern between Panhandle Eastern and
Houston-based Coastal Corp. began Jan. 16 when Coastal announced
its surprise $2.6 billion takeover bid. But the Texas Eastern board
rejected the offer as too low, signing the merger agreement with
Panhandle Eastern on Feb. 21.
   Panhandle Eastern's $3.2 billion offer includes provisions to
buy up to 80 percent of Texas Eastern's 60.8 million outstanding
shares and a stock exchange at the same $53-a-share value for the
remaining shares.
   The combination of the two companies would create a 27,000-mile
system and result in one of the nation's largest pipeline companies
in terms of miles.
   Earlier this week, Coastal extended its tender offer until March
31, while Panhandle Eastern extended their offer to April 26.
</TEXT>
