<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-89 1358EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-CommoditiesRules 1stLd-Writethru   04-19 0553</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Commodities Rules, 1st Ld-Writethru,0567</SECOND>
<HEAD>Merc Announces Recommendations of Panel in Wake of Federal Probe</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout with announcement of recommendations. Adds byline.
No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Chicago Mercantile Exchange panel today
recommended restrictions on most forms of ``dual trading,'' the
doubling of its surveillance staff and improved auditing in
response to a federal fraud investigation.
   ``Some of these proposals were under study prior to the FBI
investigation. But the failure to respond quickly would have shown
a lack of leadership,'' said John Geldermann, chairman of the
Merc's Special Committee to Review Trading Practices.
   Geldermann also is chairman of the Merc's Board of Governors, to
whom the recommendations are submitted for a decision expected
within 60 days.
   Dual trading enables a trader on the exchange to deal for his
own account as well as customers' accounts. While the practice is
legal, many consider it a problem because it allows traders to
allocate profitable deals to their own accounts and dump losing
trades on customers.
   Proponents argue that dual trading increases liquidity because
traders can continue doing business when they don't have outside
orders.
   But the Merc committee, recognizing the public perception that
the practice trading invites abuse, recommended dual trading be
banned from futures contracts in cases where market volume is great
enough to ensure liquidity.
   The panel also recommended the Merc's fulltime floor
surveillance team be doubled from four to eight staff members and
said the exchange's disciplinary committees should include a person
who is not a Merc member.
   ``It's hardly cynical to say that they're hoping to act in
advance of the government,'' Daniel Siegel, a professor at
Northwestern University's Kellogg Graduate School of Business, said
in an interview a day before the recommendations were formally
released.
   ``Frankly, I suspect the leadership at the Merc is upset by some
of the revelations coming out of the probe. Remember also that the
futures industry has prospered with self-regulation and they would
like to keep control,'' Siegel added.
   The nine-member committee was appointed in late January,
following disclosure the federal government was investigating
allegations that as many as 100 brokers at the Merc and the Chicago
Board of Trade systematically cheated investors out of millions of
dollars through illegal trading practices.
   Although as many as 200 subpeonas reportedly have been issued to
traders and firms at the world's two largest futures exchanges, no
indictments have been issued thus far.
   Among the members of the Merc committee are Leo Melamed,
chairman of the executive committee of the Merc and special counsel
to the exchange's Board of Governors; and Susan Phillips, who
formerly headed the Commodity Futures Trading Commission, the
federal agency that regulates the industry.
   Shortly after it was assembled, the committee asked Robert
Wilmouth, president of the National Futures Association, to assist
in its review of trading practices. The NFA is the industry's chief
watchdog organization.
   The exchanges have successfully fought off repeated attempts for
increased regulation in the past, most recently after the 1987
stock market crash. At the time, some critics blamed the futures
exchanges for market volatility that may have worsened the crash.
   But the exchanges, in a successful effort to forestall more
government intervention, argued that futures selling actually
provided an outlet that prevented the crash from getting worse.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
