<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Firmer On Rising Oil Prices, Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: An AMer expected by 5:30 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar closed higher on Wednesday against
most of the major currencies in European trading, boosted by rising
oil prices. Gold prices were mixed.
   Foreign exchange dealers said higher oil prices and portfolio
adjustments by dealers after the dollar's decline on Tuesday lifted
the dollar.
   They said oil price rise encouraged speculation that the Federal
Reserve would be more likely than the central banks in West Germany
and Japan to encourage higher interest rates in response to
inflationary pressures.
   However, one dealer in Frankfurt said he didn't expect to see
the dollar much stronger because recent government reports have
indicated weakness in the U.S. economy, a development that would
discourage credit-tightening by the Fed.
   The benchmark price of oil from the British North Sea's Brent
field was marked up WEdnesday by $1.48 to $21.13 a barrel for
delivery next month, after news that the entire field had been shut
down by a platform gas explosion. The field produces nearly
one-quarter of the British sector's ouput of around 2 million
barrels daily.
   In London, the British pound fell to $1.7113 late Wednesday from
$1.7185 late Tuesday.
   Other late rates for the dollar in Europe, compared with
Tuesday's late rates, included: 1.8615 West German marks, up from
1.8528; 1.6360 Swiss francs, up from 1.6283; 6.3025 French francs,
