<FIRST>r f AM-Earns-Drugs     04-19 0388</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Drugs,0405</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bristol-Myers, Other Pharmaceutical Concerns, Post Healthy Profit
Growth</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Bristol-Myers Co., maker of many widely known brands including
Bufferin and Excedrin pain relievers and Clairol hair care
products, Wednesday reported its first-quarter profit rose 12.6
percent to a record level.
   Two other companies in the pharmaceutical business _ Squibb
Corp. and Schering-Plough Corp. _ also posted healthy earnings for
the quarter.
   Bristol-Myers said after-tax earnings amounted to $237 million,
or 82 cents a share, in the three months ended March 31, up from
$210.6 million, or 73 cents a share, in 1988's first quarter.
   Sales for the quarter were the highest in the company's history,
rising just over 5 percent to $1.60 billion from $1.52 billion.
International sales gained 11 percent while domestic sales were up
3 percent.
   Bristol-Myers, based in New York, has operations in
non-prescription and prescription drugs, toiletries and household
products, such as Windex and Drano. It did not provide any specific
information about the financial performance of its individual
operations.
   Industry analysts have said Bristol-Myers has been a leader in
manufacturing anti-cancer drugs and has benefited from the
popularity of its anti-anxiety agent, BuSpar.
   Squibb said its first-quarter earnings rose 17.2 percent to
$106.5 million, or $1.09 a share, from $90.9 million, or 89 cents a
share, a year earlier. Sales increased 11 percent to $662.7 million
from $596.9 million.
   The Princeton, N.J.-based company's chairman and chief executive
officer, Richard M. Furland, said the balance sheet improvements
reflected excellent performances by Squibb's leading products,
better gross margins and a slight leverage on operating expenses.
   These positive factors more than compensated for a 23 percent
rise in research and development costs and flat sales growth in
traditional products.
   Schering-Plough said its net income rose 23.8 percent in the
first quarter to $125.7 million, or $1.12 a share, from $101.5
million, or 91 cents a share, the year before.
   Sales increased 10.5 percent to $831.8 million from $752.5
million. Schering-Plough, based in Madison, N.J., attributed the
overall growth mainly to sales in its pharmaceutical businesses,
which expanded 14 percent.
   Sales of Schering-Plough's consumer products, such as Coppertone
sun protection products and Dr. Scholl's foot care line, rose more
modestly.
   Among the products pacing the increase in pharmaceutical sales
were items to treat asthma, cardiovascular problems and
dermatological disorders, Schering-Plough said.
</TEXT>
