<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0242</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soybean, Corn Futures Drop On Rain Forecasts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corn and soybean futures prices closed with steep
losses Wednesday on the Chicago Board of Trade following midday
forecasts for an increased chance of rain in the western Corn Belt
later this week.
   But wheat futures advanced on persistent talk of hot, dry
weather in Kansas and on news that Egypt is seeking to buy 300,000
metric tons of U.S. wheat at subsidized prices.
   ``Welcome to the weather market,'' said Ted Mao, a grain
specialist with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in New York, referring
to the recent volatility in the grain markets.
   Some private meteorologists who had been predicting dry weather
for the rest of this week in Iowa and northwestern Illinois
forecast rain in their noon forecasts on Wednesday, prompting heavy
selling of corn and soybean contracts.
   The markets are unusually sensitive to weather forecasts because
last year's drought lowered U.S. grain stockpiles. Another drought
year could drain stocks down to critical levels.
   At the close, wheat was unchanged to 4} cents higher with the
contract for delivery in May at $4.11} a bushel; corn was 2{ cents
to 4{ cents lower with May at $2.73 a bushel; oats were 1\ cents to
3{ cents lower with May at $1.97 a bushel; soybeans were 3{ cents
to 11 cents lower with May at $7.45 a bushel.
