<FIRST>s f BC-PersonalFile-Dell Adv23   04-19 0964</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Personal File-Dell, Adv 23,0996</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv23</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Sunday, April 23</HEAD>
<HEAD>Computer Clonemaster Faces Wrath of Wall Street</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dell _ 24-year-old college-dropout
whiz kid multimillionaire who made his fortune cloning computers _
has a problem, he says. Wall Street doesn't understand his
5-year-old company.
   Financial analysts aren't sure Michael Dell understands business.
   Dell Computer Corp. wowed Wall Street by taking a company from
startup to $257.8 million in annual sales and $14.4 million in
profit by selling copies of the popular International Business
Machines personal computers.
   Dell carted three computers off to the University of Texas in
1984, promptly sold them at a profit and began making clones in his
condominium near the campus. Soon he was earning up to $80,000 a
month and figured computers, not classrooms, were where he should
direct his attention.
   Not bad for a pre-med major who began tinkering with computers
in high school and used to hang out at the local Radio Shack store
in Houston begging his orthodontist father for a PC.
   Success in the muddled IBM clone market brought Dell much
favorable publicity in financial and trade publications. He was
labeled an ``innovation upstart,'' ``computer industry's latest
whiz kid'' and ``entrepreneur in short pants.''
   But Dell's gimmick was marketing, not technology. He bypassed
retailers, going directly to consumers through advertisements in
user magazines and selling his wares over the phone from Austin.
   Then last year, Dell ran into a $104 million inventory buildup
and the bitter departure of a senior vice president.
   The buildup knocked revenue and sales predictions askew. Even
Goldman Sachs &amp; Co., one of the investment firms that helped with
last year's initial public offering, now is telling customers to
buy another computer stock instead.
   After an initial price of $8.50 per share, the stock climbed to
$13, but fell to $6 after the problems became apparent. It
currently is hanging around $7.
   The problems shifted the headlines, in Dell's own words, ``from
whiz kid to fizz kid.'' One publication called him ``the enfant
terrible of personal computers.''
   ``We think the perception of the company is quite different than
what's going on here,'' Dell said, describing his company as ``a
new, unique and different kind of entity...we have merged a design
and manufacturing operation for computers together into an entity.''
   But even Dell admits there were problems, although he attributes
them to success-caused malfunctions that have been fixed.
   ``I think the stock market is going to wait until it sees
tangible proof that Dell is turning around,'' said Daniel C.
Benton, who follows Dell for Goldman Sachs.
   ``The balance sheet has eroded; margins have eroded,'' Benton
said. Dell ``has phenomenal long-term prospects,'' he said, but the
market focuses on immediate gratification.
   To explain his problems, Dell draws diagrams on a note pad to
demonstrate how a backlog of orders in the second quarter of the
year inflated third quarter sales, which in turn caused forecasters
to expect unrealistic fourth quarter production.
   At the same time, Dell was anticipating huge fourth quarter
sales based on a barrage of favorable reviews in computer
magazines. The sales didn't reach expectations, saddling the
company with a large _ and in some cases high-priced _ inventory.
   ``I think he's right that the backlog issue created too high
expectations,'' Benton admitted, but added, ``If overlooking that
made us have high expectations, he did it too.''
   Much like a chastised teen-ager promising he has changed, Dell
says his company has learned from the past, with a new structure
and some new managers.
   ``The best thing I could do for the company is to find the best
people and give them the responsibility to do the job,'' he said
during an interview in his penthouse office in Austin's exclusive
Arboretum business park.
   Dell describes his workers, who average about 27 years old, as
``1,200 totally fired up, foaming at the mouth employees.''
   He often points to Glenn Henry, vice president of research and
development. Henry, 47, came from IBM's nearby laboratory in
Austin, where he helped the giant develop its Unix program for PCs.
   Henry is trying to turn the company to more technological
innovation, and Dell holds two of its own patents with more pending.
   Henry replaced Graham Beachum, hired on at Dell from Tandy Corp.
Beachum left last year following a bitter dispute with Dell over
most areas of the business.
   Dell said the blowup ``hurt the entire company, hurt me, hurt
Graham, hurt the employees here,'' but Beachum had to go because
``clearly we had a guy here who was not the right guy.''
   For his part, Beachum told Business Week magazine that Dell was
unwilling to spend money building a sales force, and that Dell's
plan for a Personal System-2 clone was ``ego-driven.''
   Henry since has scrapped those plans, and Dell says he learned
he shouldn't announce products before they're ready to be shipped.
   In the reorganization, Dell established separate subsidiaries
for domestic and overseas clients. Within Dell USA are divisions
for small customers, principally individuals and small businesses;
larger businesses; potential customers in government and education;
and resellers.
   In the meantime, Dell enjoys his riches _ he owns 10.7 million
shares of the company, even after selling 300,000 shares at about
$11 per share, or $3.3 million.
   Though Dell says his job ``is not what I would consider work,''
he does not consider himself the stereotypical yuppie obsessed with
the quest for riches and is planning to marry in a few months.
   ``I work a fairly normal set of hours for a busy person like
myself,'' he says. ``I take a good number of vacations to make sure
that I'm well-prepared to do my job.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv for Sunday, April 23</NOTE>
