<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Ralston     04-19 0239</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Ralston,0249</SECOND>
<HEAD>Earnings Fall in 2nd-Qtr</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ralston Purina Co. on Wednesday said its
second-quarter earnings slipped 2.7 percent from last year's
results that included a contribution from its Van Camp Seafood
operations which have since been sold.
   Net earnings for the quarter ended March 31 amounted to $90.8
million, or $1.39 a share, compared with earnings of $93.3 million,
or $1.35 a share, a year earlier.
   Second-quarter revenue rose 14.3 percent to $1.6 billion from
$1.4 billion for the same period last year. The company said its
Van Camp operations accounted for $4.6 million in net earnings in
the second quarter last year.
   For the first six months of its fiscal year, Ralston said its
net earnings rose 30.1 percent to $293.5 million, or $4.44 a share,
compared with net earnings of $225.7 million, or $3.25 a share, a
year earlier.
   Six-month revcenue rose 12 percent to $3.27 billion from $2.92
billion for the same period last year.
   Operating profit in the human foods and pet foods operation
increased this year over last year, the company said.
   Continental Baking Co.'s operating profit was down for the
quarter due to lower cake volume. But for the six months, higher
bread volume kept Continental's operating profit even with last
year.
   Operating profit for the quarter and the six months for Eveready
Battery was down as a result of heavy advertising and promotional
spending, the company said.
