<FIRST>u f BC-Earns-Computers     04-19 0452</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Computers,0469</SECOND>
<HEAD>Microsoft Makes A Profit After All</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Microsoft Corp. earnings rose 10 percent in the latest quarter,
the personal computer software maker said Wednesday, belying its
own forecast of an earnings decline.
   Microsoft rival Ashton-Tate Corp. reported a small earnings
gain, while Wang Laboratories Inc. predicted it would post the
worst quarterly loss in two years in its third fiscal quarter.
   Redmond, Wash.-based Microsoft said it earned $41.1 million, or
73 cents per share, in the third fiscal quarter ended March 31, up
from $37.3 million, or 67 cents a share, a year earlier. Revenue
rose 22 percent to $197 million from $161.8 million a year earlier.
   For the first nine months of its fiscal year, Microsoft's
earnings rose 33.3 percent to $184.1 million, or $2.23 a share,
from $140.9 million, or $1.68 a share, a year earlier. Revenue rose
38.8 percent to $583.3 million from $420.4 million a year earlier.
   Microsoft's stock plunged last month when the company predicted
an earnings decline, the first such drop since the company went
public three years ago.
   Some shareholders complained last month that they weren't
adequately warned about the company's difficulties. Now it turns
out that the warnings were overstated. March results turned out
better than expected, according to Pam Edstrom, a spokeswoman at
Microsoft's public relations firm.
   ``At least this news was better than the other news,'' she said.
   Lowell, Mass.-based Wang Laboratories said it expects to lose
some $55 million in its third quarter. Last week, Wang announced
plans to drop its worldwide payroll to 28,500 by June 1990. It had
31,700 employees in November, when it began a policy of not filling
vacancies.
   Wang plans to release its actual earnings figure Friday, two
days behind schedule.
   In a statement released Wednesday, the computer manufacturer
said unit sales and total revenues will be ``approximately equal''
to that of the previous quarter and the third quarter of fiscal
1988. Wang's sales totalled $767.9 million a year ago and $760.7
million in 1989's second quarter.
   Wang blamed this quarter's loss on increased discounting of
product sales, lower maintentance revenue in the United States, and
a shift to lower-margin sales of personal computers. The firm's
main business is minicomputers.
   The firm has followed 1988's $92 million gain with disappointing
profits of $13.1 million and $1 million the first two quarters of
this fiscal year.
   Ashton-Tate, of Torrance, Calif., said its net income rose to
$11.5 million, or 44 cents a share, from $11.1 million, or 43 cents
a share, a year earlier. Revenue rose to $89.8 million from $72.4
million a year earlier.
   The company attributed the flat earnings to increased research
and development and sales and marketing expenses.
</TEXT>
