<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-89 1953EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Japan-Pickens     04-19 0596</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Pickens,0619</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pickens Says Corporate Buyouts Will Find Their Way into Japan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN MOFFAT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American takeover specialist T. Boone Pickens said
Wednesday that corporate buyouts helped invigorate the U.S. economy
in the 1980s, and similar tactics will find their way into Japanese
business in the 1990s.
   Pickens visited Japan for talks with management of Koito
Manufacturing Co. after buying 20.2 percent of its shares _ a move
he said was not a prelude to a takeover attempt or greenmail.
   ``We want to work with Koito managment. We aren't doing anything
hostile,'' he said, adding that he was investing for ``the long
term.''
   Meanwhile, Koito, which expressed surprise and concern at the
time of Pickens' purchase, announced Wednesday evening that it was
transferring the shares to Pickens' ownership, dropping a request
to the Ministry of Finance to investigate whether there were any
technical irregularities that might block the purchase.
   Pickens is scheduled to meet Thursday with the president of the
company, said a company spokesman.
   At a luncheon Wednesday with the American Chamber of Commerce in
Japan, Pickens argued that corporate buyouts helped put the U.S.
economy back on its feet in the 1980s by ousting ineffective
management and making its companies more competitive.
   ``What happened in the U.S. in the 1980s will find its way to
the Japanese business community in the 1990s,'' he said.
   Analysts in Tokyo say Pickens' visit is a challenge to basic
thinking in Japan's business community that a company belongs to
its employees, not its shareholders.
   Pickens gained fame and fortune in the United States by buying
and reorganizing companies and often purging company executives,
arguing that bad managers don't give shareholders the returns they
deserve.
   He said in Tokyo Wednesday that his ``shareholders' rights''
movement would soon spread to Japan.
   ``Shareholders rights will become a worldwide issue,'' he added.
   But many Japanese businessmen, and some foreign critics, believe
that the American emphasis on return to shareholders has caused
U.S. companies to lose competitiveness to Japanese companies.
   ``Japanese companies don't generally have to answer to
shareholders with short-term profits. They can focus on longer-term
growth. Just look at these two economies to see which approach has
been more successful,'' said Keith Donaldson, an analyst at James
Capel Pacific Ltd.
   Koito makes headlights and other parts for Toyota Motor Co.,
which owns 19.1 percent of the company. Pickens' shares are worth
about $1 billion at current market prices.
   Despite Pickens' denial, ``many people think it is greenmail,''
Shigeju Kita, general manager in charge of mergers and acquisitions
at Yamaichi Securities, said of Pickens' stock purchase.
   Greenmail is a premium paid by a company to buy back stock from
an unwanted suitor.
   Pickens says he is challenging barriers to foreign investment in
Japan, and many Americans are cheering him on.
   ``I am concerned that American investors don't have the same
access in Japan as Japanese have in the U.S.,'' Pickens told
reporters.
   Pickens said he could not judge how open or closed the Japanese
market was until he saw the results of his present enterprise.
   But he added that ``people in Washington are watching this
carefully. ... Japan-bashers ... will come to the surface pretty
quick'' if they think that an American company is being unfairly
treated in Japan, he said.
   Pickens told the American Chamber audience he was considering
running for governor of Texas.
   Later, he told reporters that the Koito deal ``was not done with
political motives in mind, but I've had people suggest it might be
an advantage in a political race.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
