<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-89 2035EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Earns-Northrop     04-19 0351</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Northrop,0367</SECOND>
<HEAD>Big First-Quarter Profit Drop Blamed on Earlier Tax Benefit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Northrop Corp.'s profit plunged in
the first quarter, but the decline was attributed to a huge
one-time tax benefit in the comparable quarter a year earlier.
   Northrop, which has been rocked by a series of allegations of
overbilling and a defense fraud indictment, said Wednesday its
first-quarter profit fell to $9.7 million, or 21 cents a share,
from $139.6 million, or $2.97 a share in the first quarter of 1988.
   The difference was the result of a one-time gain of $135.1
million in the earlier quarter, when the company took advantage of
a law that allowed it to defer payment of taxes in earlier years
until the new, lower corporate tax rate took effect.
   Without the tax benefit, earnings in 1988's first quarter would
have been $4.5 million, or less than half of this year's
first-quarter income.
   Northrop's sales in the first quarter were $1.28 billion, down 7
percent from $1.37 billion a year earlier.
   The company also took a charge against profits of $26 million
for unplanned research and development expenses on an electronic
defense system for the F-15 fighter jet.
   Northrop made a similar provision in the fourth quarter of last
year for development of the system, called the ALQ-135, but didn't
reveal the amount of the write-off for that quarter.
   Overall sales declined for several reasons: Less Pentagon money
for research and development of the B-2 stealth bomber, which is
moving into production; fewer MX missile sales; and fewer
deliveries of fuselages for the FA-18 Hornet fighter, which is
built by McDonnell Douglas Corp. for the Navy.
   The sales declines were partly offset by an increase in
deliveries of 747 airliner fuselages to Boeing Corp.
   Northrop has been the target of several lawsuits by employee
``whistleblowers'' who allege the company overcharged the
government on various projects.
   The corporation and five present and former employees were
charged this month with conspiracy and fraud in an alleged scheme
to fake tests on a device used to guide cruise missiles.
   Northrop denies any wrongdoing.
</TEXT>
