<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     04-19 0495</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0513</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Firmer On Rising Oil Prices; Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON-BC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar bounced back Wednesday from its
decline of the previous session, boosted by higher oil prices.
   Foreign exchange dealers said the rise in the dollar was
amplified by purchases by traders who had been betting on its
continued decline and had to buy dollars to cover short positions.
   Oil futures prices spurted to a three-year high Wednesday after
a North Sea gas explosion and an industry report that showed U.S.
production falling to its lowest level since the 1960s.
   The rise in oil prices increased inflation fears, raising the
possibility that the Federal Reserve would tighten credit to stop
inflation. Tight credit attracts global investors to dollars.
   A government inflation report had lowered the dollar on Tuesday
by diminishing the likelihood of credit-tightening by the Fed.
   Wednesday's higher oil prices lowered the Japanese yen against
the dollar because Japan depends on imported oil.
   The yen was also hurt by an unfounded rumor that Japanese Prime
Minister Noboru Takeshita had resigned, according to Nazem Elsabeh,
a trader and vice president at Republic National Bank of New York.
   In London, the British pound fell to $1.7113 late Wednesday from
$1.7185 late Tuesday. Later in New York the pound fell to $1.7108
from $1.7164.
   In Tokyo, the dollar closed at 131.88 Japanese yen, down from
132.10 yen late Tuesday. Later in London, the dollar traded at
132.10 yen. In New York the dollar rose to 132.58 yen from 131.40
on Wednesday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with Tuesday's
late rates, included: 1.8623 West German marks, up from 1.8525;
1.6373 Swiss francs, up from 1.6270; 1.1858 Canadian dollars, down
from 1.1863; 6.3040 French francs, up from 6.2710; and 1,364.38
Italian lire, up from 1,360.13.
   Late dollar rates in Europe, compared with Tuesday's rates:
1.8615 West German marks, up from 1.8528; 1.6360 Swiss francs, up
from 1.6283; 6.3025 French francs, up from 6.2750; 2.0985 Dutch
guilders, up from 2.0935; 1,363.75 Italian lire, down from
1,366.95; and 1.1865 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1848.
   In the bullion markets, prices were narrowly mixed.
   Gold closed in Hong Kong at $384.25 an ounce, down from $386.68
late Tuesday. Gold traded at a late bid of $383.95 a troy ounce in
London, up from $383.25 late Tuesday. But the late bid price for
gold fell to $383.50 an ounce in Zurich from $384.00 late Tuesday.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery fell to $383.40 an ounce from $383.50 on Wednesday. Later,
Republic National Bank of New York said gold was bid at $382.80 an
ounce as of 4 p.m. EDT, down from $383.10 late Wednesday.
   Silver bullion traded late in London at a bid of $5.79 a troy
ounce, up from $5.78 late Tuesday. On New York's Comex, silver
bullion for current delivery fell to $5.750 an ounce from $5.763 on
Wednesday.
</TEXT>
