<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-89 1707EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-Earns-Phone 1stLd-Writethru   04-19 0295</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Phone, 1st Ld-Writethru,0303</SECOND>
<HEAD>AT&amp;T, BellSouth, Pacific Telesis, Ameritech Report Higher Earnings</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf with 1 graf to clarify that depreciation expenses
fell overall in spite of one-time charge.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   AT&amp;T results also included in AM-AT&amp;T, Bjt.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Higher quarterly profits were reported Wednesday by American
Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co. and three of its Baby Bell offspring,
BellSouth Corp., Pacific Telesis Group and Ameritech.
   AT&amp;T said it earned $594 million, or 55 cents a share, up from
$492 million, or 46 cents a share, a year earlier. Revenue rose to
$8.66 billion from $8.39 billion a year earlier.
   The company's depreciation expenses declined, boosting profits.
But for accounting reasons the company reported an $88 million
one-time charge against earnings to reflect a change in the method
of depreciating assets.
   Chicago-based Ameritech said its earnings rose 1.9 percent to
$300.8 million, or $1.12 a share, on revenues of $2.5 billion, from
$295.1 million, or $1.08 a share, on revenue of $2.4 billion a year
earlier.
   Atlanta-based BellSouth said its earnings rose 4.3 percent to
$449.6 million, or 97 cents a share, from $430.9 million, or 90
cents a share, a year earlier. Revenue rose 5.2 percent to $3.37
billion from $3.2 billion a year earlier.
   However, BellSouth's earnings would have fallen to about $404
million if not for one-time factors, the company said.
   San Francisco-based Pacific Telesis, one of the seven so-called
Baby Bells created in 1984 by the breakup of AT&amp;T, reported
first-quarter earnings of $317 million, or 76 cents per share, up
5.7 percent from $300 million, or 71 cents, in the first quarter of
1988.
   PacTel's revenues for the period increased to $2.34 billion, 1.5
percent more than the $2.3 billion reported for the same quarter
last year.
</TEXT>
