<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Banks     04-19 0333</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Banks,0348</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Quarter Earnings Up at Two Banks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Assocaited Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   First Interstate Bancorp and Bank of Boston Corp., two of the
nation's largest bank holding companies, reported Wednesday that
their first-quarter profits rose over a year ago.
   First Interstate, based in Los Angeles, said it earned $132.2
million, or $2.81 a share, for the three months ended March 31, up
29 percent from $102.6 million, or $2.20 a share, in 1988.
   Bank of Boston, based in Boston, said net income totaled $89
million, or $1.23 per share, up 6 percent from earnings of $84
million, or $1.17 a share, last year.
   First Interstate attributed its higher earnings partly to a
$21.8 million tax benefit and an accounting change that added $16.1
million. In the comparable quarter for 1988, a tax benefit boosted
profit by $15 million.
   Net interest income in the first quarter rose to $636.8 million
from $564.7 million a year ago. Non-interest income climbed to
$259.9 million from $238.9 million a year earlier. Non-interest
expense was $605.3 million, up from $580.1 million a year ago.
   First Interstate's Texas subsidiary, formerly Allied Bancshares
Inc. of Houston, lost $24.3 million in the first quarter, compared
to a loss of $2.1 million a year ago. The company blamed the loss
on continued weakness in the state's economy.
   But First Interstate banks in California, Arizona, Oregon,
Washington and Nevada turned in strong performances and most of the
other state banks reported gains, said J.J. Pinola, chairman and
chief executive.
   Bank of Boston Chairman Ira Stepanian said he was pleased with
the latest earnings report, ``especially considering last year's
particularly strong first quarter.''
   ``This year's improvement includes no special items and reflects
higher net interest revenue,'' he said in a statement.
   Consolidated net interest revenue totaled $322 million, an 11
percent increase over $292 million in 1988.
   Non-interest income for the quarter was $161 million, compared
with $176 million in 1988. Non-interest expense was $297 million, a
3 percent increase over 1988.
</TEXT>
