<FIRST>r f AM-Earns-GMSubsidiaries     04-19 0425</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-GM Subsidiaries,0439</SECOND>
<HEAD>GMAC Earnings Flat, Huges Electronics Down</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp.'s financing subsidiary
Wednesday reported a modest rise in first-quarter earnings while
the automaker's aviation and electronics arm reported a sharp 16.6
percent profit decline.
   General Motors Acceptance Corp. said rising interest rates held
quarterly net income to $356.4 million, a 0.6 percent rise over
$354.4 million in the same 1988 period.
   The 1989 earnings included $50.7 million from the sale to Isuzu
Motors of a 51 percent interest GMAC held in Isuzu Motors Finance
Co.
   GMAC said its average cost of borrowings worldwide rose to 9.2
percent for the quarter ending March 31 from 7.8 percent a year
earlier.
   GMAC's total earning assets rose to $95.3 billion as of March
31, up from $94.7 billion a year earlier. Earning assets are
amounts owed GMAC on which it receives interest.
   GM Hughes Electronics Corp., the aviation and electronics arm,
said net income fell to $201.1 million, or 51 cents a share of GM
Class H common stock, from $252 billion, or 63 cents a share in the
first quarter of 1988.
   The 1988 period's earnings were inflated by 13 cents a share by
the sale of part of GMHE's stock in Nippon Avionics Co., and 5
cents a share by an accounting change at GMHE's Delco Electronics
Corp. subsidiary, the company said.
   GMHE's revenues rose 12.7 percent to $3.01 billion for the
quarter from $2.67 billion in the year-earlier period, the company
said.
   Electronic Data Systems Corp., the data processing subsidiary,
said new insurance, financial, commercial and government
data-processing contracts helped raise net income 12 percent.
   EDS, which provides information services for GM and outside
customers, reported net income of $100 million, or 82 cents a share
of GM Class E common stock. That was up 12.2 percent from $89.1
million in the first quarter of 1988.
   EDS said revenue totaled $1.29 billion, up from $1.12 billion in
the year-earlier period, with 56 percent of the revenue from GM and
44 percent from other customers.
   New data processing contracts included a 12-year agreement with
Whitehall Insurance Holdings Ltd. in New York, and a 10-year
contract with Meritor Savings Bank of Philadelphia, EDS said.
   EDS said it signed new contracts with international customers
including BASF, West Germany's largest chemical company; Danone, a
Spanish dairy products company; DANZAS-SATEM, a French distribution
company; Banco Investimento Garantia, a Brazilian bank; and
International Bank of Asia in Hong Kong.
   GM's parent company was to announce its earnings Thursday.
</TEXT>
