<FIRST>u f AM-WallStreet 1stLd-Writethru   04-19 0487</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0507</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices kept climbing Wednesday, getting a
little more mileage out of the rally that has carried the market to
its highest levels since the crash of 1987.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 7.51 to 2,386.91,
bringing its gain over the past four sessions to 90.91 points.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 4 to 3 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
827 up, 634 down and 524 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 191.51 million
shares, down from 208.65 million in the previous session.
Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including
trades in those stocks on regional exchanges and in the
over-the-counter market, totaled 227.87 million shares.
   Analysts said stocks have drawn support in recent days from
spreading hopes that inflationary pressures might be easing and
interest rates were turning downward.
   Inflation figures for March, unlike those for the two previous
months, contained no unpleasant surprises that seemed likely to
prompt the Federal Reserve to tighten credit further.
   Signs of a slowing economy also raise some new worries for
investors. For one thing, some observers suggest, they could lead
to heightened concern about the possibility of a recession.
   However, brokers said, any such fears were countered Wednesday
by strong earnings reports from several prominent companies.
   American Telephone &amp; Telegraph rose ] to 33{. The company
reported a 20.6 percent increase in its first quarter earnings, and
said it had a good chance to keep up that pace.
   Philip Morris, which also posted a strong first-quarter earnings
gain, climbed 2} to 125[.
   Other gainers among the blue chips included DuPont, up ~ at
109]; Minnesota Mining &amp; Manufacturing, up } at 70}; Johnson &amp;
Johnson, up } at 95|, and Sears Roebuck, up \ at 45~.
   Phelps Dodge picked up 1{ to 60 on a strong quarterly earnings
report.
   Microsoft, among the volume leaders in the over-the-counter
market, rose 1| to 54~. The company reported earnings for the
fiscal quarter ended March 31 of 73 cents a share, up from 67 cents
in the comparable period a year earlier.
   Elsewhere, Carson Pirie Scott, traded on the Big Board, gained
1| to 23]. The company said P.A. Bergner &amp; Co. raised its takeover
offer from $20 a share to $24 a share.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market increased $9.71 billion, or 0.32
percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks added
.57 to 171.70.
   Standard &amp; Poor's industrial index rose 1.43 to 354.30, and
S&amp;P's 500-stock composite index was up 1.13 at 307.15.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market
gained 1.19 to 421.91. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index closed at 340.43, up 1.23.
</TEXT>
