<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     04-19 0656</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0677</SECOND>
<HEAD>Corn, Soybeans Slide On Rain Forecasts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices for corn and soybeans to be harvested this fall fell
sharply Wednesday on the Chicago Board of Trade on forecasts for
rain later this week in the western Corn Belt, a key growing area
hit hard by last summer's drought.
   Wheat futures prices rose due to persistent dryness in Kansas,
where the winter wheat crop already has sustained severe damage.
   On other markets, oil futures posted steep gains, livestock and
meat futures prices tumbled and precious metals were slightly lower.
   Wheat settled unchanged to 4} cents higher with the contract for
delivery in May at $4.11} a bushel; corn was 2{ cents to 4{ cents
lower with May at $2.73 a bushel; oats were 1\ cents to 2} cents
lower with May at $1.97 a bushel; soybeans were 3{ cents to 11\
cents lower with May at $7.45 a bushel.
   ``Welcome to the weather market,'' said Ted Mao, a New
York-based grain specialist with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.,
referring to the recent volatility in the grain markets.
   Corn and soybean planting has barely begun but the grain markets
are extremely sensitive to weather changes because last year's
drought lowered U.S. grain stockpiles. Another drought year could
drain stocks down to critical levels and cause prices to skyrocket.
   Some private meteorologists who had been predicting dry weather
for the rest of this week in Iowa and northwestern Illinois put
more rain into their noon forecasts on Wednesday, prompting heavy
selling of corn and soybean contracts.
   After the close, the National Weather Service issued a new
six-to-10 day forecast calling for above-normal rainfall in the
western Midwest and normal precipitation in the region's central
and eastern portions, which could prompt further selling of corn
and soybean futures on Thursday.
   ``The irony is that most experts agree that beyond 72 hours, the
degree of accuracy in a forecast drops geometrically,'' Mao said,
``and yet everybody pays attention to those forecasts because there
isn't anything else to trade on.''
   Unleaded gasoline prices surged on the New York Mercantile
Exchange, leading the crude oil and heating oil markets higher,
following Tuesday's American Petroleum Institute report of
substantial reductions in U.S. supplies of crude and gasoline.
   Further buying was spurred by reports that the Shell Oil Co.'s
British subsidiary had advise clients of possible shipment delays
for North Sea crude oil following the shutdown late Tuesday of a
damaged oil platform.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 2 cents to $1.10
higher with May at $22.61 a barrel; heating oil was .53 cent to .71
cent higher with May at 53.33 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was
.75 cent to 1.20 cents higher with May at 74.62 cents a gallon.
   The sharp losses in livestock and meat futures on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange were due more to profit-taking and technical
factors than to Wednesday's weaker cash markets, analysts said.
   Trading activity has grown cautious ahead of Friday's quarterly
Agriculture Department cattle-on-feed report, which is expected to
show first-quarter placements of cattle on feedlots to be 3 percent
to 10 percent above the first quarter of 1988.
   Live cattle settled .10 cent to 1.02 cents lower with June at
70.50 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .57 cent to .97 cent lower
with May at 75.55 cents a pound; live hogs were .25 cent to .80
cent lower with June at 45.90 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were 1.05 cents to 1.88 cents lower with May at 31.57 cents a pound.
   Gold and silver futures prices inched lower on New York's
Commodity Exchange. Investment demand for the metals has fallen
following government economic reports that indicate the economy is
slowing and inflation is holding steady.
   Gold settled 10 cents to 60 cents lower with June at $387.10 a
troy ounce; silver was 1.3 cents to 1.5 cents lower with May at
$5.765 a troy ounce.
</TEXT>
