<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-89 1803EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Eastern-Lorenzo Bjt   04-19 0725</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Lorenzo, Bjt,0750</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lorenzo, In Interview, Sticks By His Guns on Eastern</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texas Air Corp. Chairman Frank Lorenzo remained
locked on a collision course with the federal judge overseeing
Eastern Airlines' bankruptcy case by insisting Wednesday that the
strike-wracked carrier will be shrunk not sold.
   ``There are a lot of people out there who want to buy Eastern
Airlines for some beads, jelly beans or whatever comes to mind,''
Lorenzo told a small group of reporters at Texas Air's New York
office.
   ``Eastern has to be built back the old-fashioned way ... We
don't think that any sale transaction makes sense.''
   That position puts Lorenzo at loggerheads with U.S. Bankruptcy
Judge Burton R. Lifland, who appears poised to put the entire
airline up for sale _ including assets held by Miami-based Eastern
before Texas Air acquired it three years ago for about $676 million.
   Lifland, who generally refrains from speaking to reporters on
pending cases, was unavailable for comment.
   Furthermore, the 15-member committee representing Eastern's
major creditors could be skeptical of Lorenzo's plan to reduce
Eastern to 60 percent of its pre-strike size, sources said. The
committee is scheduled to meet Thursday, but Eastern attorney David
Boies said the plan won't be presented to creditors until next week.
   Lorenzo's insistence on holding and shrinking Eastern could be
aimed at luring back the airline's rebellious pilots, whose support
for the Machinists' strike has been critical to its success, a
union official said.
   ``His position is to threaten the pilots with `This is the only
airline we're going to have; you'd better jump on the bandwagon,'''
said Dan Ashby, a spokesman in New York for the Air Line Pilots
Association. ``The pilots are definitely holding ... This is a
desperation ploy.''
   Bruce Simon, an attorney for the pilots union, likening the
Lorenzo-Lifland showdown to ``a shootout at the OK Corral,'' said
the ``notion that you can shrink your way to profitability is sheer
lunacy.''
   There had been speculation that Texas Air's refusal to sell
Eastern, expressed by its board of directors on Monday, was a
negotiating ploy designed to elicit a higher price for the airline,
which has been mired in a strike and bankruptcy court proceedings
for more than a month.
   Last week, after the collapse of Lorenzo's $464 million deal to
sell Eastern to ex-baseball commissioner Peter V. Ueberroth,
Eastern officials said the airline would be sharply reduced.
   Lorenzo, who wore a yellow shirt and bright blue tie but no
jacket during the informal meeting with reporters, looked less
weary than he had at the federal courthouse last week but still
showed the toll of the protracted strike and bankruptcy case.
   He insisted that Eastern will be able to rebuild to a smaller
level without the fractious pilots returning to work. The airline
will need an estimated 1,500 pilots to run 60 percent of its
previous operations. Of the 3,600 or so Eastern pilots, only 200
have crossed picket lines.
   ``We can train pilots at a very substantial rate,'' Lorenzo
said. He disputed the pilots union's claim of a nationwide pilot
shortage.
   Asked whether a sharply reduced Eastern would be viable, Lorenzo
said, ``We believe it (would be) but there are no guarantees in
this world.''
   The Texas Air chief also refuted earlier statements by attorneys
for Eastern and the pilots union that another potential buyer had
emerged besides Ueberroth, hotelier Jay Pritzker and takeover
strategist Carl Icahn.
   ``There is no serious fourth bidder,'' Lorenzo said. He insisted
there are no talks currently between his company and potential
suitors.
   Lorenzo said Ueberroth had called him Tuesday and made it ``very
plain that he's out of the deal.''
   Sources close to Ueberroth, however, said Wednesday the two men
have continued negotiating by telephone.
   Simon, the pilots' attorney, insisted Wednesday that the fourth
bidding group has met with David I. Shapiro, the bankruptcy
examiner for Eastern.
   ``They are putting together their bid,'' Simon said.
   A source close to the situation, who asked not to be identified,
called the fourth bidder ``a serious and substantial presence.''
   Workers struck the nation's seventh-largest carrier March 4 in a
longstanding dispute with Lorenzo, accusing him of dismembering
Eastern and feeding its assets to sister Texas Air subsidiary
Continental Airlines. Lorenzo put the company into federal
bankruptcy court protection March 9.
</TEXT>
