<FIRST>u f AM-Drexel-SEC 1stLd-Writethru   04-19 0443</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drexel-SEC, 1st Ld-Writethru,0456</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ruder Raises Possibility of Action Against More Drexel Officials</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 6th graf pvs, Asked by, to CORRECT Markey's first name.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BENAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the Securities and Exchange
Commission suggested Wednesday the agency still might pursue action
against the head of Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. and other top
executives of the investment firm.
   SEC Chairman David Ruder, testifying before a House
subcommittee, said he expects the agency's enforcement division to
``pursue the activities of all the Drexel officials who were in
responsiblity'' during the time when massive securities violations
allegedly were committed.
   ``It is not unlikely that our investigation will reveal other
persons against whom action might be brought,'' Ruder told the
Energy and Commerce subcommittee on finance and telecommunications.
   Drexel last week agreed to a settlement of SEC civil charges
under which the firm will be subject to close federal monitoring
for three years and will restructure its operations and sever ties
with its junk bond chief, Michael Milken, who was indicted on
racketeering charges last month.
   The company also has agreed to plead guilty to six felony
charges and pay $650 million in fines and penalties in what has
become the biggest securities fraud probe in history.
   Asked by the subcommittee chairman, Rep. Edward J. Markey,
D-Mass., why Frederick H. Joseph was allowed to remain as Drexel's
president and chief operating officer under the SEC settlement,
Ruder stressed that the agreement requires Drexel to cooperate in a
continuing SEC investigation of activities at the investment house.
   He said that under standard SEC procedure, a logical follow-up
to the settlement would be for the agency's enforcement division
``to pursue questions of actions by the individuals at Drexel.''
   ``Your statement that we have decided not to take action is
simply not true,'' Ruder said.
   Markey also questioned whether the environment at Drexel could
change for the better if the firm's chief operating officer stays
on.
   ``That is a question with which we have had some concern,''
Ruder acknowledged. ``We have been looking for signs at Drexel at
the top level that there will be a change in culture and we
continue to look for signs that there is a change in culture.''
   He added that ``the primary and most significant'' change is
likely to come with the installment of former SEC Chairman John
Shad as chairman of Drexel's board.
   Ruder said the need for change at Drexel was primarily in its
high-yield junk bond department in California, which Milken had
commanded.
   ``We believe that steps to rework that department will be
effective to accomplish that cultural change,'' Ruder said.
</TEXT>
