<DOCNO> AP890419-0275 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-89 2059EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Warner     04-19 0246</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Warner,0257</SECOND>
<HEAD>Posts Big Profit Increase in First Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Warner Communications Inc. said Wednesday
first-quarter profit climbed 46.4 percent, reflecting record
performances by its filmed entertainment, records and cable and
broadcasting operations.
   Warner, which has proposed a merger with Time Inc. that the
companies hope will be approved this year, earned $101 million, or
57 cents a share, in the three months ended March 31 compared with
$68.9 million, or 37 cents a share a year earlier.
   First-quarter revenue rose 24.8 percent to $1.46 billion from
$1.17 billion.
   The latest results included $10 million in expenses related to
the pending Time merger and $38 million in charges associated with
stock appreciation-based compensation plans.
   The 1988 results included an after-tax net gain on investments
of $19.1 million and were restated to include results of Lorimar
Telepictures Corp. which Warner acquired in January.
   Warner's filmed entertainment division had operating income of
$66.1 million, nearly double the $34 million last year. Its new
movies included ``Dangerous Liaisons'' and ``The Accidental
Tourist.''
   Its recorded music and music publishing division had operating
income of $115.6 million, up 64 percent from $70.5 million a year
earlier.
   Releases by Madonna, Debbie Gibson, Roy Orbison and Guns N'
Roses were major contributors domestically, the company said, while
releases by Tracy Chapman, Fleetwood Mac and The Traveling Wilburys
sold well internationally.
   Warner said its cable and broadcasting segment earned a record
$15.2 million, up from $13.3 million a year ago.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
