<DOCNO> AP890419-0277 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-89 2102EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Earns-Kroger     04-19 0272</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Kroger,0283</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reports $19 Million Loss in 1st Qtr</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Kroger Co. said Wednesday it lost $19
million in the first quarter due to increased interest expense and
a corporate restructuring.
   The Cincinnati-based grocery chain's first-quarter results
compared with an after-tax profit of $40.3 million, or 48 cents a
share, in the first quarter of 1988.
   Kroger said it recorded the first-quarter loss despite strong
sales during the period. Revenue totaled $4.5 billion, up from $4.3
billion in the comparable 1988 quarter.
   Kroger launched a $4.6 billion restructuring last fall to fend
off takeover threats from two interested parties. The restructuring
has included sales of stores and food processing plants and the
layoff of 300 headquarters employees.
   Kroger officials said operating cash flow from units not being
sold by the company totaled $192.4 million for the quarter, up 27.3
percent from $151.2 million in the year-ago first quarter.
   Lyle Everingham, Kroger's chairman and chief executive officer,
said the company helped its first-quarter results with aggressive
marketing programs and by holding down operating costs.
   Kroger announced that a $250 million divestiture loan it took
out as part of its restructuring will be substantially repaid
within 45 days upon completion of the previously announced sale of
Kroger's Price Savers wholesale stores unit.
   The company also said it has hired Bankers Trust Co. to serve as
agent in arranging long-term financing of Kroger's real estate
holdings. Proceeds from those transactions are projected to exceed
$500 million, which Kroger said it will use to further reduce a
$2.7 billion loan. That loan has already been reduced to $2.4
billion, Kroger officials said.
</TEXT>
