<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-89 2109EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Rockwell     04-19 0240</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Rockwell,0247</SECOND>
<HEAD>Profit Rises 5 Pct in 2nd-Qtr on Sale of Subsidiary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EL SEGUNDO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rockwell International Corp. said
Wednesday its profit rose 5 percent in its latest quarter, largely
because of a one-time gain on the sale of a subsidiary.
   The aerospace company said that sales declines due to the end of
production of the B-1B bomber were offset by higher revenue on
space shuttle, space station and ``star wars'' programs, as well as
gains in the company's electronics and automotive divisions.
   Rockwell earned $270.7 million, or $1.05 a share, in its second
quarter, up from $218.4 million, or 81 cents a share, in the second
quarter of 1988. Sales for the quarter ended March 31 were $3.16
billion, up from $3.04 billion a year earlier.
   Second-quarter results were boosted by a one-time gain of $100
million, after taxes, on the sale of Rockwell's measurement and
flow division, which makes meters and valves, to BTR Dunlop Inc.,
the U.S. subsidiary of BTR PLC, the British maker of sports and
industrial products. In the comparable quarter in 1988, earnings
were increased by a one-time tax adjustment of $50 million.
   In the first half of its fiscal year, Rockwell recorded a profit
of $430.7 million, or $1.67 a share, up from $411.3 million, or
$1.52 a share, in the first half of 1988. Sales in the firsdt half
were $6.03 billion, up from $5.72 billion a year earlier.
</TEXT>
