<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-89 2110EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Earns-Wheeling-Pitt     04-19 0230</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Wheeling-Pitt,0241</SECOND>
<HEAD>Costs Deflate Profits, Sales Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wheeling-Pittsburgh Steel Corp. said Wednesday
higher production led to a 1.7 percent decline in its first-quarter
profit despite a 9.3 percent rise in sales.
   The steelmaker said it earned $45.8 million, or $8.49 per share,
in the latest three months compared with $46.6 million, or $8.68
per share, a year earlier.
   Quarterly sales rose to $287.5 million from $263 million in the
same period in 1988.
   The company, based in Wheeling, W.Va., said shipments increased
to 581,600 tons from 548,100 tons a year earlier.
   A 14.4 percent increase in operating costs reflected additional
shipping activity, blast furnace maintenance and purchases of
semi-finished steel and raw materials, the company said.
   Raw steel production declined 2.5 percent.
   Because it has been operating under Chapter 11 of the bankruptcy
laws since April 16, 1985, Wheeling-Pittsburgh is not paying
interest on most of its debt or bearing the full burden of its
pension plans. It is also benefiting from interest income on cash
that may be distributed to creditors in its bankruptcy
reorganization.
   Wheeling-Pittsburgh made $11.1 million in the first quarter and
$4.5 million a year earlier on its cash balance.
   Had the company been paying interest on its debt, its quarterly
interest costs would have been higher by at least $13.5 million
this year and $12.9 million in 1988, the company said.
</TEXT>
