<FIRST>r f AM-Earns-PhilipMorris 1stLd-Writethru f0176ar-oldsonofBernonShankwaskilledanddidn'tcommitsuicideasclaimedbytheelderShank.DoctorIsadoreMihalakisperformedtheautopsyontheteen-ager.HesayshebelivesChristopherShankdiedasaresultofahomicide.BernonShankwasthepostmasterinLamar
04-19 0524</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Philip Morris, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0176,0540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Philip Morris, American Brands Profits Rise</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 2 grafs, ADDS x grafs to UPDATE with American Brands
results.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two diversified tobacco giants, Philip Morris
Cos. Inc. and American Brands Inc., reported higher first-quarter
profits Wednesday.
   Philip Morris said its first-quarter profit rose 17.6 percent,
boosted by the contribution from Kraft Inc., which it acquired late
last year.
   Philip Morris, the large cigarette manufacturer that has become
a major consumer products company mainly through acquisitions, said
its profit totaled $590 million, or $2.55 a share, in the quarter
ended March 31 compared to last year's originally reported figures
of $502 million, or $2.12 a share.
   The 1988 first quarter results as originally reported did not
include the effects of new accounting rules pertaining to income
taxes.
   To conform with a change in the method of accounting for income
taxes, Philip Morris restated last year's results.
   Restated, but excluding the effect of the accounting change, net
income came to $490 million, or $2.06 a share in 1988's first
quarter. Income amounted to $763 million, or $3.23 a share, in 1988
after restatement and including the effect of the accounting change.
   Revenue rose 45.1 percent to $10.77 billion in this year's first
quarter from $7.42 billion a year earlier.
   Hamish Maxwell, Philip Morris' chairman and chief executive
officer, said the volume of cigarette sales increased slightly and
the company's share of the cigarette market expanded, aided by the
introduction of the Alpine brand. Among Philip Morris' other
cigarette brands are Marlboro, Virgina Slims and Merit.
   The Kraft General Foods division of Philip Morris posted higher
operating revenue in the first quarter than the comparable combined
Kraft and General Foods results for the year earlier. Kraft became
a subsidiary of Philip Morris in December 1988 and General Foods
was acquired in November 1985.
   Higher unit sales of several prepared and packaged foods under
the Philip Morris corporate umbrella contributed to overall revenue
growth. These products included General Foods' Maxwell House coffee
and Kool-Aid powdered beverages and Kraft's Cheez Whiz, Velveeta,
and packaged dinners.
   Other Philip Morris holdings that produced revenue gains were
Oscar Mayer Foods, including the Louis Rich turkey business, and
Miller Brewing Co.
   American Brands reported a 14 percent increase in first-quarter
earnings, due largely to a strong performance from its tobacco unit.
   The Greenwich, Conn.-based company earned $172 million, or $1.80
a share, on revenue of $3.24 billion in the first quarter, compared
with a profit of $151 million, or $1.40 a share, on revenue of
$3.13 billion during the same period last year.
   William J. Alley, American Brands' chairman and chief executive
officer, attributed the record rise in per-share earnings in part
to a 17.1-million-share stock buyback, which cut the number of
outstanding shares by 11 percent.
   In addition, Alley said, the company's ``core tobacco business
continues to generate sustained profit growth, both domestically
and internationally.''
   American Brands' domestic tobacco subsidiary, American Tobacco
Co., makes Carlton, Lucky Strike, Pall Mall, Tareyton and Malibu
cigarettes.
   American Brands' other operations include life insurance,
distilled spirits, office products, hardware and home improvement
products.
</TEXT>
