<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-89 2144EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-CNW-Japonica     04-19 0517</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-CNW-Japonica,0538</SECOND>
<HEAD>Battle Between CNW Corp. and Japonica Partners Heats Up</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A long-rumored acquisition battle spilled over
Wednesday as Japonica Partners disclosed intentions to acquire CNW
Corp. in a letter that asked shareholders to replace the management
of the railroad holding company with a slate of its own.
   ``I guess you could call this hostile,'' CNW spokesman James
Foote said. ``Throughout this whole campaign, they have not made an
offer to us nor have they indicated they have financing for such a
deal.
   ``Now, they apparently want to become directors so that if they
do make an offer, they would be making it to themselves.''
   Countered Japonica spokesman Frederic Spar: ``They had better
understand that when a group of quality people make a statement as
blunt as this, it should be taken seriously.''
   In a letter to shareholders, New York-based Japonica said it is
CNW's largest shareholder, owning 8.8 percent of the Chicago
company's approximately 16.4 million outstanding shares.
   Japonica said it intends to acquire CNW at a ``substantial
premium'' over the $31-per-share offer put together by CNW
management and the investment group Gibbons, Green, van Amerongen.
That proposal fell through last May.
   The letter criticizes CNW management for refusing to give
Japonica the same consideration it gave its own bid last year.
   Spar declined to be more specific about whether Japonica's plans
for an acquisition would result from a merger or tender offer or
some other arrangement, or how much more than $31 per share would
be offered.
   As for financing, he said Japonica was ``evaluating'' several
proposals.
   CNW Corp. stock climbed 37{ cents Wednesday on the New York
Stock Exchange to close at $40.
   CNW's principal subsidiary is the Chicago and North Western
Transportation Co., which operates a nine-state, 6,000-mile freight
railroad with 8,500 employees. CNW also has real estate holdings
and operates Chicago-area commuter rail lines. It earned $81
million on revenues of $995.4 million last year.
   The Japonica letter contends CNW's board has approved excessive
compensation levels and an ``inappropriate'' golden-parachute
package for CNW's senior management in case of a takeover.
   Japonica also said it would consider selling CNW's real estate,
excess equipment and the commuter lines.
   Japonica's proposed slate includes C. Howard Hardesty, former
president and chief executive officer of Purolator Courier Corp.,
as its chairman-designate.
   In a letter to shareholders last month, CNW Chairman Robert
Schmiege urged support for the company's slate at the May 16
stockholders meeting.
   Analysts attributed a recent runup in the stock to the
escalating war of words between Japonica and CNW management.
   In a related development, CNW Corp. announced Wednesday that it
had filed an appeal in the 3rd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in
Philadelphia seeking to force Japonica Partners to disclose its
plans for CNW and the identity of its investors.
   A U.S. District Court judge in Delaware, where CNW is
incorporated, recently denied CNW's request for a preliminary
injunction to force Japonica to provide such information.
   CNW also announced that its directors approved a dividend of 10
cents a share, payable July 14.
</TEXT>
