<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-89 2147EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-AMR     04-19 0192</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-AMR,0200</SECOND>
<HEAD>AMR Quarterly Profit Up 47.7 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   AMR Corp., parent company of American
Airlines, reported Wednesday a 47.7 percent jump in first-quarter
profit, partly due to increased traffic as passengers looked for an
alternative to Eastern Airlines.
   Net earnings were $101 million, or $1.60 per share, on revenues
of $2.45 billion during the quarter. That compares with earnings of
$68.4 million, or $1.12 per share, on revenues of $1.97 billion in
the same quarter last year.
   The first-quarter 1989 earnings included a $14.1 million gain
from the sale of certain property rights, the company said.
   American's load factor at Raleigh-Durham airport in North
Carolina jumped from 63 percent in last year's first quarter to
71.2 percent this year, while in San Juan, Puerto Rico, the factor
rose from 70.3 to 81.4, AMR Chairman Robert Crandall said. Both
locations were Eastern strongholds.
   Eastern filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection March 9 after
its Machinists union members went on strike, crippling the airline.
   American's revenue passenger miles, a key industry statistic,
rose 9.7 percent in the quarter, from 14.77 million in the year-ago
period to 16.2 million.
</TEXT>
