<FIRST>r f AM-CarsonPirie-Bergner     04-19 0280</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Carson Pirie-Bergner,0291</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bergner Sweetens Deal For Department Store Chain Carson Pirie</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   P.A. Bergner &amp; Co., rebuffed last week in a
takeover bid for Carson Pirie Scott &amp; Co., sweetened the deal
Wednesday by offering $24 per share for the Chicago-based retailer.
   ``We remain convinced that a business combination involving your
department stores and those of Bergner's represents a sound
business fit,'' Alan R. Anderson, chairman of P.A. Bergner, said in
a letter to Carson Pirie.
   Carson Pirie, which owns 33 department stores in Illinois, Iowa,
Indiana and Minnesota, last week rejected a $20-per-share offer
from P.A. Bergner, a Swiss-owned department store chain with
headquarters in Milwaukee.
   Carson Pirie stock jumped by $1.62{ to close at $23.37{
Wednesday in consolidated New York Stock Exchange trading.
   ``We are prepared to pay $24 net in cash for each outstanding
share of Carson's common stock,'' Anderson wrote. ``This price
represents an extraordinary premium over the recent trading history
of Carson's common stock.''
   Anderson said the offer expires April 28.
   Carson Pirie issued a statement saying its directors ``would
review the proposal ... in due course.''
   In a letter to Carson Pirie directors, Anderson said he enclosed
a copy of a letter from Swiss Bank Corp. confirming the bank would
provide P.A. Bergner with the money necessary to acquire the
outstanding shares and to refinance Carson Pirie's debt.
   P.A. Bergner operates 31 department stores in Illinois and
Wisconsin.
   Carson Pirie lost $38.8 million in the fiscal year that ended
Jan. 31, much of it from its catalog operations. Besides department
stores, Carson Pirie owns 388 County Seat speciality stores in
Midwest and Sunbelt states and 23 Arcadia stores in Chicago.
</TEXT>
