<FIRST>r f BC-NCRShareholders     04-19 0159</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-NCR Shareholders,0165</SECOND>
<HEAD>NCR Shareholders Reject South African Pullout</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DAYTON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NCR Corp. shareholders Wednesday rejected a
proposal to entirely withdraw the company's operations from South
Africa.
   NCR's board of directors had urged shareholders to vote against
the proposal at Wednesday's annual meeting. The company announced
April 4 that it plans to sell its South African subsidiary and
market its products through a distributor in that nation.
   Charles Russ III, NCR's vice president and secretary, wrote
shareholders a letter saying that if the planned South African
transaction cannot be completed, there is no assurance that the
board could enter into another agreement that would similarly serve
shareholder interests.
   Former Chairman William S. Anderson retired from the board
following Wednesday's meeting. Anderson, who reached the company's
mandatory retirement age of 70, had served on the board since his
appointment as NCR's president in 1972.
   The Dayton-based company makes and sells business information
processing systems for worldwide markets.
</TEXT>
