<FIRST>r f BC-Motorola-Patents 1stLd-Writethru   04-19 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Motorola-Patents, 1st Ld-Writethru,f0288,0361</SECOND>
<HEAD>Motorola Seeks Halt Of Phone Sales In Patent Dispute</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 8th graf pvs, `Named as ...,' to UPDATE
with Tandy comment and attempt to reach Nokia; Picks up last graf pvs.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SCHAUMBURG, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Motorola Inc., citing patent violations,
has filed complaints with the U.S. International Trade Commission
and in federal court to stop sales of some portable and mobile
cellular telephones, the company said Wednesday.
   ``We expect our competition to respect Motorola's hard-won
patent position,'' said Motorola Vice President Robert N.
Weisshappel.
   He said talks with Nokia Corp. of Finland and Tandy Mobira
Communications Corp. of Korea had been fruitless.
   The infringements allow competitors to sell products at unfairly
low prices, resulting in substantial injury to Motorola and the
U.S. cellular telephone industry, Motorola said.
   Motorola seeks permanent relief from the ITC in Washington, as
well as a temporary exclusion order and a temporary
cease-and-desist order to halt imports of cellular telephones,
primarily from Korea, that it says infringe upon seven of its
patents.
   In the court action, filed in U.S. District Court in Chicago,
Motorola seeks a permanent injunction and unspecified monetary
damages, citing infringement on nine patents.
   Named in the ITC action are Nokia Corp. of Helsinki, Finland;
Nokia-Mobira Oy of Salo, Finland; Nokia Inc. of Basking Ridge,
N.J.; Nokia-Mobira Inc. of Largo, Fla.; Tandy Mobira Communications
Corp. of Korea; Tandy Corp. of Fort Worth, Texas; and A&amp;A
International of Fort Worth, Texas.
   Named as defendants in the court action are Nokia Corp.,
Nokia-Mobira Inc., Tandy Mobira Communications Corp. and Tandy Corp.
   ``We haven't seen the exact complaints,'' Tandy spokesman Ed
Juge said. ``We've been talking to them through legal counsel for
several months. Without knowing exactly what's involved, it's
impossible to give relevant comment.''
   A phone call placed to Nokia's New Jersey operation after office
hours Wednesday went unanswered.
   Motorola is one of the world's leading manufacturers of
electronics equipment, systems and components for world markets.
Its products include two-way radios, pagers, cellular telephone
systems, defense and aerospace electronics, and information
processing and handling equipment.
</TEXT>
